        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>1</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>REPORT BY THE CHAIRPERSON OF THE TRADE NEGOTIATIONS COMMITTEE AND REPORT BY THE DIRECTOR-GENERAL</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 1.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>In taking up the first item "Report by the Chairperson of the Trade Negotiations Committee and Report by the Director-General", the Chairperson referred to the recent formal meeting of the Trade Negotiations Committee and an Informal Heads of Delegation meeting on Tuesday, 12 December. Given the extensive discussions on Tuesday, she said that she did not expect a discussion under this item. She invited the Director-General, as Chairperson of the Trade Negotiations Committee, to say a few words.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>1.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The Director-General and Chairperson of the Trade Negotiations Committee delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 1.3-->
                    <paragraph id="1.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I do not wish to say anything because we just had the TNC. The only reason I asked for the floor is to celebrate again those Members who recently ratified the Fishery Subsidies Agreement. Yesterday, we heard from the UK that they not only ratified but contributed an unexpected GBP 1,000,000 to the Fishery Subsidies Fund, which is fantastic. In addition, Chile ratified, Gambia ratified. Now we just got news that Barbados is on the verge of ratifying. This was news this morning from the Ambassador who stayed up until 2 a.m. to try to push and give us news. I want to recognize that effort and thank them most sincerely and celebrate them. I am looking for more, especially over the holiday. When we come back, I expect a lot of good news.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 1.4-->
                    <paragraph id="1.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council took note of the statement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
            </statements>
        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>2</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>THIRTEENTH SESSION OF THE MINISTERIAL CONFERENCE</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 2.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that given the long agenda and the fact that she had reported to the formal TNC and the informal HODs meetings on 12 December on the work underway on a possible MC13 outcome document, she would not repeat her report at this meeting but would simply refer to the report issued in JOB/TNC/122. She invited delegations to use the end-of-year break to also further reflect on this work, so as to be able to resume this process in the New Year in a solution-oriented and pragmatic manner. She counted on everyone's cooperation.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 2.2-->
                <p>
                    <t>Before taking up the administrative matters under this item, she thanked the United Arab Emirates for organizing the Mini-Ministerial on 11 December. She recognized the presence of H.E. Dr Thani bin Ahmed Al Zeyoudi, Minister of State for Foreign Trade of the United Arab Emirates, Chairperson of the Thirteenth Ministerial Conference, and invited him to address the General Council.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>2.3</statement_number>
                    <statement>H.E. Dr Thani bin Ahmed Al Zeyoudi, Minister of State for Foreign Trade of the United Arab Emirates, Chairperson of the Thirteenth Ministerial Conference, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.4-->
                    <paragraph id="2.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is really a pleasure to be here with you all and to meet you again at this meeting. As you all know, the past work and the amount of effort that has been done by all of you are great toward the success of the outcomes that are going to come out from the WTO and especially from MC13. We are now less than 10 weeks away from MC13, including the break that we are going to have soon, and we urge everyone to continue their efforts to ensure that we are ready for MC13 at the end of February in Abu Dhabi.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.5-->
                    <paragraph id="2.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>For the last few months and after I assumed my role as the Chairperson of MC13, we have been in direct contact with many of your Ministers and official delegations to ensure that we start the preparation for MC13. The feedback is very positive. The promises and the encouragement that we have been receiving from the officials are paving the way towards an outcome that we are going to be all proud of.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.6-->
                    <paragraph id="2.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We also tried to host a few Mini-Ministerials. The first was held on 28 November, specifically on agriculture, and the second was on 11 December in close coordination with the Secretariat and H.E. Dr. Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala and with the Ministers representatives of different groups and the attendance of the rest of the Members listening to the discussions. Our observations are very simple. First of all, most of the Ministers and representatives were reading from their remarks and that is going to stick to the extreme positions that we have been hearing for quite some time. Second, what we have been seeing from those engagements is that everyone is sticking to the process – not the substantial matter and content. I would highly urge everyone to start shifting gears towards the technicalities and the content itself if we really want to have an outcome that will serve the global community.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.7-->
                    <paragraph id="2.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Earlier today, in Dubai, we concluded the COP28 with a huge success – the success from the representatives of your nations. They achieved an outcome that has been negotiated for the last two weeks and has reflected the interests of everyone on a very complex topic that faces humanity nowadays. Whatever we are facing now, it is not as complex as climate change, and I think we can do it together.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.8-->
                    <paragraph id="2.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Another point that I want to highlight is that in the last few months I have been in direct contact and communication with many in the private sector, as part of my job as Minister of State for Foreign Trade and as Minister in charge of Investment before - and the only comments that I keep hearing are – we do not know what the Ministerial meetings are doing. They are saying that they are not even considered in the discussions and outcomes. As governments, we think that we are doing the right thing for the community, the businesses and the private sector. So, we should engage them and hear their views to ensure that we reflect on the growth of global trade and the global businesses we would like to see.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.9-->
                    <paragraph id="2.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>So, as we are heading to MC13, I would like to lay out some of the plan for the upcoming few weeks. If there is any need for another Mini-Ministerial, we would host it, but there is no plan for now to host any. The Ministerial meeting will start on 26 February and will end on 29 February. We are not planning to have a Senior Officials meeting for now. We are discussing it with both the Chairperson of the General Council and the Director-General of the WTO, but we are still assessing the best modalities and way forward to ensure that we bring some of the technical discussions forward.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.10-->
                    <paragraph id="2.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The team in the other room is briefing the other representatives of your teams on the logistical details. If there is anything which we can do as a host nation, we will be more than happy to do it. What we promise you is that we are going to be very transparent and inclusive and ensure that the whole meeting is bringing together everyone involved. So, we are looking forward to working with you all and hosting you all in Abu Dhabi.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.11-->
                    <paragraph id="2.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson thanked H.E. Dr. Thani bin Ahmed Al Zeyoudi for his address to the Council and said she looked forward to working with him intensively in the weeks ahead.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>2.12</statement_number>
                    <statement>The Director-General delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.13-->
                    <paragraph id="2.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Let me join the General Council Chairperson in welcoming H.E. Dr. Thani bin Ahmed Al Zeyoudi, Minister of State for Foreign Trade of the United Arab Emirates and Chairperson of the Thirteenth WTO Ministerial Conference. I want you all to know that when we were in the UAE for COP28, he and Ambassador Abdelsalam Mohamed Al Ali and their team went out of their way to make sure we had a real success. It was not easy. It was a huge place with lots going on and I must say that the UAE team was sterling. So that really made us feel good and gives us a lot of hope for how I hope we will operate once we have MC13 on the ground. So, I want to say heartfelt thank you to the Minister, the Ambassador and the entire team of the UAE.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.14-->
                    <paragraph id="2.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The GC Chairperson and I have started to work closely with you, and you have also started to reach out and I hope you will be able to talk to as many of the Ambassadors as possible – while keeping in close contact with the General Council Chairperson and I, as we move towards this preparation and, of course, with the Secretariat.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.15-->
                    <paragraph id="2.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Delegations may recall that, at our previous Ministerial Conference (MC12), we circulated the modalities of that Conference three weeks before Ministers arrived. The modalities document contained the programme and detailed explanations on how the meetings would be conducted.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.16-->
                    <paragraph id="2.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As delegations know well, the modalities of a Ministerial Conference are shaped by the membership, in particular, the state of play of work in negotiating groups and in Councils and Committees. Therefore, clarity on the sessions that we will have and the structure of the conference itself will depend on the clarity we get from the negotiations and discussions amongst Members in the lead up to MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.17-->
                    <paragraph id="2.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As I urged at the TNC yesterday, let me reiterate my call to all Members to redouble efforts in bridging and closing as many gaps as possible here in Geneva to avoid a situation where Ministers have to engage in technical negotiations. We just had the same call from H.E. Minister Al Zeyoudi urging us to work here in Geneva and all of you, Excellencies, have said that you want to do that. Ambassadors and technical experts have stressed that delivering much of the result and leaving as few square brackets as possible is within your reach. So, I really urge you to do it and until we see what we can do, we will be watching to see how we can shape those modalities.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.18-->
                    <paragraph id="2.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With this in mind, the MC13 Chairperson, the General Council Chairperson and I will continue to work together to ensure that we circulate the MC13 modalities in early February, which will provide better clarity for planning and organization as we draw closer to the Conference. This will address the questions delegations have posed about Senior Officials' engagement, duration of the Conference and what will be expected of Ministers each day. Circulation of the modalities in early February should provide delegations with enough time to brief capital while allowing the ongoing processes to significantly progress.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.19-->
                    <paragraph id="2.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson noted that the Rules of Procedure (Rule 12) for the Ministerial Conference established that "During the course of each regular session a Chairperson and three Vice-Chairpersons shall be elected from among the Members. They shall hold office from the end of that session until the end of the next regular session." She recalled that in July, the General Council had elected the MC13 Chairperson. Regarding the three Vice-Chairpersons, since the Chairperson would come from the Asian region, and in line with customary practice, she had invited the representatives of the other three broad groupings – i.e., Africa; Latin America and the Caribbean (GRULAC); and developed countries – to consult with their constituencies in order to submit the names for the proposed MC13 Vice Chairpersons.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.20-->
                    <paragraph id="2.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Consultations had been conducted by the group coordinators, and further to this process, the Chairperson had sent a communication on 30 November informing all Members of the three proposed names for the appointment of the MC13 Vice-Chairpersons. In the communication, she had also proposed that, if no objections were received, the General Council would elect the proposed Vice-Chairpersons at the present meeting. Following the communication, she had been informed that H.E. Mr. Federico Alfaro Boyd of Panama was no longer in office. Since then, GRULAC had been consulting and she had received a communication nominating H.E. Jorge Rivera Staff, Minister of Trade and Industry of the Republic of Panama, as proposed MC13 Vice-Chairperson. Since there had been no objections with regard to the proposed nominations communicated on 30 November, which had already included Panama, she believed that the General Council was in a position to elect H.E. Mr. Luc Magloire Mbarga Atangana (Cameroon); Hon. Mr. Todd McClay (New Zealand); and H.E. Jorge Rivera Staff (Panama) as MC13 Vice-Chairpersons.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.21-->
                    <paragraph id="2.21">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council so agreed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.22-->
                    <paragraph id="2.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In moving to the next sub-item "Request for Observer Status by Palestine", the Chairperson drew the General Council's attention to the request for Observer status at MC13 by Palestine, circulated in WT/L/1171. In accordance with customary practice, she had undertaken consultations, and it was her understanding that Members might be in a position to take action concerning this request. Therefore, she proposed that the General Council agree to grant Palestine Observer Status at MC13 on an ad hoc basis.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 2.23-->
                    <paragraph id="2.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council so agreed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
            </statements>
        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>3</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>FOLLOW-UP TO OUTCOMES OF MINISTERIAL CONFERENCES</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 3.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson noted that the follow-up to MC12 was contained in sub-items 3.A.(i)-(iv) while sub-item 3.B. referred to follow-up to previous Ministerial Conferences. She therefore proposed to first take up the matters listed under sub-item 3.A.(i) – (iii) and open the floor once. Thereafter, she would take up all matters under sub-item 3.A.(iv) and open the floor. Finally, she would take up sub-item 3.B. and open the floor.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The Chairperson delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.3-->
                    <paragraph id="3.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Since the beginning of the year, work has intensified in fulfilling Ministers' commitment at MC12 to work towards necessary reform of the WTO in all its functions. During this period, my predecessor and I have updated Members on WTO reform work at every regular meeting of the General Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.4-->
                    <paragraph id="3.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Colleagues, in 2023, Members remained actively engaged in the reform work. A plethora of proposals was tabled, and many innovative ideas were shared that enabled WTO reform work to advance. I commend all of you for your hard work in this regard.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.5-->
                    <paragraph id="3.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This year, we had informal meetings on WTO reform focused on development in February, deliberative function and institutional matters in June, and trade and industrial policy in September. We likewise had deliberations on trade and environmental sustainability at the Senior Officials' Meeting in October.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.6-->
                    <paragraph id="3.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Following reform discussions on institutional matters, throughout the year, Members have emphasized the need to ensure meaningful Ministerial engagement during Ministerial Conferences. With MC13 fast approaching, there was demand from Members for the General Council Chairperson to establish a roadmap to guide the work in the lead up to MC13. In this regard, you may recall that I circulated in July a road map to MC13, which I further fleshed out following my consultations with Members in November.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.7-->
                    <paragraph id="3.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Members continue to attach high priority to dispute settlement reform. You may recall that, in February 2023, Mr. Marco Molina of Guatemala started convening informal meetings on DS Reform with the objective of having substance-based discussions to find practical solutions to the concerns identified by Members. These discussions have intensified and, as I understand from the DSB Chairperson – Ambassador Ølberg, an agenda item dedicated to this matter will again be taken up at the DSB meeting on Monday, 18 December.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.8-->
                    <paragraph id="3.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Reform-by-Doing work has also progressed this year. Notably, the Goods Council has adopted a report in G/L/1523 capturing 127 reforms that have been implemented to improve the functioning of the Goods Council and its 14 subsidiary bodies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.9-->
                    <paragraph id="3.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>These include significant changes to assist delegates, measures to improve the planning and organization of meetings, the procedures for the conduct of formal and informal meetings and the introduction of digital tools to improve productivity and exchange of information.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.10-->
                    <paragraph id="3.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I also note that important efforts have been undertaken in other WTO Councils and Committees. Following Members' request, the General Council continues to monitor progress and coordinate with WTO Bodies as "reform-by-doing" work advances. In this regard, in addition to the reports by respective Chairpersons of WTO Bodies, I asked the Secretariat to continue updating the report in JOB/GC/359 at every regular session of the General Council at least until MC13. An update of the report was circulated prior to the Senior Officials' meeting, and the most recent revision was circulated as JOB/GC/359/Rev.2 on 11 December.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.11-->
                    <paragraph id="3.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As we inch closer to MC13, WTO reform has become an important element of our preparations to ensure a successful Ministerial Conference in Abu Dhabi. In this regard, as you have heard from my report on Tuesday at the TNC, Members are currently working on a section on WTO reform for a possible MC13 outcome document.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.12-->
                    <paragraph id="3.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This comprises (i) a reaffirmation of Ministers' WTO reform commitment at MC12, (ii) a general acknowledgement of the progress of WTO reform work since Ministers last met, (iii) welcoming and taking note of reform-by-doing efforts, a paragraph on DS reform – which would depend on the ongoing process, (iv) acknowledging the reform retreats, and (v) recognizing the need for all Members to deepen dialogue in a more focused manner to improve understanding on issues.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.13-->
                    <paragraph id="3.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I recognize that, at MC13, the General Council and its subsidiary bodies are tasked to report on progress on WTO reform work. Given the numerous discussions and the amount of work we have accomplished thus far, I encourage all Members to continue participating in WTO reform work in this spirit. Let us together seize available opportunities, address the challenges faced by the WTO, and ensure the Organization's proper functioning – through WTO Reform.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.14-->
                    <paragraph id="3.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson noted that pursuant to paragraph 24 of the Ministerial Declaration on the WTO Response to the COVID-19 Pandemic and Preparedness for Future Pandemics (WT/L/1142), "A stocktaking exercise will be taken of the work by WTO bodies under this declaration yearly at the General Council until the end of 2024, based on the reports of those relevant bodies." She recalled that this annual stocktaking exercise had been undertaken at the July General Council meeting.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.15-->
                    <paragraph id="3.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>She said that work in this area had continued, as had been reported to her in the meeting with Chairpersons of regular WTO bodies earlier in the week. The Goods and Services Councils had adopted reports contained in G/L/1521 and S/C/66. The TRIPS Council had continued its discussions under an agenda item named "IP and COVID-19". Also under this item, Members had continued their practice of sharing experiences on domestic COVID-related IP measures taken during the pandemic on the basis of a Secretariat compilation of such measures that was updated and maintained on the WTO website.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.16-->
                    <paragraph id="3.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In moving to sub-item (iii) "Paragraph 8 of the Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement – Duration of Extended Deadline", the Chairperson noted that at MC12, Ministers had decided that "No later than six months from the date of this Decision, Members will decide on its extension to cover the production and supply of COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics." She then recalled that at the March General Council meeting, a common understanding had emerged - namely: the issue of the duration of the deadline will remain on the General Council agenda; that Members will provide an update on where they stand on their internal processes; and that substantive discussions will continue in the TRIPS Council. It was her understanding that Members had continued their discussions on the substance of paragraph 8 of the TRIPS Decision in the TRIPS Council, and that Ambassador Pimchanok Pitfield (Thailand), Chairperson of the Council for TRIPS, would provide an update on these discussions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.17</statement_number>
                    <statement>Ambassador Pimchanok Pitfield (Thailand), Chairperson of the Council for TRIPS, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.18-->
                    <paragraph id="3.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to take this opportunity, as Chair of the Council for TRIPS, to provide a brief status report under my own responsibility on the state of play of discussions under paragraph 8 of the MC12 Decision – on whether to extend the scope of the Decision to COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.19-->
                    <paragraph id="3.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Since July, discussions on paragraph 8 of the TRIPS Decision have continued at an informal Council meeting on 9 October, at the formal Council meeting on 30-31 October, at informal consultations I held on 6-9 November, and again at an informal Council meeting on 29 November 2023. To further broaden the basis for fact- and evidence-based discussions, the Council also held a "Thematic Session for External Stakeholder Input" on 28 September 2023, where more than 20 representatives from data analysts, international organizations, civil society, business and academia shared facts, evidence and experiences relevant to the Council's discussions on this issue. The interventions at this thematic session reflected a broad spectrum of views and provided additional detail and analysis on certain elements of this long-running debate. My report on the thematic session has been circulated in document IP/C/W/706. WTO Members were also briefed on the "Report on COVID-19 therapeutics and diagnostics and TRIPS flexibilities" by the US International Trade Commission on 19 October 2023.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.20-->
                    <paragraph id="3.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Despite this continued and focused engagement on this issue there is currently no consensus among Members on whether to extend the Decision to COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics. In my meetings and consultations, Members have largely reiterated their known and diverging positions. A number of Members consider extension long overdue, and are calling for a binary "yes-or-no decision" on this question at this General Council meeting based on the proposed decision text in document IP/C/W/694/Rev.1. Other Members consider that there is no basis for an extension as they see no evidence of IP-related barriers to such products and consider that the pandemic is largely over. Some have suggested that, as consensus on extension is unlikely, Members should agree on a forward-looking work programme on pandemic preparedness so as to continue the discussion on IP in a broader WTO context. In light of these diverging views and suggestions, I stand ready to continue facilitating Members' engagement on this question as appropriate. This concludes my status report on the work under paragraph 8.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.21-->
                    <paragraph id="3.21">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>While I have the floor, let me also briefly report on the TRIPS Council's discussions on TRIPS non-violation and situation complaints.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.22-->
                    <paragraph id="3.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As you know, the MC12 Decision on this issue instructs the Council for TRIPS to continue its examination of the scope and modalities for such complaints under the TRIPS Agreement, and to make recommendations to MC13. Members agreed that, in the meantime, such complaints would not be initiated under the TRIPS Agreement. Despite my encouragement in the course of my consultations on this issue in November, and the continued discussion at the informal Council meeting in November, a number of Members are not ready to agree on a recommendation on TRIPS non-violation complaints at this stage. On 29 November, I circulated a draft decision as a basis for consideration for Members, in the event that they might wish to recommend to the Ministerial Conference to once again extend the moratorium on such complaints under the TRIPS Agreement. This draft has been circulated in JOB/IP/72 and is closely based on the text of previous such decisions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.23-->
                    <paragraph id="3.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Both these items – paragraph 8 of the TRIPS Decision and non-violation complaints – remain open on the TRIPS Council's agenda, so that the Council meeting can be resumed if Members are ready to agree on a conclusion to these issues.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.24-->
                    <paragraph id="3.24">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson invited the delegation of South Africa to introduce the item and communication contained in WT/GC/W/913 – IP/C/W/694/Rev.1.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.25</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of South Africa, on behalf of the co-sponsors of IP/C/W/669/Rev.1, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.26-->
                    <paragraph id="3.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The WTO has exhibited glaring shortcomings in its inability to take timely, adequate measures to address the needs of developing countries. The arduous one-and-a-half years it took for the WTO to arrive at a narrowly focused decision solely on vaccines is emblematic of its failure. The final Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement, adopted on 17 June 2022, falls short of the comprehensive TRIPS waiver proposal championed by 65 developing country Members and supported globally by health experts and members of the public.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.27-->
                    <paragraph id="3.27">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Paragraph 8 of the Decision states, "No later than six months […] Members will decide on its extension to cover the production and supply of COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics". This paragraph was a major concession by cosponsors who, in good faith, agreed to allow Members the six months they requested to conduct internal consultations. One and a half years later, there is still no decision. The tactics employed by some Members to continually delay the adoption of a decision on the extension are unacceptable. At the TNC on Tuesday, one Ambassador aptly referred to a trust deficit prevailing in the WTO. Certainly, reneging on the commitment in paragraph 8 has damaged trust. The time for delays is over – decisive action is required.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.28-->
                    <paragraph id="3.28">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The emergence of COVID-19 variants, characterized by an increasing number of mutations, has been confirmed by scientists. The heightened risk is evident in the appearance of new variants, surges in infections, and declining immunity. The challenge of high prices and limited access persists in many developing countries. Despite representing only 16 per cent of the global population, high-income countries acquired more than 70 per cent of therapeutic supplies. It is reported that the number of people with high-risk COVID-19 infections in developing countries exceeded the procured supply of paxlovid recommended by the WHO by at least eight million courses in 2022. This shortfall left unmet at least 90 per cent of the health need for the WHO-preferred treatment in developing countries. Cosponsors, WHO, and other experts have presented evidence on the insufficiency of initiatives such as voluntary licenses, tier-pricing and access schemes of international organizations in facilitating prompt access to COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics in developing countries. Ample facts and evidence have been conveyed to Members questioning the need to extend the waiver decision to therapeutics.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.29-->
                    <paragraph id="3.29">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Allowing the extension of this waiver will lessen the burden of pandemics on health systems, and during pandemics on health and thus allowing to focus on economic development. Further, allowing the extension of this waiver to diagnostics and therapeutics would give us a fighting chance when there is a surge of variants in future. And this would cement the WTO's relevance in responding to the effects of the pandemic.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.30-->
                    <paragraph id="3.30">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>A pivotal aspect of the 17 June Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement is the waiver of Article 31(f). Removing this legal hurdle for COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics holds the potential to achieve economies of scale, reduce prices and supply developing countries lacking sufficient manufacturing capacity. Other aspects of the Decision that reaffirm existing flexibilities are equally important.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.31-->
                    <paragraph id="3.31">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Given this background and paragraph 8 of the Ministerial Decision, the co-sponsors call on the General Council to immediately extend the 17 June TRIPS Decision adopted by the Ministers by consensus after long protracted negotiations, mutatis mutandis, to therapeutics and diagnostics as proposed in document WT/GC/W/913. This extension presents WTO Members with a timely opportunity to demonstrate their ability to respond swiftly to the ongoing global public health challenge marked by inequitable access.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.32-->
                    <paragraph id="3.32">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Failure to adopt this Decision at the General Council would force Members to avoid multilateral approaches in favour of unilateral measures. Such an unfortunate outcome would fragment the IP system. It would also underscore the WTO's emphatic incapacity to deliver multilateral outcomes of interest to developing countries. Such a message would not bode well for confidence building towards MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.33-->
                    <paragraph id="3.33">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Post-script, failure to extend the decision on TRIPS is 'not only a failure of reason, but also a moral failure, and an unnecessary stain on the history of this Organization'.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.34-->
                    <paragraph id="3.34">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson added an additional point from her preparatory meeting with the Chairpersons of regular bodies. On the food security work programme, the discussions in the Committee on Agriculture had taken place within the overall thematic parameters approved by the Committee in November2022 in a dedicated Working Group. The Working Group had been given one year (i.e., until the end of November 2023) to conclude the work. Since its establishment, the Working Group had engaged in substantive discussions, covering various themes such as border measures, encompassing both import and export restrictions, financing matters, production resilience, and fostering collaboration with international organizations.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.35-->
                    <paragraph id="3.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Approaching its conclusion in November, the Working Group had deliberated on a draft revised report and recommendations prepared by the coordinator, contained in RD/AG/120/Rev.2. There had been a broad convergence in the Working Group to accept the report as a compromise and transmit it to the Committee for approval. However, one Member had maintained some concerns, deeming the report lacking ambition in certain respects. Similarly, other Members had resisted substantive changes to the report, citing reasons of overall balance contained in the current draft.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.36-->
                    <paragraph id="3.36">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Considering the dynamics in Members' positions, both at the last meeting of the Working Group on 20 November and the formal meeting of the Committee on 27-29 November, the Chairperson had informed the Committee of his readiness to convene a special meeting for finalizing the report and recommendations of the work programme if consensus were to emerge in the coming days. There had been no consensus for the further continuation of the Working Group beyond end of November 2023.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.37</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nigeria delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.38-->
                    <paragraph id="3.38">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the outset we wish to associate ourselves with the statement delivered on behalf of the 65 cosponsors of IP/C/W/669/Rev.1. Paragraph 8 of the MC12 Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement regarding the extension of the decision to cover the production and supply of COVID-19 therapeutics and diagnostics is unambiguous. Regrettably, we have not been able to deliver on this issue that would better equip developing countries to respond to current and future pandemics. While non-proponents continue to maintain that voluntary licenses are sufficient to address developing countries concerns, we are of the view that though voluntary licenses are pertinent and useful public health tools, they are not adequate in addressing all issues of public health, during global health emergencies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.39-->
                    <paragraph id="3.39">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The African Group, at the TRIPS Council, has cited enough examples that highlight the several issues with the voluntary license mechanism including that the actual utility of some of the licenses is a concern for many African countries. Therefore, with respect to the draft General Council Decision regarding the issue of extension of paragraph 8 of the MC12 Decision on the TRIPS Agreement, we are of the view that this General Council should finalize this issue, and we call on Members to decide on the extension of paragraph 8 of the MC12 decision to therapeutics and diagnostics.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.40</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Djibouti, on behalf of the LDC Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.41-->
                    <paragraph id="3.41">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With regard to item 3.A(i), the LDC Group is on record supporting improvements to the functioning of the WTO bodies, particularly those that had a genesis in the LDC Group submission in April 2022. Those include use of annotated agendas, expediting the production of minutes, mechanisms to avoid overlapping of key meetings, summary notes the same day of meetings, and translation provided for all informal meetings.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.42-->
                    <paragraph id="3.42">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>To complement the work done, we suggest that some improvements in the process of the reform could be considered. For example, future proposals requiring adoption and of a crosscutting nature with impact on LDC participation in WTO bodies, should be sent to the General Council for discussion and decision. LDCs and small delegations are all at the General Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.43-->
                    <paragraph id="3.43">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Some recent adoptions, for example the change of the 10-days rule to 15 days, (in the CTG, CMA, CTS), some of our Members thought that the change meant more time to prepare. We did not reverse these adoptions not to stand in the way and change anything. However, we request the General Council to agree that the change in those bodies can be implemented on a trial basis. This is similar to what was already agreed in some of the bodies where it was agreed to apply the e-agenda on a trial basis – a good idea that came from the reform by doing process. We can also test the impact on the LDC Group and LDCs. Finally, while useful in some cases, the "written procedure" and circulating proposals for adoption during summer recess should be avoided. We reiterate our applause to the Secretariat, and the Chairpersons for all of the great work done on several areas of reform of the functioning of the various committees and councils.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.44-->
                    <paragraph id="3.44">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With regard to item 3.A(ii), the LDC Group thanks you for your statement on paragraph 24 of the Ministerial Declaration on the WTO Response to the COVID-19 Pandemic and Preparedness for Future Pandemics. We have some comments on the report contained in document G/L/1521 on the WTO response to the COVID-19 pandemic and preparedness for future pandemics. We note that in addition to the Council for Trade in Goods, almost all of its 14 subsidiary bodies have undertaken at least one activity to implement paragraph 24 of said Declaration. The work carried out has taught us several lessons relating to what each actor should adopt, at the national and/or international level, in times of crisis. With this in mind, we welcome the concrete results that the Committee on Market Access (CMA) has agreed. We urge other bodies to follow the example of the Market Access Committee in order to also achieve concrete results in their respective areas. Furthermore, we want to reiterate our call to net food exporting Members to refrain from applying export restrictions to LDCs and NFIDCs importing critical products for their domestic health and protection needs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.45-->
                    <paragraph id="3.45">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We have noted the importance of digitalization for the global economy during the COVID-19 pandemic. We reiterate that the WTO has an important role to play in working with relevant international organizations to help LDCs bridge the digital divide in order to strengthen the resilience of their economies and initiate their structural transformation. Finally, as part of the update of the WTO website to reflect actions taken in the context of the implementation of paragraph 24 of the Ministerial Declaration on the WTO response to the COVID-19 pandemic and preparedness for future pandemics, we urge the WTO Secretariat to add at least one link relating to the impact of this pandemic in LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.46-->
                    <paragraph id="3.46">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On item 3.A(iii), the LDC Group thanks South Africa for presenting the document. The LDC Group is a co-sponsor of the initiative leading to the Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement Waiver on COVID-19 Vaccine during MC12. Our Group calls on Members to continue to engage constructively in order to find consensus by the MC13 to include therapeutic and diagnostic products in said Ministerial Decision. We must learn from our failures, and the same mistakes and procrastination should not be repeated during a pandemic in future. For any global crisis, the LDCs are the worst victims. In this regard, the LDC Group requests to make a favourable decision to extend the MC12 decision on the TRIPS Waiver to cover therapeutics and diagnostics.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.47</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Guyana, on behalf of CARICOM, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.48-->
                    <paragraph id="3.48">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We note the update on the detailed overview of the work carried out by councils, committees and negotiating bodies with respect to reform by doing. Paragraph 3 of the MC12 Outcome Document commits us to work towards necessary reform of the WTO in a manner which is Member-driven, open, transparent and inclusive. While we especially commend the work being carried out by the Council for Trade in Goods and its subsidiary bodies, we note that many developing Members with capacity constrained delegations, including CARICOM Members, have not been able to actively participate in much of this reform work. We view many of the improvements being introduced to be useful. However, we need to strike the right balance in terms of ensuring that there is a sufficient level of inclusivity in this work. We also have to ensure that some reforms which are meant to bring about improvements, do not have the unintended effect of imposing additional burdens on developing countries and LDCs. In this regard, it is important to retain the reporting arrangements to the General Council and we trust that Members will maintain a sufficient level of flexibility to allow a developing Member to comment on or propose any amendment to a particular reform measure.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.49-->
                    <paragraph id="3.49">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With respect to TRIPS and Public Health, the CARICOM Group thanks South Africa and the co-sponsors for their submission and calls for meaningful, constructive, and fair negotiations on Paragraph 8 of the MC12 Decision on the TRIPS Agreement, that would allow for a balanced approach between intellectual property and public health concerns. The CARICOM Group recognizes that the issue has been discussed both in the formal and informal working groups of the TRIPS Council and the SOM this year, yet there has been limited progress. We note that this issue remains important as a decision on Paragraph 8 will provide more legal certainty for Governments and legitimate policy space to adequately respond to health emergencies, and we wish to urge necessary and requisite action.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
