                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.54</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, on behalf of the OECS, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.55-->
                    <paragraph id="3.55">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We align with the statements on behalf of the CARICOM and ACP Groups. Thank you for your reports on the work being done with respect to the reforms focused on the deliberative function and institutional matters. It is clear that a significant amount of work has gone into improving the functioning of the Council for Trade in Goods and its subsidiary bodies. Much of this is commendable and important work and perhaps to the extent possible, rather than starting at ground zero, other committees and subsidiary bodies can borrow from and build on this important body of work.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.56-->
                    <paragraph id="3.56">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The CTG oversees the functioning of 14 subsidiary bodies and as a very small delegation, unfortunately, we lack the capacity to engage meaningfully in the work of the majority of these bodies, especially in a context where the negotiating agenda of the WTO remains very active. Therefore, these reports to the General Council take on added significance.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.57-->
                    <paragraph id="3.57">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We wish to make a caution and a suggestion. We caution against the introduction of reforms or improvements which on the surface, may appear to be making a qualitative difference, but which in actuality, impacts negatively on Members with small delegations. Here, we mention the change in the number of days before an agenda is closed. On one hand, it does objectively allow for Members to have better sight of an agenda which could go a far way in aiding preparations for a meeting, including consultations with capitals and stakeholders. However, on the other hand, it also reduces the time that a capacity constrained delegation has to introduce an item on an agenda. This leads to our suggestion, which is that these reforms should be reviewed periodically so as to assess their impacts and where necessary, make appropriate modifications.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.58-->
                    <paragraph id="3.58">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding the extension of the COVID-19 Waiver to Therapeutics and Diagnostics, we are broadly supportive of the call by Members to extend the waiver to cover these products. We therefore thank South Africa for its communication.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.59-->
                    <paragraph id="3.59">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Referring to item 3.A(iv), on the e-commerce issues, we thank all proponents for their proposals. We are broadly supportive of the renewal of the Work Programme and the extension of the Moratorium on Customs Duties on Electronic Transmissions. The Work Programme must reflect a clear development dimension. It is also important for there to be ongoing discussions on the definition, scope and impact of the Moratorium. We take note of the recently submitted ACP proposal in document WT/GC/W/916. We believe that the ACP Draft Decision on the Work Programme and Moratorium could serve as a useful bridge around which to structure our conversations.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
