                    <statement_number>3.64</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the United Kingdom delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.65-->
                    <paragraph id="3.65">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Thank you first for your thanks for our contribution to the fish fund, and ratification of the agreement. On reform, let me welcome the efforts of the Secretariat and all the efforts that we, the Members have put into institutional reform. As you know, the UK (and 55 Members) presented a paper to this Committee on this very important issue. We talk about showing progress, since MC12, we can be proud of the work we have done as an organization, and it shows how much we can achieve if we just get on with it. Look at the work of the CTG, just one example, 120 reforms across that Committee. At the heart of that, ensuring that we build trust, and that we ensure even the very smallest delegation here can engage in our work in a way that is constructive.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.66-->
                    <paragraph id="3.66">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the pandemic response and TRIPS, we have done some really important work on the pandemic response, following on the statement from MC12, which obviously needs to continue. On TRIPS it is clear, that the reality, despite all the discussions we have had, there is no consensus amongst Members on whether or not the extension on therapeutics and diagnostics is genuinely required. It is also true that the MC12 decision, which we spent so much time elaborating, has not been used. We need to think carefully about the value of extending something that does not appear to help all that much as we had hoped on the ground. So, without understanding the consequences of extending that decision we risk compromising the very international IP system that we have worked so effectively to develop, and has been, in our view, been so useful to us in that pandemic response.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.67-->
                    <paragraph id="3.67">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In our view, we need to build on the TRIPS Agreement to build on the way it works, not undermine it and we need to broaden the conversation on the longer-term initiative to increase access to medicines as we are hoping to achieve, with our paper on voluntary licensing and technology transfers. We recognize that voluntary licences are not a silver bullet, as is clear in the Annexes to our papers, but there are clear examples of their successful use. We are really pleased with the response to the paper, and we want to thank each and every Members who has engaged with us on it and we want to encourage all of us to share to our experiences and we look forward to further engagement in this area in the New Year.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.68</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the European Union delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.69-->
                    <paragraph id="3.69">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>There is still a lot of work to do in this final stretch ahead of MC13. We all need to show flexibility and willingness to reach landing zones if we want MC13 to be the first truly "reform ministerial." The European Union welcomes the processes that are ongoing on the different issues, including the work on reform by doing. We need to find workable solutions to key negotiations for MC13, such as dispute settlement reform, agriculture, and fisheries subsidies. We also need to identify a way forward on the issue of the e-commerce moratorium and work programme. We also need to agree on how the WTO can work post-MC13 on key issues for the multilateral trading system.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.70-->
                    <paragraph id="3.70">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the WTO's response to the COVID-19 pandemic, the European Union welcomes the work undertaken in the subsidiary bodies of the CTG on experience-sharing relating to the trade challenges that emerged from the COVID-19 pandemic. We believe that this type of technical work was not only useful to help identify solutions and best practices during the pandemic itself but can serve as a model for future pandemics and similar trade-disruptive events. We especially welcome the outcome document agreed upon in the Committee on Market Access, which attempts to draw conclusions and provides a useful summary of the work done. We welcome that the report endorses and highlights these conclusions. On TRIPS, while the European Union is ready to engage in the discussions on whether to extend the scope of the Ministerial Decision to COVID-19 therapeutics and diagnostics, we note that little progress has been made in this complex discussion and the positions of Members remain far apart. It is clear to us that there is no consensus on this issue among the Members. The European Union remains ready to engage constructively and therefore considers that the discussion should continue in order to find a consensual solution.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.71</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Bangladesh delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.72-->
                    <paragraph id="3.72">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Bangladesh aligns with the statement delivered by Djibouti on behalf of the LDC Group. We thank you for your report and for the state of play report on WTO reform contained in the document JOB/GC/359/Rev.2 regarding the work improvement in WTO councils and committees. We welcome the improvements. The core objective of WTO institutional reform is to improve its work and not to create new difficulties. Moreover, any reform must not lead to an alteration of the multilateral and Member-driven character of the WTO. All reform proposals and their finalization must be consolidated in the General Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.73-->
                    <paragraph id="3.73">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In the Senior Officials' Meeting in October, senior officials from Bangladesh and majority of Members strongly expressed support for a two-tier DS system. The senior officials also reiterated the need to bring the so-called delegate-led informal discussions as soon as possible under a relevant WTO body. It is a pity that despite clear instructions by the Ministers in MC12 outcome document paragraph 4, till date no WTO body has initiated any discussion on DS reform. Members can legitimately provide suggestions or express concerns only through a relevant WTO body. Therefore, it's urgent to bring the DS reform discussion under a relevant WTO body, respecting the agreed and established procedures of decision making in WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.74-->
                    <paragraph id="3.74">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In conclusion, we urge Members to favourably consider the LDC Group's submission JOB/GC/223/Rev.1. This is vital that, as LDCs, our voices must be heard in any reform discussion and accommodated in the decision-making process.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.75-->
                    <paragraph id="3.75">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding paragraph 8 of the Ministerial decision on TRIPS Waiver, Bangladesh aligns with the statement delivered by South Africa on behalf of the Cosponsors of IP/C/W/669/Rev.1 and the statement delivered by Djibouti on behalf of the LDC Group. We are disappointed that Members could not agree within the deadline to follow the good gesture of the Ministers. Enough facts and evidence were provided by the co-sponsors. Future pandemic is a threat. We must learn from our failures as WTO could not address the supply constraints of necessary COVID-19 vaccines, medicines, and diagnostics in a timely manner. The same mistakes and procrastination should not be repeated in future. Bangladesh supports that the MC12 decision on TRIPS Waiver should be extended to cover therapeutics and diagnostic, as soon as possible, as proposed in the draft decision WT/GC/W/913, as presented by South Africa on behalf of the co-sponsors.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.76</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Malaysia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.77-->
                    <paragraph id="3.77">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On item 3.A(i) related to WTO reform, having a fully functioning dispute settlement system is Malaysia's top reform priority. As we reiterated in numerous occasions, a fully functioning of the two-tier dispute settlement system is fundamental to this Organization and must remain as the central pillar of this institution. In this regard, Malaysia is glad to engage in the ongoing process, and we welcome the informal discussions on the dispute settlement reform, with a view to restore and making the dispute settlement system operational again. However, we wish to highlight that participation in these discussions is not without its challenges to small delegations, like Malaysia. In order to safeguard the interests of all Members, with a particular emphasis on developing and least-developed countries, it is imperative that this process is carried out in a manner that embodies inclusivity and transparency.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.78-->
                    <paragraph id="3.78">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Malaysia subscribes to the spirit of 'reform by doing' and we believe these reform initiatives should be treated as an ongoing process, and should not be rushed – but, area of priorities need to be identified with an aim to address current challenges and uncertainties.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.79-->
                    <paragraph id="3.79">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With regard to item 3.A(iii) on extending the TRIPS Decision to COVID-19 diagnostics and therapeutics, Malaysia acknowledges the importance of adopting an evidence-based approach to illustrate that intellectual property rights do not obstruct access or supply of these products. Hence, Malaysia is of the view that some related reports, including by the USITC are crucial to support the ongoing discussion at the WTO. The COVID-19 pandemic has highlighted the critical need for equitable access to affordable diagnostics and therapeutics globally. Hence, Malaysia hopes that a consensus that strikes a balance between public health needs and concerns related to intellectual property rights, can be reached at MC13 by fostering constructive dialogue and intensifying evidence-based engagement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.80</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Paraguay delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.81-->
                    <paragraph id="3.81">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On reform by doing, I commend the Council for Trade in Goods for its excellent work, as evidenced by the report in document G/L/1523, which records a total of 127 improvements in the functioning of the CTG and its subsidiary bodies. We recall that the CTG and its 14 subsidiary bodies constitute the majority of the WTO's regular bodies. These improvements, requested and pursued by Members to ensure better, more effective participation, therefore constitute significant work. The effective functioning of the regular bodies is necessary to continue and improve the monitoring and implementation function of the Agreements in force and their successful application.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.82-->
                    <paragraph id="3.82">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My delegation, together with other Latin American delegations, has been working tirelessly to boost the participation of small delegations in regular meetings, and we are pleased to see that many of the improvements suggested in document JOB/CTG/21 have already been or are being implemented. We would also like to thank the delegations of the United Kingdom and India for their specific contributions to these processes, and the constructive spirit with which all Members have participated, enabling the progress made to be implemented.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.83-->
                    <paragraph id="3.83">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Improving the functioning of the regular bodies is an incremental and ongoing process, and we would like to see similar progress in the implementation of improvements in other Councils and Committees, including this Council, which could start with a better scheduling procedure so as not to negatively impact the schedules of delegations or other bodies of this Organization. We believe that the CTG has adopted exemplary improvements, and we would like to call on all WTO Councils to assess the best practices adopted by the CTG, with a view to replicating and adopting them, where feasible. The Committee on Trade and Environment is also working on some improvements and held its first thematic session this year within the framework of the "reform by doing". Regarding formal procedural improvements, my delegation has already submitted specific proposals, which, as agreed, will continue to be analyzed with a view to their implementation under the Chair's excellent stewardship. We commend him for his leadership in advancing this issue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.84-->
                    <paragraph id="3.84">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I express my appreciation for the exemplary leadership of the CBFA Chair and DDG Ellard in seeking a compromise-based solution for the WTO budget alongside Members. We appreciate, in particular, the commitment shown in meeting the information technology requirements for the successful implementation of the digital solutions under the "reform by doing", an initiative of which Paraguay is a proponent alongside other developing Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.85-->
                    <paragraph id="3.85">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On paragraph 8 of the Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement, I express my thanks to the TRIPS Council Chair for her report and to the delegation of South Africa for its proposal. Paraguay wishes to express its support for document WT/GC/W/913, which proposes to extend the waiver to COVID-19 therapeutics and diagnostics. For countries like Paraguay, i.e., net importers of medical products and equipment with a limited capacity for local production, it is crucial to have a proper international supply chain. This includes COVID-19 vaccines, medicines, medical equipment, materials and diagnostic methods. It is essential that markets remain open without unnecessary distortions and that there be greater transparency regarding prices and conditions. We also support the strengthening of trade facilitation measures for such products with a view to reducing the restrictions imposed by producer Members, as the most vulnerable suffer most. I would like to stress that this is not simply a trade issue but also has a direct impact on our citizens' health. Paraguay therefore wishes to reaffirm its commitment to the Ministerial Decision on the TRIPS Agreement adopted at MC12 and support the extension to therapeutics and diagnostics. We urge Members to reach a consensus on this issue as soon as possible.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
