                    <statement_number>3.97</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Switzerland delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.98-->
                    <paragraph id="3.98">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I will make a single intervention under agenda items 3.A (i), (ii) and (iii). Let me thank all the Members for their meaningful engagement in conducting the work on the WTO reform as mandated in the MC12 outcome document. On the deliberative function, we welcome the steps taken in the WTO councils and committees to improve their functioning. The "reform by doing process" should continue along the same positive trend. This step-by-step approach is indeed useful in consolidating the WTO as a forum for international dialogue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.99-->
                    <paragraph id="3.99">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Future work should aim at making the WTO more inclusive and more responsive to current and future challenges. This includes launching a dedicated dialogue on trade-related global challenges: trade and industrial policy; trade and environmental sustainability; and inclusiveness at MC13. WTO reform will be at the heart of MC13. It will be an opportunity to record progress beyond improving the deliberative function.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.100-->
                    <paragraph id="3.100">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Having a fully functional dispute settlement system by 2024 remains of the highest priority for Switzerland. At MC13, we should do more than taking stock of the work done and progress achieved so far. To that end, it is important that all Members remain constructively engaged in the informal process.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.101-->
                    <paragraph id="3.101">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the negotiation function, let me recall the importance of the JSIs and their integration in the WTO framework. They contribute to strengthening the multilateral trading system and reaffirm the credibility of the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.102-->
                    <paragraph id="3.102">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the WTO response to the pandemic, we welcome the report by the CTG and its subsidiary bodies pursuant to paragraph 24 of the MC12 Ministerial Declaration. The report highlights a number of lessons learned, including the need to enhance transparency of trade-related measures, the need to better coordinate between Members and with the private sector, and the need to improve data collection and information sharing. These are areas where the WTO could carry on useful work in anticipation of future health crises.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.103-->
                    <paragraph id="3.103">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding item 3.A(iii), let me thank the TRIPS Council Chairperson for her report. My delegation takes note of communication WT/GC/W/913. We recall that WHO declared last May the end of the COVID-19 pandemic as a health emergency. More than a year ago Mexico and Switzerland submitted facts and figures in communication IP/C/W/693, which demonstrate that COVID-19 therapeutics and diagnostics are sufficiently available globally and that access is not blocked by IP. These trends have since been confirmed, including by the facts and data presented at the thematic session, that there is a surplus both in products and manufacturing capacity for COVID-19 vaccines, therapeutics and diagnostics. Millions of COVID-19 vaccines doses, therapeutics and diagnostics have had to be destroyed since due to reaching expiry date. As just mentioned by the UK, the MC12 TRIPS Decision on COVID-19 vaccines has not been used. An extension of this Decision to therapeutics and diagnostics is not necessary nor useful and risks to be counterproductive. In sum, there is no consensus among Members to take a decision on paragraph 8 extension, and the General Council should take note of this.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.104-->
                    <paragraph id="3.104">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This being said, a number of broader points were raised in the Council's discussion, such as the concern of how to stimulate geographically more diversified manufacturing of pandemic-related health products or questions in relation to the geographical limitation of certain voluntary licenses granted in the context of the pandemic. My delegation is ready to continue a constructive, facts-based discussion on these and related matters.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
