                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding item 3.A(ii), my delegation noted the extensive work carried-out pursuant to the mandate of paragraph 24 of the Ministerial Declaration at MC12. We should continue to further engage on this subject with special focus on challenges encountered by the developing countries and LDCs relating to crisis management.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.121-->
                    <paragraph id="3.121">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding paragraph 8 of the Ministerial decision on the TRIPS Agreement, my delegation wishes to thank South Africa and co-sponsors for the statement. Sri Lanka also wishes to align with many Members who proposed the extension of 17 June 2022 Ministerial Decision to COVID-19 therapeutics and diagnostics. As we know, markets failed to address the COVID-19 pandemic that had an impact on the majority of the people on this earth. The main reason was the constraints of supply side of the market. If we had a stronger supply side, not only for vaccines, but also for therapeutic and diagnostics, we could have avoided many catastrophic situations in many developing countries and LDCs. Therefore, the extension is important not only for economic reasons of correcting the market forces, but also for moral reasons.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
