                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.125-->
                    <paragraph id="3.125">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Let me respond to the agenda item 3.A(i) and 3.A(iii). We appreciate your update on the state-of-play of WTO reform. Like many others in this room, my delegation wants to see the WTO that is fit-for-purpose, fit-for-its time, and caters to the needs and interests of its diverse membership. My delegation attaches great importance, among others, on measures to facilitate Members' effective participation in WTO bodies. This includes allowing ample of preparatory time for Members to participate in the meeting. I welcome progress in the right direction, for instance, in recent Committee on Agriculture Regular Session, whereas Members approved to advance the timelines for the release of the reminder airgram and the closure of agenda. I also wish to underline the need to avoid scheduling conflicts, especially between meetings that attract great deal of interests from Members. A case in point is yesterday's session of the General Council that coincided with the Secretariat's logistical briefing for the MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.126-->
                    <paragraph id="3.126">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Moving to agenda item 3.A(iii), Indonesia would like to align its statement with South Africa, on behalf of the IP/C/W/669/Rev.1 co-sponsors. Despite evidence and facts showing that COVID-19 is here to stay, it is inexplicable that we keep hearing a much louder cry for more "evidence" or "facts" to reach a decision on this issue. Indeed, we cannot apologize to the dead, particularly to the 7 million people whose live tragically ended by COVID-19 – many of them are friends and families of ourselves. However, we can rectify our past mistakes through immediately extending the 17 June TRIPS Decision adopted by the Ministers by consensus after long protracted negotiations, mutatis mutandis to therapeutics and diagnostics, as requested by proponents in document WT/GC/W/913. Our action, or inaction, will be judged by our future generations. Therefore, it is my hope that this organization is able to show that we care about protecting public's health and to be united for common good.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.127-->
                    <paragraph id="3.127">
                        <content>
