                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.128</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the Plurinational State of Bolivia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.129-->
                    <paragraph id="3.129">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding WTO reform, we take note of the discussions and appreciate the efforts made. We believe that for the process to be credible and fruitful, it must necessarily be Member-driven, provide tools that ensure the participation of all countries based on the principles of inclusiveness and transparency, and allow the Members of small delegations from developing countries to participate fully in meetings.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.130-->
                    <paragraph id="3.130">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding paragraph 8 of the MC12 decision, we endorse the statement made by the distinguished delegation of South Africa on behalf of the co-sponsors of document IP/C/W/669/Rev.1. We regret that, more than one and a half years later, no concrete progress has been made in fulfilling the mandate adopted by Ministers at MC12 to extend the waiver decision to therapeutics and diagnostics, as indicated in paragraph 8 of the decision. The high cost of essential medical supplies to combat COVID-19 became evident during the pandemic, and many countries face major challenges in accessing medicines and diagnostic tests, the procedures for which are costly, complex, and lengthy. Several states encourage the use of voluntary licensing, but Bolivia made a request in this regard, and to date, we have heard nothing, which clearly shows how voluntary licensing does not offer an opportunity to provide the rapid response required in a health emergency.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.131-->
                    <paragraph id="3.131">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Accordingly, we believe that it is crucial to continue the discussions to conclude the implementation of the decision. It is clear that the international community's response to the COVID-19 pandemic was, for many populations worldwide, belated and limited. The pandemic and its effects remain latent, and one of the lessons learned is that to react to future pandemics, the limited access to vaccines, therapeutics and diagnostics must be addressed. We must prioritize human life and those hit hardest by the adverse effects of this and future pandemics.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
