                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.140</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.141-->
                    <paragraph id="3.141">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With regard to item 3.A(iii), I would like to thank the Chairperson of TRIPS Council for her report. India would like to echo the views of co-sponsors who spoke before me and align ourselves with the statement made by South Africa on behalf of co-sponsors. It is regrettable that a decision remains elusive for this multilateral body on such a critical issue of global significance. Despite protracted deliberations over three years, we have disappointed ourselves and we have disappointed the world that was anticipating a quick multilateral response from the organization and during a pandemic. Several rounds of submissions have been made on this issue, so we have not left any stone unturned in responding to all questions raised and clarification sought by Members and through extensive discussions, we presented facts and evidence to guide us in making a decision. I urge all Members to engage with good faith and conclude our discussion today by taking a decision. We hope we all are able to agree for the extension of the MC12 decision to therapeutics and diagnostics as presented in the document IP/C/W/694/Rev.1.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.142-->
                    <paragraph id="3.142">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Now I will touch upon the reform part. We thank the Secretariat for the compilation in JOB/GC/359/Rev.2. There is a need for continuing this process of incremental reform. Several suggestions by Members are in the pipeline's while a number of short-term implementation suggestions from India through our proposal WT/GC/W/874 dubbed as 30 for 30 have been implemented. There are certain medium to long term suggestions, which still require further consideration and we will work towards that, like productive apps, website management, manner and extent of external stakeholder engagement and communication, WTO rules and procedures and committee specific suggestions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.143-->
                    <paragraph id="3.143">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In my bilateral or informal consultations, I realized that this phrase of reform by doing is understood differently by different Members. We believe that reform or incremental change has to be Member-driven and consensus based that does not alter the rights and obligations of Members and adhere strictly to the foundational principles of this organization. It should not be envisioned as a tool for creating new mandates or prioritizing new agenda while shelving the pending agenda and mandates. The Organization would be fit for purpose by improving the working of the Organization to make it open, transparent, inclusive and efficient.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.144-->
                    <paragraph id="3.144">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would also like to thank and welcome the report G/L/1523. We are delighted that the CTG and its 14 subsidiary bodies have implemented 127 improvements. My delegation has been engaged deeply and constructively in this exercise. While our paper envisages 30 improvements to the WTO before it completes 30 years, I believe we should up these and replicate the CTG successes elsewhere to make it 300 for 30!</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.145-->
                    <paragraph id="3.145">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The last item which is response to pandemic. On all these three items, I will submit the written statement since time is over. I will just highlight two submissions which we made on response to pandemic that is WT/GC/W/866 and WT/GC/W/867 relating to "role of telemedicine services" and another on "building a pool of health professionals to respond to pandemic and natural disasters" respectively. We look forward to further discussions both at the GC and at the Council for Trade in Services to analyze lessons that have been learned and challenges experienced during the COVID-19 pandemic. I look forward to these important discussions being reported to MC13 and seek further guidance from Ministers at the MC13 to continue future work on these two proposals. Lastly, on India's paper in CTG relating to response to pandemic, we would like to say that though it was not part of any notification obligation, but it was an effort on our part to explain the multifaceted response to the pandemic and the key role played by India's trade related government institutions in the response to pandemic.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.146</statement_number>
                    <statement>The Director-General delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.147-->
                    <paragraph id="3.147">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Just two quick comments on two aspects. One is on reform by doing, I want to congratulate Members on the work that they are doing. It is very challenging, and I am sure no matter the effort put in there will always be gaps. We have tried from the Secretariat to be as innovative as we can, and I am glad that Ecuador referred to the e-Delegates platform that we have put together, as well as e-agenda and others. We continue to try to come up with ways to make it easier, especially for small delegations to engage, within the resources that we have. This morning we had a staff recognition day where we recognized some of those who have come up with these innovations, amongst staff.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.148-->
                    <paragraph id="3.148">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>For the LDCs, we are very sympathetic about the limited resources. Just some advice it may be important for some smaller delegations to pull resources because I see that with the MC13 negotiations coming, there is just no way. It is like what I said the other day, we need a lot of meetings to negotiate but these meetings are challenging for small delegations because you want to participate in all. Pulling resources like the Pacific Islands Forum has done could be very helpful to smaller delegations because then a number of countries are represented, or the OECS. This is just a suggestion. I have been trying to get some of the leaders to understand the enormous amount of work here at the WTO for their delegations and some have promised to beef up their missions with some additional help but not all can do it. So, we have to find also other ways or means for least-developed country Members to try to get the work done.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.149-->
                    <paragraph id="3.149">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the TRIPS waiver, I strongly want to urge that I hope the membership can come to some decision on this particular issue and not allow it to trail in our books. Bolivia said something important, it was about voluntary licensing, it has not been able to move forward. I hope that the private – all those that have the private sector actors - can move on this particular aspect, if it is to be a tool. But multiple tools are needed. Whilst all this is happening, it is important to say that some Members have moved ahead to change the legislation to enable them to be able to work. For instance, Senegal is moving ahead with a whole supply chain on several types of vaccines, so whilst some are talking others are doing. I strongly also want to urge developing country Members to move quickly on their legislation. We are working with 16 countries now, the WHO, WIPO and the WTO, to help them assess their legislative capabilities to use the flexibilities and to fix it. I just wanted to urge Members to take a look at this and let us know if it is something that the tripartite agreement can help you with.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.150-->
                    <paragraph id="3.150">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson thanked the Director-General for her input and those practical suggestions and for sharing some of the developments that are taking place.</t>
                            </p>
