                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.154-->
                    <paragraph id="3.154">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council took note of the Chairperson's statement and of the other statements made.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.155-->
                    <paragraph id="3.155">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson said that there were four matters under this sub-item, which she would take up in turn, before opening the floor to delegations once at the very end.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.156-->
                    <paragraph id="3.156">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>She first turned to Ambassador Dwarka-Canabady (Mauritius), in her capacity as Facilitator, to provide the WTO membership with a report on the work and developments since the meeting of the General Council in November.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.157-->
                    <paragraph id="3.157">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Ambassador Usha Dwarka-Canabady (Mauritius), Facilitator for the E-Commerce Work Programme and Moratorium, delivered the following report:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.158-->
                    <paragraph id="3.158">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Thank you for this opportunity to provide an update on the Work Programme on Electronic Commerce before the year end. As we prepare for MC13, I believe we can look back with a certain degree of satisfaction at the work that we have carried out this year and I wish to take this opportunity to thank all Members for their engagement throughout these discussions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.159-->
                    <paragraph id="3.159">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Since my last report in November (JOB/GC/368), we have held two dedicated discussions. The Dedicated Discussion on 14 November was the third meeting of the year to focus on the moratorium. Given the calls for more engagement on this issue and for evidence-based analysis, I invited the WTO Secretariat to present the findings of the report on Digital Trade for Development jointly prepared with the IMF, OECD, UNCTAD, and the World Bank. Representatives of the respective organizations attended the meeting and answered Members' questions including on two recent papers issued by the IMF and OECD. The Joint Report had not yet been launched at the time of the meeting. It has since then been officially launched during the e-Week of UNCTAD and is now accessible on the WTO website.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.160-->
                    <paragraph id="3.160">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the Dedicated Discussion held on Friday, 8 December, Members started consideration of text-based proposals for a draft Ministerial decision. Three submissions were considered in this regard. Two of them are on the agenda of today's meeting (WT/GC/W/909 from Canada, Switzerland and other co-sponsors, and WT/GC/W/911 from South Africa). A third one, from the ACP Group, was made available in the room and subsequently circulated in WT/GC/W/916. All three draft documents call for the continued re-invigoration of the Work Programme in line with the 1998 mandate. Some contain additional elements, such as emphasis on the development dimension and the reporting process on the work programme to the General Council and/or other relevant bodies and the timings thereof. There were equally proposals for the creation of a trust fund and suggestions for the development of a more level playing field. With respect to the moratorium, two of the draft documents call for the extension of the moratorium until MC14 and one calls for its termination at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.161-->
                    <paragraph id="3.161">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Despite known differences, I am pleased to report that discussions on Friday last were constructive, and delegations offered specific comments and suggestions on each of the draft proposals put forward.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.162-->
                    <paragraph id="3.162">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In terms of format for a draft ministerial Decision, there seems to be a preference for maintaining the structure and brevity of recent Ministerial Decisions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.163-->
                    <paragraph id="3.163">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Since the three draft documents presented at the meeting bear a number of similar elements, these commonalities emerged during discussions, for example, with respect to acknowledging progress made in the reinvigoration of the Work Programme; upholding the development dimension of the work programme; the need to continue working with other IGOs to address identified challenges and deepening discussions on certain issues.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.164-->
                    <paragraph id="3.164">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>There was less convergence with regard to the reporting structure and the level of prescription for reporting. There was nonetheless flexibility from the proponents to accommodate the concerns raised.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.165-->
                    <paragraph id="3.165">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The extension of the moratorium remained the main point of contention. Members reiterated well-known positions, and some renewed their calls for including reference to continuing discussions on the definition, scope and impact of the moratorium. I noted the readiness to discuss further and have encouraged delegations to put forward proposals on scope and definition from their individual perspectives.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.166-->
                    <paragraph id="3.166">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>More work is certainly needed if we are to find a middle-ground, particularly on the moratorium. I have requested delegations to reflect further on the three draft proposals currently on the table and to send any additional comments they may have by Friday, 15 December, close of business.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.167-->
                    <paragraph id="3.167">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I intend to hold consultations in mid-January to deepen our discussion on these draft texts for a Ministerial decision. This will take place ahead of the Dedicated Discussion scheduled for 25 January. The purpose would be to find language that captures the commonalities between the three texts on the table.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.168-->
                    <paragraph id="3.168">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Before concluding, let me recall the more recent communications from the LDC Group in document WT/GC/W/905, from India and South Africa in document WT/GC/W/902/Rev.1, and from South Africa in WT/GC/W/910 – the latter being on the agenda of today's meeting. As our discussions on thematic issues have concluded, we have not been able to consider them in the Dedicated Discussions. Whilst I remain guided by Members as to whether there should be special sessions to discuss these papers at a later point, I did inform Members at our meeting last Friday, that they are free to propose language for a Ministerial decision based on their perspectives. Should there be anything specific in these papers that the proponents would wish to see reflected in a potential draft ministerial decision, they are welcome to propose any specific textual language.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.169-->
                    <paragraph id="3.169">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I look forward to Members' continued engagement during consultations in January and the forthcoming dedicated discussion.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.170-->
                    <paragraph id="3.170">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson thanked Ambassador Dwarka-Canabady. Before moving to the next matter, she noted that at her recent meeting with Chairpersons of regular WTO bodies, she was informed that discussions on the work programme were also taking place in the respective bodies – although at different levels of engagement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.171-->
                    <paragraph id="3.171">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson invited the delegation of South Africa to introduce the communication titled "Challenges for Digital Industrialization in Developing Countries".</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.172</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of South Africa delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.173-->
                    <paragraph id="3.173">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Our paper on challenges to digital industrialization in developing countries such as ours shares practical examples of how the dominance of global tech firms and other features of these markets undermine economic diversification and inclusive supply chains. Sharing case examples can help to enrich our discussions, even if we hold differing views.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.174-->
                    <paragraph id="3.174">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The concentration of market power, particularly by global tech giants, is resulting in uneven participation in global commerce, notably hindering the growth of Micro, Small, and Medium-sized Enterprises (MSMEs) and digital start-ups. Our delegation views the Electronic Transmissions (ET) moratorium as one of the significant factors exacerbating these disparities. This moratorium has been in place for a quarter of a century. There is no consensus on this issue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.175-->
                    <paragraph id="3.175">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We submitted a comprehensive presentation of our paper during the dedicated discussion on 8 December. For the record, we will submit this paper to the Secretariat. We received valuable feedback from several delegations during the dedicated discussion, and we look forward to studying these insights in detail when the minutes are circulated.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.176-->
                    <paragraph id="3.176">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We acknowledge the recent study jointly published by the WTO Secretariat, the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), and the World Bank. While the study primarily emphasizes revenue losses, we wish to underscore that our core concern, articulated consistently by South Africa and others, is the erosion of policy space to employ tariffs as a tool for industrial development. This central challenge has not yet been met with credible responses from the proponents of the moratorium.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.177-->
                    <paragraph id="3.177">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The contention raised by proponents about the supposedly negligible impact of the moratorium on revenue is a straw man argument. We must underline that neither the recent studies nor the positions advocated by the proponents have adequately addressed this fundamental challenge expressed by South Africa and others.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.178-->
                    <paragraph id="3.178">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the April dedicated discussion, my delegation posed four questions to proponents that would assist in taking this discussion to fruitful avenues. These questions have, by and large, returned blank.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.179-->
                    <paragraph id="3.179">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In sum, these questions concern the scope and definition of electronic transmissions; the extent of 'online imports' of electronic transmissions in different countries; the substantive basis for discrimination between digitizable products and physical products; and the potential foreclosure of possibilities for digital industrialization due to the extension of the moratorium.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.180-->
                    <paragraph id="3.180">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As indicated by our Minister at the Mini-Ministerial on 11 December, my delegation is not convinced by the arguments offered by the proponents so far. Some of the insights from the reports presented to us seemed skewed in favour of the heuristic biases of the proponents. We are not in a position to agree to the extension of the moratorium.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.181-->
                    <paragraph id="3.181">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We remain ready to engage constructively on this issue, including fact-based and evidence-based discussion, while countries exercise their rights to use tariffs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.182-->
                    <paragraph id="3.182">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson then turned to the remaining two communications, both containing draft language for a Ministerial decision on the Work Programme on Electronic Commerce. Before inviting the respective delegations to introduce the communications, she recalled that, as heard from Ambassador Dwarka-Canabady, these draft decisions had been discussed extensively at the Dedicated Discussion held on 8 December. She reminded delegations that the Dedicated Discussions were held under the auspices of the General Council and that there were minutes for those meetings.  In light of the extensive agenda and to ensure an efficient use of time, she encouraged delegations to avoid duplication of discussions on this item and to intervene only if they had something new to add. She then invited Switzerland to introduce communication WT/GC/W/909.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.183</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Switzerland delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.184-->
                    <paragraph id="3.184">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Switzerland is making this statement on behalf of the following Members who are co-sponsors of WT/GC/W/909/Rev.1: Australia; Canada; Chile; Costa Rica; Georgia; Hong Kong, China; Iceland; Israel; Korea; Liechtenstein; Moldova; Montenegro; North Macedonia; Norway; New Zealand; Paraguay; Peru; Qatar; Singapore; Switzerland; Separate Customs Territory of Taiwan, Penghu, Kinmen and Matsu; Ukraine; United Kingdom and Uruguay.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.185-->
                    <paragraph id="3.185">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Before presenting our draft for a decision on e-commerce at MC13, we would like first to acknowledge the leadership of Ambassador Dwarka-Canabady, whose facilitation of the Dedicated Discussions has been instrumental in reviving works under the 1998 Work Programme.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.186-->
                    <paragraph id="3.186">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, while we present today our proposal for a draft decision on the Work Programme and moratorium on e-commerce, we have received valuable inputs in bilateral contacts as well as during the meeting of 8 December of the Dedicated Discussion. We would like to thank in particular CARICOM and the OECS for their feedback and the valuable exchange. We are currently working on integrating these inputs – in particular on the importance to reflect the development dimension – with a view to submit a revised draft decision. We would also like to thank the ACP Group for their proposal for a draft decision contained in communication WT/GC/W/916.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.187-->
                    <paragraph id="3.187">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is clear that there is strong and growing convergence across the membership on extending the moratorium on customs duties on electronic transmissions. We are looking forward to further engagement with all interested Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.188-->
                    <paragraph id="3.188">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Turning to our communication specifically, our proposal intends to capture the progress accomplished since MC12. It aims at continuing work under the e-commerce Work Programme and extending the e-commerce Moratorium until the next Ministerial Conference We welcome the exchanges under the Dedicated Discussions, which have contributed to the marked increase in engagement under the Work Programme.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.189-->
                    <paragraph id="3.189">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In order to build on this positive engagement, we now call to focus our discussions. Selecting a set of specific trade related issues will allow delegations to address issues of particular importance to Members in more depth and dedicate their resources more effectively.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.190-->
                    <paragraph id="3.190">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the e-commerce moratorium, there is a growing body of evidence supporting the importance of not applying customs duties. Indeed, just last week another study by the IMF, OECD, UNCTAD, World Bank and WTO on "Digital Trade and Development" was released.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.191-->
                    <paragraph id="3.191">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The bottom line coming out of the vast majority of these studies is that not applying customs duties benefits businesses in all member countries, LDCs, developing, and developed, particularly for micro, small, medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs), which are the lifeblood of the global economy.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.192-->
                    <paragraph id="3.192">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Hence, we are comforted in the view that continuing to provide to each other the guarantee to not impose customs duties on electronic transmissions is the right path to follow. We strongly believe that the lapse of the moratorium would degrade the international regulatory framework for digital trade, thereby causing significant uncertainty and unpredictability to the global economy given an increasing proportion of trade is digital.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.193-->
                    <paragraph id="3.193">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We welcome further support to this draft decision and stand ready to adapt it to reflect the needs and concerns of the membership.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.194-->
                    <paragraph id="3.194">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson then invited the delegation of South Africa to introduce communication WT/GC/W/911.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
