                    <statement_number>3.207</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Samoa, on behalf of the ACP Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.208-->
                    <paragraph id="3.208">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The ACP Group commends the work of the Facilitator and looks forward to her continuing the dedicated discussions. We welcome the submissions of other Members. While our new submission WT/GC/W/916 is not on the agenda, the ACP Group has been working on this submission as a contribution to the reinvigoration of the work programme on E-Commerce. We covered the areas in the thematic sessions such as emerging supportive legislation such as consumer protection, privacy, transaction laws, tax laws, and areas of digital divide, for the e-commerce platform.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.209-->
                    <paragraph id="3.209">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Our members are working on and choosing which legislation is needed and how much of it in order to facilitate the growth of e-commerce, build infrastructure, skills, payment systems, and legislation to protect consumers. Legislation alone is not a panacea for e-commerce and its development role. Too much legislation could defeat our development goals. Legislation must match the development needs and e-readiness goals of each member. We need not only digital trade, we must have targeted assistance, investment, and cooperation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.210-->
                    <paragraph id="3.210">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Our submission also takes up the question of the moratorium. We looked into the antecedents of the treatment of software while in the carrier medium and treatment of content for tariff purposes, other products that were traded in carrier media, to later transform by virtue of the technology into digital form. In the reinvigoration of the work program, it will help developing countries and LDCs to adapt to the transformation and proper analysis be prepared to compare what we were actually doing during this transformation, rather than relying on estimates or predictions. In addressing revenue gain for governments, we must also balance our evaluation to consider the impact on our consumers and businesses, especially small medium sized businesses, and the enterprises of women and youth.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.211-->
                    <paragraph id="3.211">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We conducted internal discussions with the UN, OECD, and heard presentations of some of our own Members on their work on digital tax and value added tax systems which are also not a panacea. We also listened with interest in the presentations from Indonesia. At the same time, we see that the tariff charge is zero. Some Members have raised other elements that can help us.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.212-->
                    <paragraph id="3.212">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The work programme must continue its reinvigoration to take the progress in our discussions further to a mutually acceptable landing in the context of the WTO. In the meantime, we should extend the moratorium which is part of that discussion. You will see we have an annex in this regard. We can come together and find common ground and do no harm, by continuing the reinvigoration of work programme with information exchanges, deeper dive discussions on the regulations, technologies, VAT systems, customs duties, methodologies to reduce the digital divide, in order to arrive at the most pragmatic way to consider all of the relevant elements.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.213-->
                    <paragraph id="3.213">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The WTO can upgrade its convening role to include key international organizations to come forward with targeted reports with a view to advancing the development aspects of e- commerce. We thank the Director General for kicking off the joint report "Digital Trade for Development". We are still studying the document.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
