                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.238</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Indonesia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.239-->
                    <paragraph id="3.239">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We extend our sincere appreciation to the Facilitator for her tireless efforts in facilitating discussions among WTO Members throughout the year to address critical issues related to member participation in digital trade. We envision that these discussions will continue in the future, with a sharpened focus that will lead to concrete outcomes actionable by Members, particularly in bridging the digital divide.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.240-->
                    <paragraph id="3.240">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We also would like to support the submission by South Africa and wholeheartedly agree with the findings of the South African Market Inquiry, which clearly demonstrate the negative impact of the moratorium on customs duties on electronic transmissions on digital industrialization in developing countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.241-->
                    <paragraph id="3.241">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As we approach the MC13, we urge Members to uphold the policy space and flexibility required for the implementation of Customs Duties on Electronic Transmission. The moratorium, which has been in place since 1998, has continuously hindered developing Members to leverage electronic transmissions for their domestic digital economies. Hence, we call for collective efforts to address the current digital trade imbalances and set a definitive end to the moratorium. The termination of the moratorium will not only level the playing field for developing countries but also allow us to gather concrete evidence of its positive impact on our economies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.242-->
                    <paragraph id="3.242">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This evidence will serve as a valuable basis for future Member discussions within the framework of the Work Programme on E-Commerce. Therefore, recognizing the gravity of this matter, Indonesia stands in opposition to making any decisions regarding the moratorium at the General Council meeting. We firmly maintain that this matter merits deliberation at the highest level, namely at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
