                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.253</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Singapore delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.254-->
                    <paragraph id="3.254">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to start by putting on record my delegation's appreciation to the Facilitator for her able leadership in advancing discussions on the Work Programme on E-Commerce (WPEC). We would also like to thank South Africa for presenting their two communications. Allow me to share three points.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.255-->
                    <paragraph id="3.255">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, Singapore is pleased to co-sponsor the draft Ministerial Decision (WT/GC/W/909) to continue the Work Programme on E-Commerce and extend the Moratorium on Customs Duties on E-Commerce. We urge Members to join this emerging consensus as co-sponsors, and to accelerate efforts to reach agreement on a Ministerial Decision early, rather than leaving it to the eleventh hour at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.256-->
                    <paragraph id="3.256">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, Singapore welcomes the rejuvenated discussions at the WPEC Dedicated Sessions since MC12, which is in line with Ministers' instructions. Like other Members, Singapore has actively contributed by sharing our experiences through five presentations that deal with a range of issues such as (a) our new overseas vendor registration system; (b) the Digital Economy Agreements (DEAs); and (c) trade digitalization. We appreciate the active engagement by Members and hope that these experience-sharing sessions have helped to stimulate a fruitful exchange of ideas and fostered deeper understanding of these important topics.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.257-->
                    <paragraph id="3.257">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Third, we must avoid politicizing the Moratorium and engage in more evidence-based discussions. Several useful studies on this issue have been issued, including the joint international organization report on "Digital Trade and Development" launched last week. The report highlighted that the moratorium's impact on government revenue is estimated to be very small (below 0.33 per cent of overall government revenue on average), and that value added taxes are viable alternative policy tools. While there will no doubt continue to be divergence of views over issues such as the scope and definition of electronic transmissions, we hope that the latest evidence-based studies can help to bridge such gaps. We further encourage bringing external stakeholders, such as private sector players, to complement our discussions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
