                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.261</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Costa Rica delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.262-->
                    <paragraph id="3.262">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to thank the Facilitator for her report and her leadership and efforts in this area. For Costa Rica, it is essential that the moratorium on electronic transmissions be maintained and become a permanent decision as soon as possible so that trade actors, particularly those from developing countries, LDCs and MSMEs, have security and predictability regarding the conditions they currently enjoy. Evidence shows that the alleged loss of tax revenue due to the moratorium is either non-existent or completely marginal when compared to its benefits to competitiveness, economic growth, technology transfer, the bridging of the digital divide and development. Lifting the moratorium would lead to less competitiveness and increased costs, which would affect developing countries in particular, widen the digital divide and impact negatively on MSMEs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.263-->
                    <paragraph id="3.263">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Costa Rica is therefore pleased to endorse WT/GC/W/910, which is aimed at continuing discussions within the framework of the Work Programme and maintaining the moratorium until MC14. We also welcome the recent proposal by the ACP Group, which is in the same vein and contains very interesting points, such as continuing collaboration with other relevant international organizations and stakeholders.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.264-->
                    <paragraph id="3.264">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding the documents submitted by South Africa, I wish to point out that Costa Rica is concerned about several aspects. In particular, we do not agree with the paragraph in the draft decision concerning the removal of the moratorium. We are concerned that efforts are being made, in the name of development, to reverse the openness that has existed in this sector since 1998, with disregard for the evidence and data showing its benefits.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
