                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.279</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nigeria delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.280-->
                    <paragraph id="3.280">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank the Facilitator for her report. We also thank South Africa for presenting its paper contained in document WT/GC/W/910. While it is evident that some Members, especially the home states of large technology platforms, have managed to harness the full benefits of technological advancements and of ecommerce, we believe some the conclusions of the Competition Commission of South African regarding how the Moratorium on Electronic Transmission is undermining digital industrialization in Developing Countries requires further reflection.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.281-->
                    <paragraph id="3.281">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe a comprehensive assessment of the welfare effects of the moratorium would reveal that it bolsters the competitiveness and growth of Developing Countries MSMEs who are able to access intermediate content at cheaper price as well as strengthen market linkages not to mention consumer surplus. We would however engage with South Africa to enable us gain insight into the scope, methodology and findings of the paper.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.282-->
                    <paragraph id="3.282">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank the proponent of WT/GC/W/909 for their statement. Nigeria consistently called for the Work Programme on Electronic Commerce to be approached from a Development Perspective so we can collectively explore the appropriate policy instruments within the WTO toolbox that could be deployed to foster the development of ecommerce ecosystem in Developing Countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.283-->
                    <paragraph id="3.283">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the moratorium, we believe that the scope and the definition need to be clarified so Members can understand the scope of their commitment. Hitherto, it has remained ambiguous, and WTO Members have conflicting interpretation of these issues. However, given that achieving consensus on this issue is unlikely at MC13 due to time constraint, it should be accorded priority and taken up post MC13. Regarding the moratorium on Imposing Customs Duties on Electronic Transmissions, Nigeria believes it should be extended temporarily at MC13. Nigeria holds this view for three important reasons. First, the non-renewal of the moratorium would undermine the predictability of global e-commerce environment, and this would negatively affect businesses and consumers. Next, it will undermine the competitiveness and growth of our MSMEs who would be unable to access intermediate content at cheaper price. Third, given the dynamic effects of the moratorium, we believe the benefits outweigh the cost and non-renewal will only mean the WTO has chosen not to be responsive to the economic realities of the 21st century.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.284-->
                    <paragraph id="3.284">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank South Africa for their statement. This draft decision further articulates the conclusions of WT/GC/W/910. Nigeria supports the temporary extension of the moratorium for reasons we shared earlier and in the interest of time we will not repeat ourselves. We will continue to engage South Africa constructively towards ensuring the renewal of moratorium and the adoption of a development centric work programme at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
