                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.311</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chinese Taipei delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.312-->
                    <paragraph id="3.312">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to thank Switzerland for introducing the draft Ministerial Decision of WT/GC/W/909, of which we are one of the co-sponsors. We believe that this proposal is a more balanced one. It recommends the continuation of the current practice of not imposing customs duties on electronic transmissions until the 14th Ministerial Conference. It leaves Members with the opportunity to continue periodically reviewing the moratorium. The proposal also upholds the development dimension in the Work Programme to help reduce the digital gap among Members. We urge Members which are yet to join the initiative to support the proposal. I also thank South Africa for introducing its proposals. However, we would like to raise our concern about the WT/GC/W/911 regarding the suggestion of terminating the moratorium.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.313-->
                    <paragraph id="3.313">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The complex nature of the global digital ecosystem is obvious in that all stakeholders of the e-commerce platforms, the content suppliers and the e-commerce consumers are interconnected. Imposing customs duties on electronic transmissions in the whole ecosystem will be invariably impacted, regardless of their business size. The suggested text in WT/GC/W/911 about terminating the moratorium not only gives rise to serious uncertainty to international trade in e-commerce, but most importantly, poses immense adverse impacts on related sectors and consumers in all Members, particularly those in the more vulnerable Members. It will undermine MSMEs' economic positions most seriously. It is because that, given their limited resources to adapt to drastic changes in the digital trade environment, MSMEs are most vulnerable to any imposition of duties on e-commerce transactions on which they heavily rely.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.314-->
                    <paragraph id="3.314">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We sincerely hope that WT/GC/W/911 concerning its suggestion on stopping the moratorium can be reconsidered. We will engage constructively in the discussion on the concerns raised by its proponents.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
