                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.319</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.320-->
                    <paragraph id="3.320">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to thank Ambassador Usha Canabady for her efforts in steering the work programme on e-commerce. India has contributed constructively to this process of reinvigoration, particularly through our submissions on consumer protection, competition and digital public infrastructure including the international experiences.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.321-->
                    <paragraph id="3.321">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would also like to thank the proponents and the papers submitted in the form of WT/GC/W/909, WT/GC/W/910 and WT/GC/W/911, particularly the last two papers from South Africa, and we feel disappointed that the proponents of WT/GC/W/909 have once again taken it for granted that without evidence and without explanation, Ministers will be able to take a decision by simply writing two paragraphs on extension of the moratorium.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.322-->
                    <paragraph id="3.322">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The current global landscape of e- commerce is dominated by a few firms based in developed countries, and most developing countries are net importers of digital products. Increasing participation of developing countries in global e- commerce continues to be a challenge due to the digital divide that exists between the developed and the developing countries. At various international fora concerns have been expressed about the increasing influence of big tech firms, which is counter to the narrative that we hear in this room. MSMEs face considerable challenges on account of anti-competitive business practices of the big tech firms, which had been clearly brought out in the South African submission. Very recently we have seen that in one of the judgments of the authorities in a developed country in the discussion around the moratorium, we believe that the agenda of big tech, I repeat, that we believe that the agenda of big tech is being pursued in the garb of MSMEs. We have never got information that how much of gain in the demanding countries are going to MSMEs and to the big tech firms respectively-that evidence has not been put on table.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.323-->
                    <paragraph id="3.323">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Unfortunately, in the last agenda item we heard the same problem for TRIPS waiver decision that we need evidence but, in this case, we take shelter under various reports and the proponents fail to bring out specific submissions highlighting what their country or what their industry is gaining through these 25 years of moratorium.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.324-->
                    <paragraph id="3.324">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In the wake of lack of common understanding amongst the membership on the scope of the moratorium, and the significant implications of the moratorium, particularly on developing countries, including LDCs, the merit of continuing to maintain this practice needs to be questioned. We have not yet seen convincing evidence by the proponents of the moratorium, that its continuation has benefited countries particularly developing and LDCs having large population and marketplace. Customs duties have traditionally been used to confer level playing field to domestic industries and also to work on macroeconomic policies for controlling unhindered imported goods influence in case of currency crisis. India believes that while digital industrialization holds the promise for economic development and prosperity for the developing countries, including the LDCs all policy tools in the toolbox, which includes customs duties are needed to realize its full potential.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.325-->
                    <paragraph id="3.325">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>India supports reinvigoration of the work under the work programme of e-commerce, and through our submissions we have made efforts to draw attention of the membership to the challenges related to consumer trust and anti-competitive practices, role of digital public infrastructure approach in promoting innovation, democratizing technology and fostering competitive ecology of digital businesses.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.326-->
                    <paragraph id="3.326">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In India, the unified payment interface is enabling more than 10 billion transactions monthly which is more than the global population. It has democratized digital payments at zero cost. Open Network for digital commerce enables inclusive e commerce by allowing small sellers to participate on equal footing on fair terms without getting extorted by the big tech platforms.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.327-->
                    <paragraph id="3.327">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>India stands ready to contribute to global efforts at harnessing to transform essential capabilities of e-commerce. Last but not the least, I would like to remind that graduating LDC countries had to negotiate very hard for duty free quota free access for the transition period. Let us not give this duty-free quota free access to the big tech firms in developed countries for the markets of developing countries without any evidence and without any discussion.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
