                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.399</statement_number>
                    <statement>The Director-General delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.400-->
                    <paragraph id="3.400">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like first to provide an update on the ongoing Aid for Trade monitoring and evaluation exercise. I discussed this at November's General Council. This exercise is important in understanding the trade and development priorities of developing countries and LDCs – and how they are evolving.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.401-->
                    <paragraph id="3.401">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I am pleased to see an active engagement by Members in this year's Aid for Trade monitoring exercise. As of now, we have received 61 responses from a diverse range of Members. So far, 44 responses have come from developing countries, including 20 LDCs, 15 from donors (both bilateral and multilateral), and two from South-South partners. This demonstrates a global interest and commitment to the Aid for Trade Initiative.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.402-->
                    <paragraph id="3.402">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As you have heard from the GC Chairperson, the deadline to respond has been extended to 5 January. I would urge Members to use this time to send in responses. The more diverse the response, the more comprehensive an understanding of the various perspectives and challenges faced by our Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.403-->
                    <paragraph id="3.403">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The insights gathered from this monitoring and evaluation exercise are valuable. They contribute not only to the effectiveness of Aid-for-Trade interventions but also inform the broader discussions on trade and development.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.404-->
                    <paragraph id="3.404">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Let me now give some further details on the organization of the Global Review. I understand that Ambassador Sánchez-Fung will launch a call for thematic session proposals in January, with a submission deadline at the end of March. Members, Observers and Observer Organizations can submit requests to organize thematic sessions during the Global Review.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.405-->
                    <paragraph id="3.405">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This year's theme Global Review theme will follow the main topic of the biennial work programme, that is: "Mainstreaming Trade". I believe that there is still much that we can do to integrate trade perspectives in development, notably in the context of the pivot to sustainability. This is of course a theme that resonated at the Trade Pavilion during COP28.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.406-->
                    <paragraph id="3.406">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I encourage you to use the Global Review to look at the impact of the Aid for Trade Initiative and ensuring that it remains fit for purpose in a rapidly changing trade and development context. The Global Review will take place on 26-28 June, with events likely taking place in the full week of 24 June 2024. I encourage all Members to mark this date on their calendars.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.407</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.408-->
                    <paragraph id="3.408">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to again remind of the pending decision of Bali and Nairobi, including the General Council Decision of November 2014 on permanent solution to PSH which remains unfulfilled. Our Commerce and Industry Minister underscored the importance of honouring the past Ministerial Decisions during the Virtual Mini-Ministerial meeting on 28 November 2023. It was further underscored by the Ministers of the Members co-sponsoring JOB/AG/229.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.409-->
                    <paragraph id="3.409">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Preceding the Ministerial meeting, the Agriculture and Food Security session of the Senior Officials Meeting held on 22 and 23 October 2023 clearly highlighted the concern and the importance given by a large number of Members, especially the developing country Members, to the past Ministerial Decisions, especially to the mandate provided to the Permanent Solution to the PSH and SSM. During the three breakout sessions on Agriculture, 88 Members made interventions, and nearly 60 Members called for a PS to the PSH at the MC 13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.410-->
                    <paragraph id="3.410">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Food Security, as per the AoA, is a non-trade concern. As per the Ministerial Mandates of Bali and Nairobi, the permanent solution to the PSH was to be achieved on fast track, accelerated basis in the dedicated sessions – completely delinked of normal proceedings by CoA SS by MC11. Maybe third time lucky by MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.411-->
                    <paragraph id="3.411">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In the past, we noted that the credibility of the Organization will be at risk if it does not deliver on the mandated issues. Here we are trying to have new decisions, completely forgetting we also have a responsibility to implement past decisions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.412-->
                    <paragraph id="3.412">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We had also requested that the compilation of all outstanding decisions of our Ministers be brought before the General Council by the Secretariat, so that we are able to track those decisions and take necessary actions. This is still desired, and this request is again given through you Chairperson to the Secretariat.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.413-->
                    <paragraph id="3.413">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It seems the credibility of the Organization, which is on the edge, is not a concern for many who continue to stonewall permanent solutions to the PSH. In this regard, we wish to mention two points.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.414-->
                    <paragraph id="3.414">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, one is the clear message our Senior Official delivered in the SOM. (i) We would like to put on record the Facilitator report on agriculture, particularly paragraph 3 thereof. We hope the Members who object to achieving the Permanent Solution to PSH as per the mandate realise that they are primarily responsible for not achieving any meaningful reforms in agriculture. The harder they resist the permanent solution to PSH, the longer it will take to initiate the rest of the agriculture reforms.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.415-->
                    <paragraph id="3.415">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>(ii) We also heard a number of delegates speak on the food security decision or package. We want to make it very clear that we would not like to have something like in the past Ministerials where we have declarations and decisions, but it does not add a single grain to vulnerable populations. We should resist talking in the name of transparency or trade facilitation while forgetting about the concrete measures. We had two decisions on food in MC12. So far, they have not added an additional morsel of grain to the needs of the vulnerable populations and countries. Here we are yet again talking about yet another declaration on Food Security uninhibited.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.416-->
                    <paragraph id="3.416">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>(iii) For India, there cannot be a decision on Food Security without a permanent solution to the PSH. Hence, we have suggested starting with JOB/AG/229 on a permanent solution for public stockholding, a joint proposal of three large groups accounting for more than 80 Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.417-->
                    <paragraph id="3.417">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>(iv) Some Members have said that PSH is one of the solutions to ensure food security and is not the only solution. We agree. In this regard, we have two points to mention.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.418-->
                    <paragraph id="3.418">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>One, we never said it was the only solution. We have also acknowledged some other views that state free trade can also play some role in rendering food security, though its impact is minimal. The FAO reports have clearly shown that only 17 per cent of the world's food is traded across borders. Further, during the pandemic time, free trade in agriculture or the so-called agriculture-producing countries failed to rise to the occasion when required. So, according to us, the argument that free trade ensures food security fell flat and square on its face during the past COVID-19 pandemic. On the other hand, the PSH programme of India remained resilient and provided for 800 million people for more than 18 months.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.419-->
                    <paragraph id="3.419">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, food security is a non-trade issue, and WTO, with its limited reach of 17 per cent, cannot provide a solution to the global food security needs. Hence, it is only prudent that Members recognize this reality and let the permanent solution to PSH be delivered at the MC13; that is the only way to make progress in the otherwise stalemated Agriculture negotiations in the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.420</statement_number>
