                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>3.424</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Paraguay delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.425-->
                    <paragraph id="3.425">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I will be brief and limit my response to simply stating that my delegation expects the implementation of all Ministerial mandates, as well as the international legal obligations under Article 20 of the Agreement on Agriculture. Under this Article, all Members have committed to the substantial and progressive reduction of distortion and protection in trade in agricultural products. The negotiating process, which began in 2000 and was incorporated as a central component of the Doha Round in 2001, should have been concluded in January 2005.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.426-->
                    <paragraph id="3.426">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We understand the frustration of some Members, who are impatient to conclude mandates that should have been fulfilled in 2017. At the same time, we hope that they can understand the frustration and impatience of delegations like ours that have been waiting for the conclusion of mandates that were supposed to be completed not six, but 18 years ago. We hope that we can all work together with steadfast political determination to concurrently fulfil all these mandates through holistic and targeted reform.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.427-->
                    <paragraph id="3.427">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The representative of Indonesia provided the following statement:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.428-->
                    <paragraph id="3.428">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My delegation continues to regret lack of progress in resolving outstanding mandates from previous Ministerial Conferences – including to agree on a permanent solution on PSH for food security purposes. All Ministerial mandates must be respected. This is key to restoring trust that is severely lacking in agriculture trade negotiation – and preserving the integrity of the Ministerial Conference. Agreeing on a permanent solution is even more important now at the time of food crisis – and we need a PSH that cover all future programmes for food security purposes.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.429-->
                    <paragraph id="3.429">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The G33, the African Group, and the ACP have put together a comprehensive joint proposal JOB/AG/229 – which we believe constitute a solid basis for a text-based negotiation on PSH for food security purposes. We categorically reject attempts to frame the discussion on PSH for food security purposes exclusively within the confine of domestic subsidies. They are not only misguided, but also demonstrate total disregard for food security challenges faced by developing country members, including LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.430-->
                    <paragraph id="3.430">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Now, on fisheries subsidies. We appreciate the efforts to put the CBDR principle in practice through the two-tier approach, as the Chair stated in his report at the TNC meeting. However, it is important that we agree on the parameter first. Second, it is important to tighten the discipline for those in the stricter tier, not just by way of adding notification obligation, but also through additional responsibility to change the status quo. Reducing the capacity of large-scale fishing vessels and/or distant water fishing vessels is one example. On the SDT, it is unfortunate that the objective for this discipline is to ensure that the less members that can access the flexibility under the provision, the better. That is not what effective and appropriate SDT is.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.431-->
                    <paragraph id="3.431">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Indonesia's position is well known in that SDT should not come with a geographical limitation, transition period or de minimis. However, we do understand that developing Members and LDCS are not a monolith. We all have different situations that informs our needs and interests. Thus, the SDT provisions should be able to capture these interests to provide us with necessary policy space to develop our fishing sectors in a sustainable manner.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.432-->
                    <paragraph id="3.432">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On DS reform, in terms of substance, Indonesia's first and foremost interest is the revival of two-tier dispute settlement system. And having heard some Members stating that it might not return to provide security and predictability to the multilateral trading system, is concerning, to say the least. We are also concerned that while Members' due process rights are further limited, there is an ongoing effort to provide unlimited transparency to the general public on the ongoing disputes that may interfere with the cases and jeopardize disputing Members with the limited capacity.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.433-->
                    <paragraph id="3.433">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In terms of process, Indonesia relentlessly asks for the discussion to be formalized to keep the capital abreast on the fast pace of the negotiation as well as to ease the burden of small delegations, like Indonesia. However, where request to have interpretation service is provided, the same request to have an online presence of capital delegation due to clashing schedule is continued being denied, without offering any solution. Instead, we are asked in return to request the other formal negotiating body to change their schedule, because, and I quote "we have decided the date earlier". If there is a "good will", there will be a "good way". And this, is not the way.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 3.434-->
                    <paragraph id="3.434">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council took note of the Chairperson's report, the statement of the Director-General and the statements made.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
            </statements>
        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>4</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>WORK PROGRAMME ON SMALL ECONOMIES – REPORT BY THE CHAIRPERSON OF THE DEDICATED SESSION OF THE COMMITTEE ON TRADE AND DEVELOPMENT (WT/COMTD/SE/12)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 4.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson noted that in accordance with the agreement in the General Council in 2002, the Work Programme on Small Economies was a standing item on the agenda and the Committee on Trade and Development reported regularly on the progress of work in its Dedicated Sessions. She recalled that, at MC12, Ministers had reaffirmed their commitment to the Work Programme and instructed the CTD to continue its work in Dedicated Sessions under the overall responsibility of the General Council. She then invited Ambassador José Sánchez-Fung of the Dominican Republic, Chairperson of the CTD, to take the floor to provide the General Council with an update of the ongoing work in the Committee.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>4.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>Ambassador José Sánchez-Fung (Dominican Republic), Chairperson of the Committee on Trade and Development, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.3-->
                    <paragraph id="4.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I am pleased to introduce the report of the CTD's Dedicated Session on Small Economies to the General Council, which is contained in document WT/COMTD/SE/12. It has been prepared in line with the established practice for the Dedicated Session to submit a written report to the General Council in the lead-up to a WTO Ministerial Conference.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.4-->
                    <paragraph id="4.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In addition to an introductory part, the report has two main sections. The first of these sections, titled "Submissions and Proceedings", provides an overview of the work undertaken in the Dedicated Session since the last Ministerial Conference – MC12 – held in June 2022.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.5-->
                    <paragraph id="4.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>To briefly summarize the content of this section, let me say that three formal meetings of the CTD in Dedicated Session have been held since MC12.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.6-->
                    <paragraph id="4.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In line with the instructions given by Ministers in the MC12 Ministerial Decision on the Work Programme on Small Economies, the first two of these meetings focused on the topic of "integrating small economies into the post COVID-19 economy: effects of the pandemic, challenges and opportunities".</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.7-->
                    <paragraph id="4.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the meeting held on 30 March 2023, discussions took place on the basis of a background note prepared by the Secretariat on this topic. At the subsequent meeting held on 19 October, discussions focused on the challenges and opportunities for small economies in the post COVID-19 recovery phase. Presentations were made by the Commonwealth Secretariat, the South Centre, the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development and the World Bank. Presentations were also made by three members of the SVE Group: Ecuador, El Salvador and Sri Lanka.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.8-->
                    <paragraph id="4.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the most recent meeting of the Dedicated Session, discussions took place on 16 November, and at a reconvened meeting on 24 November, on proposed texts submitted by Guatemala on behalf of the SVE Group for a Ministerial Decision at MC13 on the Work Programme on Small Economies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.9-->
                    <paragraph id="4.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I am pleased to inform you that, at a further reconvened meeting on the 1st of December, the Dedicated Session agreed to the proposed text contained in document WT/COMTD/SE/W/46/Rev.2.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.10-->
                    <paragraph id="4.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In line with past practice, the Dedicated Session also agreed to reflect this text in the other main section of the report – the section titled "Future Work" – in the form of recommendations or proposals to the General Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.11-->
                    <paragraph id="4.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>These include, inter alia, the proposal that the General Council recommend to the Thirteenth Ministerial Conference that Ministers reaffirm their commitment to the Work Programme on Small Economies and take note of all the work conducted to date; and that, through cooperation with relevant international organizations, work be undertaken specifically on the following three issues:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.12-->
                    <paragraph id="4.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The CTD in Dedicated Session would continue monitoring the progress of the small economy proposals in WTO bodies and in negotiating groups with the aim of providing responses, as soon as possible, to the trade-related issues identified for the fuller integration of SVEs in the multilateral trading system, as well as assessing the effectiveness of the responses framed so far to integrate the SVEs in the multilateral trading system.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.13-->
                    <paragraph id="4.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In short, the recommendation of the CTD's Dedicated Session on Small Economies to the General Council is that the proposed text for a Ministerial Decision on the Work Programme on Small Economies, as contained in document WT/COMTD/SE/W/46/Rev.2, be transmitted to Ministers for adoption at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>4.14</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Guatemala, on behalf of the SVEs, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.15-->
                    <paragraph id="4.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On behalf of the SVE Group, the Small Economies Group would like to thank the Chairman of the Committee on Trade and Development, for his report on the progress of the work of our Dedicated Sessions. As a follow-up to our report at the last General Council, we would like to report that the Members worked on a proposal for a Ministerial decision for MC13 and after much deliberation, I am pleased to report that consensus was reached on this proposal.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.16-->
                    <paragraph id="4.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The proposal consists of continuing the work on the recommendations that were made in the instruction derived from MC12 on how to integrate small economies into the global economy post COVID-19. In this regard, the areas of work that were agreed upon were: Challenges and opportunities for small economies in using e-commerce and digital ecosystem to drive competitiveness; Addressing the importance of resilient, accessible, open, reliable and transparent supply chains for small economies given food security issues, and the impact of non-tariff measures on trade costs; Exploring with other relevant WTO bodies how to integrate trade related climate change adaptation and mitigation policies into the trade policies of small economies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.17-->
                    <paragraph id="4.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Finally, we would like to thank the other Members who supported the discussion of this proposal and who continue to support the work of small economies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>4.18</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Barbados, on behalf of CARICOM, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 4.19-->
