        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>6</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>TRIPS COUNCIL MATTERS</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 6.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that the item contained two sub-items and she proposed to take both items up together, and to open the floor only once. She recalled that, in August 2003, the General Council had adopted a Decision on the Implementation of Paragraph 6 of the Doha Declaration on the TRIPS Agreement and Public Health. She further noted that the General Council had also adopted, in December 2005, a Protocol amending the TRIPS Agreement. In accordance with Article X:3 of the WTO Agreement, the Protocol had entered into force on 23 January 2017, upon acceptance by two-thirds of the WTO Members. She recalled that both the amended TRIPS Agreement and the 2003 Decision provided that the TRIPS Council shall review annually the functioning of the system and shall also report on its operation to the General Council. She further recalled that the Members that were yet to accept the Protocol amending the TRIPS Agreement currently had until 31 December 2023 to do so. She then invited Ambassador Pimchanok Pitfield (Thailand), Chairperson of the Council for TRIPS, to report on these two matters.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>6.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>Ambassador Pimchanok Pitfield (Thailand), Chairperson of the Council for TRIPS, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.3-->
                    <paragraph id="6.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As you will recall, the Amendment to the TRIPS Agreement entered into force in January 2017. The amendment provides a special compulsory licensing system for the benefit of countries which rely on imports of medical technologies because of insufficient or no domestic pharmaceutical manufacturing capacities. It makes permanent the related rules already contained in the earlier waiver decision.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.4-->
                    <paragraph id="6.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At its meeting of 30-31 October, the TRIPS Council completed its annual review of the functioning of the System, pursuant to paragraph 7 of the amended TRIPS Agreement and paragraph 8 of the Decision of 30 August 2003 on the Implementation of Paragraph 6 of the Doha Declaration on the TRIPS Agreement and Public Health.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.5-->
                    <paragraph id="6.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The TRIPS Council's report on this review to the General Council has been circulated in document IP/C/97, which is Sub-item A of this Agenda Item. It includes information about the implementation and use of the System, as well as on the status of acceptances of the Protocol Amending the TRIPS Agreement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.6-->
                    <paragraph id="6.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Pursuant to the General Council's decision in 2021, the Protocol is open for acceptance by the remaining Members until 31 December 2023 or such later date as may be decided by the Ministerial Conference (WT/L/1122). Despite indications that a number of Members are making domestic efforts in this regard, there are still 27 WTO Members that are yet to accept the Protocol. The TRIPS Council, therefore, agreed to propose to the General Council a decision to extend the period for acceptance by two more years, i.e., until 31 December 2025. This proposal is set out in document IP/C/96, which is Sub-item B of this Agenda Item. On behalf of the TRIPS Council, I am submitting this to the General Council for a decision today.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.7-->
                    <paragraph id="6.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Before I conclude, I would like to call upon those Members who have yet to accept the Protocol to expedite action. A practical guide on how to do so is also available on the WTO's webpage on TRIPS and public health. Me and the Secretariat team, as always, will be happy to provide further assistance if necessary.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>6.8</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Colombia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.9-->
                    <paragraph id="6.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to take the floor briefly to say that the report submitted has left me with a sense of unease. Indeed, we see once again how the amendment to the TRIPS Agreement establishing Article 31bis and thereby the special compulsory licensing mechanism, has not worked as it should. Despite the considerable efforts of the Secretariat and certain countries, the mechanism has not actually been used, and its practical impact is far from striking the desired balance identified when discussions began in 2001.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.10-->
                    <paragraph id="6.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to point out that the same thing seems to be happening with the waiver agreed upon at MC12. The waiver has not been used once, and its practical impact is far from striking the desired balance identified when discussions began in 2020. When we broaden the waiver, it will likely lead to an increase in its use – and we will discuss this tomorrow – but as things stand, the fact is that it has not been used. The problem is that when we agreed on these flexibilities, we ladened them with so many requirements and conditions that we made them unfeasible in practice. While the solutions have proved ineffective, the problem remains.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.11-->
                    <paragraph id="6.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Both initiatives sought to resolve the rigidity of export and import requirements for a number of countries. The most important part of the special mechanism under Article 31bis and of the COVID-19 waiver revolves around Article 31(f) of the TRIPS Agreement, in other words around the artificial restriction on export markets imposed by this requirement. With this requirement, the WTO went far beyond what was established for unauthorized uses in the WIPO Agreements.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.12-->
                    <paragraph id="6.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The decisions we reached in the past acknowledged this problem. But the solutions we offered have not worked as they should, and the problem is far from being resolved. It has been and will be repeated. The Article 31(f) limitation is and will be a restriction that is unfair and too strict for two groups of developing countries that cannot make proper use of the counterbalances under the TRIPS Agreement - countries that are net importers (limited by the lack of local manufacturing) and sandwich countries (limited by their naturally small market size).</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.13-->
                    <paragraph id="6.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With this in mind, I would like to call for an in-depth review of this restriction in the medium term. In light of the unsuccessful experiences we have accumulated, such as the one being reviewed under this agenda item today, we should recognize that this is a key issue that we must address together and that we cannot weigh it down with new requirements, annexes, appendices and footnotes that would eventually make the solution unworkable. To restore the balance established in the TRIPS Agreement, we need to find a relevant, comprehensive solution to the problem clearly outlined in this report.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>6.14</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nigeria delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.15-->
                    <paragraph id="6.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Nigeria recognizes the difficulty faced by some Members that are still undertaking domestic processes required to accept the Protocol amending the TRIPS Agreement, as well as to deposit the Instrument of Acceptance. We note that this process is taking longer than expected, we therefore welcome the decision in document IP/C/96.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.16-->
                    <paragraph id="6.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson said that as reported by the TRIPS Council Chairperson, this draft decision was before the Council for action, and she proposed that the General Council take note of the report of the TRIPS Council in document IP/C/97 and adopt the draft decision in document IP/C/96 extending the time period for acceptance by Members of the Protocol amending the TRIPS Agreement until 31 December 2025.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 6.17-->
                    <paragraph id="6.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council so agreed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
            </statements>
        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>7</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>COMMITTEE ON BUDGET, FINANCE AND ADMINISTRATION – REPORTS ON MEETINGS OF 17 OCTOBER (WT/BFA/216) AND 22 NOVEMBER 2023 (WT/BFA/217)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 7.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson drew Members' attention to the reports of the Committee on Budget, Finance and Administration, in documents WT/BFA/216 and WT/BFA/217, and invited Ambassador Bettina Waldmann (Germany), Chairperson of the CBFA, to introduce them.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>Ambassador Bettina Waldmann (Germany), Chairperson of the Committee on Budget, Finance and Administration, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.3-->
                    <paragraph id="7.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Since my last report to the General Council, the CBFA has met on several occasions, both in formal and informal mode. I would like to present to you the CBFA reports for formal meetings of the Committee that took place in October and November.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.4-->
                    <paragraph id="7.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In particular, my remarks today will focus on the meeting of the CBFA held on 22 November 2023, which continued and concluded on 12 December. The report of that meeting can be found in document WT/BFA/217.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.5-->
                    <paragraph id="7.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Following constructive and solutions-oriented discussions over several months, the Secretariat circulated a document entitled "Updated Secretariat WTO 2024-2025 Budget Proposal and Disposition of the 2021 Budget Surplus". That document is dated 29 November 2023 and bears the reference WT/BFA/W/659/Corr.1.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.6-->
                    <paragraph id="7.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the continuation of the 22 November formal meeting of the CBFA on 12 December, there was widespread consensus among almost all Members with regard to the following elements of the budget compromise:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.7-->
                    <paragraph id="7.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Members were also in agreement that the proposed increase of an additional 0.9 per cent for 2025 (the second year of the biennium) can be put aside for now and discussed in the context of a possible mid-term review in 2024.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.8-->
                    <paragraph id="7.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Moreover, there was strong support by most Members to endorse the recommendation by the WTO Pension Management Board regarding the closing of the funding gap and to establish a Working Group to examine the question of deeper pension reform. There was also broad agreement that action must be taken to address the funding gap in the near term, and not in the much longer period of time that would be required to consider deeper structural changes to the Pension Plan.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.9-->
                    <paragraph id="7.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>However, three Members were not yet ready to endorse the recommendation by the Management Board. The Committee therefore deferred the matter for now and decided to revert to it in early 2024.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.10-->
                    <paragraph id="7.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Personally, I believe that it is unfortunate that we were not able to take a decision regarding the immediate question of the Pension Plan funding gap, while simultaneously establishing a Working Group to examine and, if appropriate, propose longer term structural reform of the WTOPP. Staff and retirees deserve a stable pension, so we must return to close the funding gap quickly.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.11-->
                    <paragraph id="7.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>That said, the recommendations in relation to which there was widespread consensus can be found in paragraph 3.14 of the CBFA report contained in document WT/BFA/217. They foresee that:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.12-->
                    <paragraph id="7.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As to the budget compromise, one Member indicated that it still needed some time to consult with its capital and thus was not able at the time of the CBFA meeting held on 12 December to join all others in endorsing the recommendations contained in document WT/BFA/217, for approval by the General Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.13-->
                    <paragraph id="7.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In my capacity as CBFA Chair, I am therefore communicating these recommendations to the General Council for appropriate action.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.14-->
                    <paragraph id="7.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson thanked the CBFA Chair for her report. She noted that there were some positive developments to report. She had been informed that that Member that could previously not join consensus at the CBFA meeting, was now in a position to do so.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.15</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chinese Taipei delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.16-->
                    <paragraph id="7.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We have seen the CBFA Chair and the Secretariat working hard with Members on hammering out a viable budgetary suggestion for 2024-2025 to ensure WTO's smooth operation. We will be ready to join the consensus to support the budget proposal notwithstanding that we made a number of comments at the CBFA meetings. We look forward to the WTO's continued efficient and transparent operations.</t>
