                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.18</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Switzerland delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.19-->
                    <paragraph id="7.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Switzerland would like to thank the Chair of the CBFA for her report and the hard work she has put, together with the Secretariat and delegations, into this process. The compromise found for which we could establish consensus is not the optimal solution in our view, as we would have been ready to accept the DG's initial budget proposal. It is about securing the resources enabling the Secretariat to deliver high quality services as requested by Members. But we understand the budgetary constraints and caution of many Members. In that sense, the solution found represents a reasonable and responsible compromise. We already now invite all Members to carefully examine the Secretariat's resource situation at the next Mid-Term Review, upcoming before the end of 2024.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.20-->
                    <paragraph id="7.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Regarding the Pension Plan, we find it regrettable that very few Members could not join the consensus regarding the Reform. We are in favour of establishing a Working Group to examine a more fundamental reform of the Pension Plan, but this is a complex issue and will take time. At the same time, there is a clear cost of waiting to fill the actuarial gap in the Pension Plan which is currently increasing steadily. We urge Members to address the situation in early 2024 in the CBFA in order to agree on a timely solution before examining the possibilities of a more fundamental reform.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.21</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nigeria delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.22-->
                    <paragraph id="7.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My intervention is just on call to the WTO membership. We have been talking in this house on the need to support the Secretariat to be more productive. We also have been talking among ourselves on the need to enhance processes – even on negotiations, we have established that trust has been a challenge, and because of that we have not been reaching convergence in most of the issues. In recent times, we observed certain things that needed to be improved in the WTO. With the efficient leadership presently, they have come up with solutions through which these challenges to Secretariat will be addressed. So, the issue of additional requests for funding was presented before Members, and we met several times. We made observations. The Secretariat went back and responded to those questions, and I feel that in terms of budgeting, it really should not be an issue. Our target on the Secretariat is much, and to get those results, then we have to support them with their budget request. I urge those Members who still have concern to reflect and change their mind, so that we can immediately approve the support and request by WTO, so that they can give us the best that we want.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.23</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Singapore delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.24-->
                    <paragraph id="7.24">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Singapore is pleased that following the extensive and thorough discussion on the WTO 2024-2025 biennium budget, the CBFA is now able to present a budget proposal to the GC. As noted in WT/BFA/218, the CBFA met a total of thirteen times since July 2023 to discuss the budget, which gives Members a good sense of the importance of this matter. Allow me to make three brief points.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.25-->
                    <paragraph id="7.25">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, when the Director-General first presented her budget proposal in July 2023, Singapore stated clearly that we were prepared to positively consider it for three reasons. One, Singapore's consistent position is that if Members want to ensure that the WTO is fit for purpose, it has to be equipped with the necessary resources. Two, Singapore is satisfied that the Secretariat has been prudent and transparent in its management of the budget. In fact, the Secretariat conducted five informal technical sessions to address various issues, including HR policies, staffing considerations, and travel expenditure. Three, Singapore is of the view that the budget proposal has taken into account Members' sensitivities and budgetary challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.26-->
                    <paragraph id="7.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, Singapore can join the consensus on the recommendations contained in WT/BFA/217 even though it is sub-optimal. The 3.6 per cent increase and the use of CHF 2m from the 2021 surplus will allow the Secretariat to respond to key pressure points such as inflation and non-recurring expenditures.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.27-->
                    <paragraph id="7.27">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Third, we should seriously examine how we can better manage the budget approval process and avoid such a last-minute scramble. It would also be helpful to begin consultations on the next mid-term budget review discussion and take into account DG Ngozi's report during the TNC on 12 December 2023 concerning the Secretariat's transformation process and strategic vision.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.28</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Indonesia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.29-->
                    <paragraph id="7.29">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to express my appreciation the CBFA Chair, the Director-General, and her team for their tireless efforts and communication on budgetary matters. Indeed, we understand the difficulties faced by the Secretariat in managing the budget in the current challenging economic conditions. Therefore, we appreciate the efforts made by the Secretariat to streamline its operations and reduce costs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.30-->
                    <paragraph id="7.30">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In addition, we support the immediate establishment of a Working Group to monitor the Pension Fund and possibly other related issues as deemed necessary. This Working Group will provide Members with the opportunity to discuss these issues in more detail and develop recommendations to address them. We look forward to discussions on these issues early next year to address the challenges facing the Pension Fund.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.31</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Paraguay delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.32-->
                    <paragraph id="7.32">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Paraguay wishes to express its support for the proposal and the recommendations submitted.  We would like to commend the leadership of the CBFA Chair and DDG Ellard in finding pragmatic solutions with Members, including the information technology budgetary requirements requested to implement the "reform-by-doing" digital solutions, an initiative of which we are proponents. We appreciate the consensus emerging among Members, noting in particular the careful analysis of the elements set out in the recommendations. The proposal for a 3.6 per cent increase in the operational budget for 2024 and 2025 reflects our commitment to strengthen WTO operations. We also welcome the proposal regarding the use of the 2021 surplus, including returning CHF 4 million to Members, as a sign of responsible financial management. We trust that, with further discussion, the Pension Plan can reach a satisfactory consensus.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>7.33</statement_number>
                    <statement>The Director-General delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.34-->
                    <paragraph id="7.34">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to sincerely thank Members for approving a modest budget increase for the WTO. I want to thank all those who supported an even higher proposal and worked hard. I want to thank all of you that worked for the compromise, and finally got all Members around it. It is much appreciated. This is the Organization's first adjustment in the past 12 years of zero nominal growth. I am pleased that we have been successfully proving to you the need for this request, especially at a time that is hard for many of you. I appreciate your recognition of pressing inflationary and contractual obligations. This compromise brought together different groups of Members - those that wanted full increase of 7.4 per cent as I had originally requested, those who wanted something less than a full increase, and those that preferred to stay at zero nominal growth. In addition, the compromise will result in a credit of CHF 4 million against Members' 2024 contributions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.35-->
                    <paragraph id="7.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The compromise will help us do our job better for you. It shows that you Members care about this Organization, and that we do is useful for you and the people you represent. This is an important signal - especially as we prepare for MC13. That is why we fought so hard. This compromise shows that we can agree by consensus and deliver here in Geneva. It is also a vital show of support for our staff and will help with staff morale. I am grateful for this point, as we mentioned to you, or as I had said during my CBFA interventions, you may not know it, but staff morale was a serious issue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.36-->
                    <paragraph id="7.36">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I wish to thank the CBFA Chair for her tremendous effort and her commitment and the excellent work of the Committee. Thank you for the personal effort you put into it. I also wish to thank DDG Ellard and the Secretariat team for their hard work and dedication to this effort. Many people will not know the sleepless nights that went into this, maybe some of you have an idea that understand what it entails in revising a position so many times.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.37-->
                    <paragraph id="7.37">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to thank the Pension Management Board and its Chair for all the work done on how to address the funding gap in WTO's pension plan. Although most were ready to join consensus to adopt the Boards' recommendation and establish a working group to consider broader reform. As we heard, a few Members were not yet ready to join this consensus. As such, we will not be able to proceed on this matter today, and as the Chair said, we will defer it to next year. In the meantime, the gap continues to grow. Staff members and retirees deserve a stable predictable and well-functioning pension plan, it's a top priority to them and something they look at. As they work, they need to know that when they leave their future will be secured. Therefore, I am happy to hear that Members will revert to this matter early next year. This will give staff some hope. I look forward to doing all we can to work with Members, so that the pension matter can be settled as quickly, and the working group is established to get some results. I wish to thank all Members once more for making this gesture. It's a good Christmas gesture.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.38-->
                    <paragraph id="7.38">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Chairperson then invited the General Council to take note of Ambassador Waldmann's statement and the other statements made; approve the Budget Committee's specific recommendations in paragraph 3.14 of the report in WT/BFA/217; and adopt the reports contained in WT/BFA/216 and WT/BFA/217.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 7.39-->
                    <paragraph id="7.39">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council so agreed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
