                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>9.74</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Angola delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 9.75-->
                    <paragraph id="9.75">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Angola continues to fully support the revised document WT/GC/W/807/Rev.2 proposed by the LDC Group urging WTO Members to enable future graduated countries to continue to benefit from the flexibilities currently enjoyed by LDCs, ensuring a smooth transition and a sustainable exit from the category. This debate started in the General Council gathered on 16-17 December 2020, continued in October 2021 GC, and received a contextual uphold with the MC12 ministerial declaration on LDCs preferential rules of origin, services waiver, duty-free quota-free market access, and positive actions regarding graduation from the LDC category. On this path, Angola is particularly pleased that the General Council could adopt the important decision WT/L/1172 on the Annex-1 or DFQF, thus recognizing the critical gravity of a congruent and smooth transitional period for countries graduating from the LDC category.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 9.76-->
                    <paragraph id="9.76">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Allow us to recall again the regrettable situation with which countries like Angola were suddenly confronted since we should have already graduated in 2021 and then postponed to 2024 due to the irruption of the global COVID-19 pandemic crisis. The postponement of this long waiting graduation process had several negative consequences, eroding economic confidence, favorable access to capital, investment, loans, and trade markets, thus contradicting the political and social mobilization of Angolan public and civil organizations who fought several years for graduation from the LDC category as a just reward for their efforts in work, reforms and modernization of the country. Moreover, removing the LDCs from subdevelopment, economic crisis, and social poverty is not a mere national ambition but a global imperative that should be a permanent concern of the WTO. Angola reiterates that this is not a merciful agency but a critical global commitment towards sustainable world development. Consequently, Angola expects that the forthcoming MC13 will approve a formal declaration on a smooth and assisted transition from the LDC category for a pertinent period of time that includes exemption from action under the WTO dispute settlement mechanism, extension of guarantees of LDC-specific special flexibilities, and continuation of technical assistance as listed in the Appendix of Annex 2 to the present proposal.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 9.77-->
                    <paragraph id="9.77">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Finally, Angola fully supports that this General Council renew a formal mandate to instruct the LDC subcommittee to continue to formulate favourable recommendations for the smooth and assisted LDC graduation process by completing the Annex-2 provisions ahead of MC13, thus achieving a concrete draft proposal for the approval of the forthcoming Abu Dhabi Ministerial Conference.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
