        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>11</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>MC13 – IMMEDIATE STEPS TO RESPOND TO FOOD INSECURITY – COMMUNICATION FROM SINGAPORE (WT/GC/W/908)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 11.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that the item "MC13 – Immediate Steps to Respond to Food Insecurity" had been included in the agenda at the request of the delegation of Singapore – together with the communication in WT/GC/W/908.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Singapore delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.3-->
                    <paragraph id="11.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Over the course of the past few months, my delegation has been engaging with many Members on WT/GC/W/908. We have consulted widely, with both developed and developed Members, with various groups including the Cairns Group, G10, G33, ACP, Africa Group, LDCs, OECS, and Pacific Group. Based on the consultations, which were very useful, we have distilled what we gathered were the possible elements into the Communication that you see before you today. I will make three brief points.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.4-->
                    <paragraph id="11.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, let me share what this paper is not about. One, it is not intended to distract or detract from the critical discussions at CoA SS. Singapore recognizes the importance that many Members attach to the ongoing negotiations and will continue to support it. In fact, we have heard from many during our consultations, Members can walk and chew gum at the same time. Two, it is not meant to compete with other proposals at CoA SS. In fact, we have stated this clearly in Paragraph 8, which urges Members to consider in greater detail the relevant submissions submitted to date. Given the challenges in the CoA SS discussions, it is important that Members continue to consider all dimensions of food insecurity and the steps that we can take to address them. Three, this paper is certainly not meant to be a silver bullet to resolve all dimensions of the food insecurity challenges. Any such effort will certainly require all Members to work together to seek a win-win outcome.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.5-->
                    <paragraph id="11.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, let me share what this paper is about. One, it is a modest attempt to contribute to an MC13 outcome. It is a response to the almost unanimous emphasis that Members have placed on addressing the challenges of food insecurity. Two, this proposal is targeted at the short to medium term. In other words – what can we meaningfully do in the six working weeks that we have left to MC13? Three, this paper brings together elements that we see as realistic and credible, in areas such as export restrictions, added transparency, exemptions for LDCs and increased international collaboration.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.6-->
                    <paragraph id="11.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Third, let me share what this paper can be. One, this paper can be a stepping stone to build confidence and continue negotiations, after MC13. Two, it would send an important signal to the global community that our Ministers are able to collectively respond to the current and pressing challenges of food insecurity. Three, the proposals in this paper might be modest, but they are meaningful in making a difference to many food-insecure Members, particularly the LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.7-->
                    <paragraph id="11.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Singapore stands ready to engage in sincere, constructive, and pragmatic discussions on this important issue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.8</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon, on behalf of the African Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.9-->
                    <paragraph id="11.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe a medium and long-term solution to food security challenges can only be delivered through a MC13 outcome that include substantive food security and livelihoods package with decisions on issues under negotiations in the CoA SS such as PSH, and SSM, as well as outcome on domestic support especially with regards to levelling the playing field. These are the outcomes that are necessary for ensuring food security in developing countries and LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.10-->
                    <paragraph id="11.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe the Singapore proposal which is confined to issues of transparency and new disciplines on export restrictions cannot be part of a medium or long-term solution to food security challenges. The African Group holds this view for four important reasons. First, existing disciplines are sufficient and balanced to address export restrictions as well as to safeguard policy space when required to address essential food needs of Members in times of critical food shortages. Second, GATT Article XI and Article 12 of the AoA balance the obligation with the need. Any effort to increase obligations on removing export restrictions while not recognizing domestic needs to address food crisis will adversely affect this balance. Third, there is lack of hard evidence that freeing up exports will provide the needed solution to food crises and food security. Lastly, due to resource and capacity constraint, we are not in a position to undertake further transparency obligation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.11-->
                    <paragraph id="11.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In view of these, the African Group is not in a position to support this proposal. Works in the area of export restrictions if needed should be about how to ensure Members adhere to existing exports restrictions obligation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.12</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Fiji, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.13-->
                    <paragraph id="11.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We appreciate the communication from Singapore. We commend Singapore's leadership on this urgent issue which affects millions of people especially in LDCs and developing Members. Like many SIDS, Fiji faces multiple challenges in ensuring food security and nutrition for its population. Taking guidance from the FAO, food imports outweigh food production as source of many SIDS. We recall here Dr. Ngozi's call at G20 Summit in Bali last year to reduce or eliminate export restrictions, following also on the MC12 outcome.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.14-->
                    <paragraph id="11.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Fiji attaches great importance of fair and market-oriented agricultural trading system. Fiji commends the commitment of Singapore and others that any emergency measures introduced to address food security concerns are consistent with WTO provisions and that they are transparent, temporary, targeted and take into account the possible impact on other WTO Members. We look forward to action on this proposal for MC13, and that we demonstrate relevance and responsiveness to global food security challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.15</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Egypt delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.16-->
                    <paragraph id="11.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Egypt acknowledges the significance of promoting transparency in handling export prohibitions and restrictions. However, while transparency is crucial, it alone may not guarantee access of Least Developed Countries and Non-Food Importing Developing Countries to open international food markets to fulfill their basic food needs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.17-->
                    <paragraph id="11.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Additionally, there is a need for clarification on what would constitute essential foodstuffs and who would have the authority to determine this—whether it is the exporting or the importing country.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.18-->
                    <paragraph id="11.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Moreover, while the draft text acknowledges the multifaceted nature of food security, it lacks immediate steps to address vital elements crucial to food security. Instead, it defers the matter to future negotiations in the context of CoA SS. This approach overlooks existing proposals, such as the Public Stockholding (PSH) by the African Group and G33 (JOB/AG/229) and the de minimis section in the African Group proposal on domestic support (JOB/AG/242), which could provide immediate solutions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.19-->
                    <paragraph id="11.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The draft proposal does not mandate the expeditious and prioritized handling of these issues in negotiations. To ensure a comprehensive response to food insecurity, a concrete and credible decision in MC13 should encompass:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.20-->
                    <paragraph id="11.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Egypt asserts that the current draft falls short of addressing immediate and comprehensive food security needs. It lacks specificity on critical issues and does not prioritize existing proposals like PSH and de minimis. Egypt believes this document should not be the basis for discussions on food security.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.21</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Japan delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.22-->
                    <paragraph id="11.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We appreciate Singapore's proposal. In light of the current situation, it is important to demonstrate the WTO's commitment to addressing food insecurity at MC13. Supply chain disruptions particularly affected vulnerable countries, and it is important to ensure smooth trade in agricultural products as one of the factors that contributes to global food security and will complement each Member's domestic production.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.23-->
                    <paragraph id="11.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Japan sees value in Singapore's proposal and appreciates its initiative. We are aware of the ongoing discussions at the CoA SS on how to proceed with agricultural reform, including ensuring food security. Japan believes that all items, including issues addressed in this agenda, should be put on the table to pursue a comprehensive outcome, and we will continue to be engaged in the process.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.24</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the United States delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.25-->
                    <paragraph id="11.25">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We look forward to discussing this proposal in more detail. There are two other proposals at CoA SS on related issues. We hope that all the proponents, and us also, we are happy to join the conversation, that we can work together on the topic. Export restrictions have proven time and again to only exacerbate market volatility, often in direct conflict with their intended purpose. They also undermine the livelihoods of producers by reducing their incomes for their current production, creating a perverse incentive to not produce. We welcome the proposals and hopefully we can work together.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.26-->
                    <paragraph id="11.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We have heard multiple Members say that an outcome on export restriction is not viable on its own or is a distraction from more substantial outcomes. We urge these Members to stay constructively engaged on tangible outcomes that the WTO can deliver - an area that was requested by LDC Members for the WTO to take action. We hope we can engage constructively on this.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.27</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Tanzania delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.28-->
                    <paragraph id="11.28">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Food security remains a critical challenge for developing countries, especially LDCs and NFIDCs. We consider it a sensitive subject, which as a delegation we have often referred to as a national security matter. We believe that countries facing greater burden of food security should themselves decide on suitable solution for food security, and not have solutions superimposed from outside. Special safeguard mechanism, PSH and other domestic support measures can improve domestic food security particularly in NFIDCs and LDCs, if implemented carefully and responsibly. Further, we believe that any policy space provided under GATT Article XI.2 and AoA Article 12 may serve as an important instrument to avert risk of encountering critical shortages of food stuff. We also fully subscribe to the wisdom captured in AoA, which clearly states that food security is a non-trade concern. While we acknowledge that trade can help; food security should not be looked at from perspective from trade alone. It should rather consider the wider array of solution to food insecurity challenges. A call which we also heard a few days ago from Ministers during the Ministerial meeting. Finally, we align with statements of the African Group.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.29</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the Philippines delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.30-->
                    <paragraph id="11.30">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to thank Singapore for surfacing this proposal at the General Council, which complements ongoing work in the CoA SS, and attempts to mitigate against possible trade distorting measures that could affect the food security of net food importing countries. The Philippines does support a holistic outcome on agriculture at MC13 but we also remain pragmatic that we should be open to achieving tangible results in the near term.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.31-->
                    <paragraph id="11.31">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We do not believe that the issue of export restrictions is a key offensive or defensive interest of members in agricultural negotiations. We sense that the membership generally holds a similar perspective that it is a policy tool that must be used judiciously in only extreme and temporary situations. The Singapore proposal does contain key elements that help to reinforce the responsible use of export restrictions, such as on the notification and review of export prohibitions or restrictions, commitment to engage in consultations, and the key commitment to refrain from imposing export restrictions on essential foodstuffs for least-developed countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.32-->
                    <paragraph id="11.32">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We look forward to further engagement in delivering concrete food security related outcomes at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.33</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Ukraine delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.34-->
                    <paragraph id="11.34">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Ukraine welcomes the continued interest in export restrictions previously held within the framework of CoA SS. We thank Singapore for the contribution. Combatting the aggravated food insecurity crisis for almost two years, as a result of Russia's invasion, Ukraine recognizes importance of providing timely information on export restrictions. This will enable importing countries, particularly LDCs and NFIDCs to diversify supply chains to minimizes threats to national food security.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.35-->
                    <paragraph id="11.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Ukraine would also like to emphasize once again the importance of refraining from unnecessary export restrictions. In this regard, we welcome the ongoing collaborative work of like-minded Members in CoA SS, based on proposals from Japan, the LDC Group and United Kingdom. Before MC13, we should focus our joint efforts on achieving a balanced solution on agriculture. In this connection, we share Singapore's views on comprehensive and meaningful reform in agriculture with an emphasis on substantial progressive reduction of support and protection. For this reason, Ukraine looks forward discussing Singapore's proposal at upcoming CoA SS meeting.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.36</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.37-->
                    <paragraph id="11.37">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My following statement is for both items 11 and 13. China supports reaching food security outcomes for the vulnerable members at MC13. We commend Singapore and African Group's efforts in this regard. We see valuable elements from both papers which could constitute the potential elements of MC13 integrated food security outcome package. We believe food security outcomes could be achieved if we are working in a pragmatic way and we believe some recommendations from both proposals could constitute the potential elements of MC13 integrated food security outcome package. We hope members can engage with goodwill, show sincerity and move towards each other to explore practical food security outcomes in the next 2 months. For China, we reiterate that food security should be a part of MC13 deliverables. On export restriction, China commends Singapore's continuous efforts on responding to food insecurity after the remarkable WFP outcomes at MC12.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.38-->
                    <paragraph id="11.38">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe that the implementation of export prohibitions or restrictions in strict accordance with relevant WTO regulations is crucial to ensure the stability and reliability of the global agricultural trade supply chain. On the basis of implementing the MC12 Ministerial Declaration on food security, China supports improving the discipline of export restrictions in accordance with the current rules, so as to ensure that members can better fulfil the existing WTO obligations. However, the requirements beyond the existing rules need to be carefully studied and deliberated. China also stresses that the disciplines of export restrictions should take full account of the capacity and resource constraints of developing Members to ensure that the relevant discipline is practical for them.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.39</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the European Union delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.40-->
                    <paragraph id="11.40">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The European Union would like to thank Singapore for its communication and Ambassador Tan for the useful clarification in his statement. The food security challenges will remain at the top of our agenda in WTO. This is also natural considering a majority of WTO membership is developing countries. In that sense we see value in this proposal.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.41-->
                    <paragraph id="11.41">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>An outcome on food security at MC13 should be the immediate focus considering the current crisis and needs of many vulnerable countries. Elements of such outcome could include enhanced transparency on areas related to food security challenges (such as food aid, export restrictions) as well as clarifications of the rules on export restrictions which would limit their unjustified use. The proper functioning of the markets is essential so that supplies can reach those that need them most. Any measures, which restrict trade, must be limited to what is necessary and be strictly proportionate.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.42-->
                    <paragraph id="11.42">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>WTO rules allow export restrictions on food in the certain circumstances of threats to food security but we as WTO Members should do more on a commitment to avoid unjustified export restrictions and to take into account the impact on net food importing countries. Transparency and effective monitoring of export or restrictions are crucial for a predictable international trading environment and international food security. Moreover, sustainable food systems and resilient agricultural productions are part of the solution addressing the global food security challenges we are facing.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.43</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Ecuador delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.44-->
                    <paragraph id="11.44">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This contribution on food security addresses key areas such as transparency issues relating to notifications, and commitments among Members to minimize trade distortions and export prohibitions. Nevertheless, we note that it does not include other elements connected to food security that have been under discussion for months in the CoA SS. In today's world, we are facing a chronic problem - food insecurity. Unfortunately, there are few prospects for a rapid solution to this serious humanitarian and human rights challenge. Trade is not the only solution, as we were reminded a moment ago by the delegation of Tanzania, but it can and must be part of a solution.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.45-->
                    <paragraph id="11.45">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Political, economic and sustainable development discussions, including those concerning climate change, suggest the need for trade measures related to this issue that are not part of short- or medium-term solutions, but that contribute to long-term food security for all. Agricultural trade that is stable and free of distortions and barriers is, in the long term, the most effective response to address the problem of food security. Short-term solutions can only be effective if they form part of a wider process that would take place if the negotiations under Article 20 of the Agreement on Agriculture were implemented, covering all pillars of the negotiation in a comprehensive manner. We call for this proposal to be included in the discussions of the Committee on Agriculture. This contribution can play a positive role in these discussions and in a Committee where other food security-related proposals are also being taken into consideration.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.46</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the Russian Federation delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.47-->
                    <paragraph id="11.47">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On Singapore draft proposal. Addressing food security, we need to deal not only with the interests of net importers but with those of all other participants of the international trade, including the exporters. Moreover, we stand for a systemic and balanced approach to food security in all its dimensions, rather than deliberately and unjustifiably focusing on one element. We deem that global food security is based on joint efforts of Members and all the Members are interdependent on each other in this sense. We fully agree with the fact, outlined in the communication by Singapore that "high prices undermine food security and nutrition for all Members".</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.48-->
                    <paragraph id="11.48">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>But some provisions of this proposal seem to be not realistic. In particular, the commitment to refrain from imposing export prohibitions or restrictions on essential foodstuff imported by least-developed countries, even in circumstances set out in Article XI:2(a) of the GATT 1994, seems to be not elaborated enough. In particular, we find it not feasible in the situation of critical shortage of foodstuffs in any country to prevent it from protection of their population of famine. We shall add, that we have witnessed numerous instances when the measures imposed by certain WTO Members had a deteriorating effect on the exports of other Members. The concerns were consistently raised under the CoA review process.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.49-->
                    <paragraph id="11.49">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>So, we are certain that we need to tackle not only export restrictions per se but as well other measures having detrimental effect on food security. Any new modalities and further discussions should be based on this approach so to discipline their application in the same manner as export restrictions. We believe that the discussion of the ER in agriculture is incomplete without addressing unilateral economic measures that are a huge challenge and impediment to global food security, international trade and growth.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.50</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chinese Taipei delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.51-->
                    <paragraph id="11.51">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank Singapore for its proposal on the immediate steps to respond to food insecurity, which acknowledges the current global food insecurity and the way of addressing it. For the remaining limited weeks prior to MC13, it is desirable for Members to focus on addressing problems arising from a possible disruption of food supply chain caused by export restrictions, which lead to severe fluctuations in the domestic market of importing Members, particularly the net-food importing Members. This is the "minimum" element for food security issues to make a meaningful contribution to the world. Singapore's suggestion is in line with the idea of focusing on a possible achievable for MC13. We welcome further conversations on this matter to enhance transparency and other disciplines for export restrictions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
