                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.81-->
                    <paragraph id="11.81">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We are grateful to Singapore for its proposal. We find it instructive that the WTO Director-General's annual overview of developments in the international trading environment, presented on 7 December at a meeting of the Trade Policy Review Body, indicates that trade restrictions continue to weigh on global trade, with persistent export restrictions contributing to food price volatility. Added to this, the polycrisis environment lends greater weight to the pressing need for a discrete food security package at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.82-->
                    <paragraph id="11.82">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In the OECS, inflation, public debt and climate change represent the antecedents for food insecurity. Already, all OECS countries meet the majority of their food demands through external sources, reflecting a considerable level of reliance on food imports. Four out of six OECS countries are also considered to be moderately to severely food insecure.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.83-->
                    <paragraph id="11.83">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is in this context that we see the Singapore proposal as containing many elements which we find useful. However, we believe that any final outcome has to be sensitive to the needs and special circumstances of Net-Food-Importing-Developing-Countries (NFIDCs) and it is on this point that we believe that the proposal has not gone far enough. We stand ready to engage constructively with Singapore on this.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
