                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.101-->
                    <paragraph id="11.101">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Brazil does not identify export restrictions as the main cause of high prices, excessive volatility, trade disruption and food and nutrition insecurity. Unfortunately, a declaration along the lines proposed would not address those concerns. WTO solutions to global food insecurity are trade-related and require a holistic approach, involving all elements of agricultural liberalization, from domestic support to market access, and the creation of a productive and resilient food system.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.102-->
                    <paragraph id="11.102">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Evidence points to the positive contribution to global food security that would arise from reducing distortions and improving market access in agriculture, as per the fundamental principles of the WTO. We appreciate the initiative has been presented as a constructive effort, but it moves us away from the debate that can lead to a lasting solution. In this sense, it has the effect, though unintended, of a red herring. The focus solely on "export restriction" will not bring food to the table of those most in need.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.103</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Sri Lanka delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.104-->
                    <paragraph id="11.104">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Food Security is of highest priority for my country. It goes without saying that food insecurity is a multifaceted issue, which need to be addressed through holistic solutions. Even among NFIDCs and LDCs, we see vast diversity relating to challenges they face relating to food security. This was well reflected during our sixteen-month long engagement under the dedicated Work Programme established as the MC12 Food Insecurity Declaration. Members amply reflected on the lack of advanced technology, lack of finance, limited or no investment in R&amp;D, limited access to credit; and insurance systems. Due to all these challenges, agricultural productivity and production is very low in NFIDCs and LDCs. In this context, there is an urgent need to make the agrifood systems of NFIDCs and LDCs more efficient, inclusive resilient and sustainable. This can be achieved only through enhancing agricultural production and productivity of NFIDCs and LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.105-->
                    <paragraph id="11.105">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We need to take an array of measures towards this end, which may encompass technology transfer, long-term financial support, technical assistance and capacity building, etc. While we do not deny that trade is important for food security of any country, we wish to mention that the AoA has made it clear that food security is a non-trade concern. If we are serious in finding solutions to the food insecurity of NFIDCs and LDCs, we need to treat it as a non-trade issue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.106-->
                    <paragraph id="11.106">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Accordingly, our work at the WTO should aim at concrete measures that would provide long lasting solutions to the food insecurity of NFIDCs and LDCs. Such measures must take into consideration the specific needs and challenges of NFIDCs and LDCs. In this regard we reiterate our call for adopting measures to bolster the agricultural production and productivity of NFIDCs and LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.107</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.108-->
                    <paragraph id="11.108">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>India would like to thank the proponent for this agenda, though we would have preferred that this agenda could have come in CoA SS, like the proposals of the UK, Japan, and LDCs. But since it is there before us, let me comment on the proposal. So, first of all, let us understand that export restriction comes mostly in the supply-constrained scenario. And in the supply-constrained scenario, if you are not imposing the export restrictions, that means you are allowing your own people to be vulnerable to the supply-side shock.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.109-->
                    <paragraph id="11.109">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the same time, if you open up without any restriction or without any monitoring, it will lead to crowding out. This is exactly what happened in the first and second quarter of 2022. In the crisis, when India, which is not a traditional wheat-exporting country, saw a 400 per cent rise in the export of wheat. Incidentally, most of that wheat was going to one of the proponents of the removal of export restrictions. This wheat was not going to the bowl and plates of LDCs or NFIDCs, but it was going to the futures and options contractors and to those countries who can afford to have deep pockets to order more than their food requirement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.110-->
                    <paragraph id="11.110">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>So let me give you three scenarios in honor of the proponent. As part of the safety instructions on flights, in cases of low oxygen, passengers are asked to cover themselves first before assisting infants. It doesn't mean that the mother, the parent, or the adult passenger is not concerned about the well-being of the infant. But the instruction is that first, you wear your oxygen mask and then try to help others. So, export restriction is one such example.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.111-->
                    <paragraph id="11.111">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The second example is in the case of a car. If you don't allow the brake in a car, that means the car will never speed. So, the brake is not to reduce the speed, but it gives you freedom to accelerate. And if you remove that export restriction from the toolbox, which is available under GATT and AoA, it means you are not allowing trade to happen freely. In the absence of an export restriction tool, everyone will be too conservative to allow trade to happen.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.112-->
                    <paragraph id="11.112">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>And last but not least, we have seen in the previous agenda that in the name of duty-free quota, there is free access to big tech platforms, but we were saying that it is for the MSMEs of least developed countries and developing countries. In the same way, in the name of futures and option traders, we are saying it is for LDCs and NFIDCs, rather LDCs and NFIDC would get benefit in the case of export restriction if the G2G agreement can take place where due to availability of assured supply, affordable rate and transact serving available currency may help them.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.113</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the United Kingdom delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.114-->
                    <paragraph id="11.114">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The food security challenge is acute. The WTO has a clear role to play in responding to the food security crisis. This is an issue our Ministers are going to want to focus on when they reach Abu Dhabi, so it is right that we are considering what we can do here. That said there are live discussions happening in the CoA SS and we should continue discussing Singapore's ideas there. It is clear we have to progress negotiations towards a fair and market-oriented trading system, including on reducing trade-distorting support, which would be beneficial for food security globally.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.115-->
                    <paragraph id="11.115">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe the efforts and progress made this year in CoA SS ought to allow us to be more specific and ambitious in the details of what is possible than is currently contained in this proposal.   As part of this wider work in the CoA SS it is clear that we need to begin to tackle export restrictions.  The UK has put forward a proposal, alongside proposals by the LDC Group and Japan. We see complementarity between those ideas and as encouraged by the CoA SS Chair we are actively engaged on bringing together the key elements of all three proposals. We plan to bring our ideas back to the membership in January, and we want to work with all Members, including Singapore, on what might be possible.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.116-->
                    <paragraph id="11.116">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Tackling this issue needs to be part of a holistic outcome on agriculture at MC13. As we have said before, tackling export restrictions is not a substitute for progressing agriculture reform. There are high ambitions across the membership across all files on agriculture reform. We welcome and fully support the efforts by the CoA SS Chair to find a way through this challenging negotiation. As we said at TNC, let's now intensify discussions, including at HoD level, to ensure we deliver on Agriculture at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>11.117</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Singapore delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.118-->
                    <paragraph id="11.118">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank all Members who have provided the views on our communication. The points have been carefully noted. Let me just be brief and make three points.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.119-->
                    <paragraph id="11.119">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, it is evident that there is broad recognition that it is important for MC13 to address the global food security challenges. Food security is of universal concern to all Members and will benefit from a broader, more sincere and constructive conversation in the General Council. It does not help the conversation if we use spurious examples to back spurious arguments. I think Members would be better served if we come together and agree on the importance of delivering an outcome at MC13. As I have stated in my opening presentation, this Communication is not intended to be a silver bullet. We have six weeks left. We must be pragmatic, realistic, and try our best to deliver an outcome that will serve the systemic interests of the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.120-->
                    <paragraph id="11.120">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, I urge Members to avoid allowing the pursuit of the perfect to become an enemy of the good.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.121-->
                    <paragraph id="11.121">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Third, there is evidently a trust deficit which some Members had highlighted earlier; and this deep-seated mistrust among Members, underpins an unfounded fear that addressing Export Restrictions to ease pressing food insecurity challenges will result in other important issues being left unaddressed. This is a zero-sum mindset that will not allow us to make progress.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.122-->
                    <paragraph id="11.122">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Singapore will continue to work closely with Members to refine the proposal, and we welcome any constructive feedback.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 11.123-->
                    <paragraph id="11.123">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council took note of the statements.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
            </statements>
        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>12</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>PROPOSED MINISTERIAL DECLARATION FOR THE THIRTEENTH MINISTERIAL CONFERENCE: STRENGTHENING REGULATORY COOPERATION TO REDUCE TECHNICAL BARRIERS TO TRADE – COMMUNICATION FROM CAMEROON; CHINA; JORDAN; MACAO, CHINA; MYANMAR AND SEYCHELLES</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 12.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that the following item "Proposed Ministerial Declaration for the Thirteenth Ministerial Conference: Strengthening Regulatory Cooperation to Reduce Technical Barriers to Trade – Communication from Cameroon; China; Jordan; Macao, China; Myanmar and Seychelles" has been included in the agenda at the request of the delegation of China, on behalf of the co-sponsors.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>12.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.3-->
                    <paragraph id="12.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The draft Ministerial declaration prepared for this agenda item has been circulated in document WT/GC/W/915, which is currently co-sponsored by 41 Members. Early this morning, we received confirmation from Switzerland and Australia for joining us as new co-sponsors. Now there are 43. It is very encouraging, and we are more than happy to add more members' names to the proposal after this GC meeting. On behalf of all the co-sponsors, I would like to give a brief introduction to our proposal.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.4-->
                    <paragraph id="12.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, the purpose of this Ministerial Declaration is to highlight the importance of one aspect of WTO work that is sometimes overlooked. In the ministerial context, we are used to focusing on our negotiating agenda, but another important element of WTO's work is cooperation and dialogue that takes place in the regular Committees. In the regulatory area, this is of growing importance. Governments around the world are increasingly using regulations and standards to tackle some of the most pressing challenges of our time.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.5-->
                    <paragraph id="12.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Indeed, we, as WTO Members, need to cooperate more if we want to effectively tackle the challenges ahead of us. I am thinking of health matters, or the environment and climate change, and of the digital economy. Regulatory cooperation helps ensure that we together address these important challenges although our regulatory systems may sometimes be different. In doing so, we need to be transparent, we need to share good practices, we need to promote capacity building. And we need to strengthen cooperation at the multilateral level. This is what the declaration is about.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.6-->
                    <paragraph id="12.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, let me make some important clarifications about what this TBT Ministerial Declaration is not about. The declaration will not add to or detract from obligations or rights of members under the TBT Agreement. That is perhaps obvious, but I want to make it clear. The declaration intends to spotlight the importance and, indeed, the increasing relevance, of work on regulations that affect trade. It is remarkable that the TBT Agreement, now almost 30 years old – due to the constructive engagement of Members in its Committee - is still effective in addressing emerging global challenges faced by all of us today.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.7-->
                    <paragraph id="12.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We, the co-sponsors, seek to emphasize the importance of regulatory cooperation and transparency in reducing unnecessary barriers to trade, including with respect to crucial emerging regulatory issues such as the protection of the environment, the emergence of the digital economy and public health matters. We underscore the value of transparency and call for further enhancement of our digital tools, such as ePing and eAgenda. Finally, we emphasize the importance of technical assistance and capacity building on TBT matters.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.8-->
                    <paragraph id="12.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My third and last point, the TBT Ministerial Declaration will not create any new work streams for the TBT Committee. As I mentioned, the intention is to put a "ministerial spotlight" on the importance of regulatory cooperation at the multilateral level. The Declaration should push us to become more efficient. The substance of this work, of course, is left to the technical experts in the TBT Committee.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.9-->
                    <paragraph id="12.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Finally, as the Director-General said when speaking at the launch of "Trade Day" last week in Dubai, "We need to use every weapon in our arsenal to fight the climate crisis". International cooperation on regulatory matters in the context of the WTO's regular work is a powerful but less known tool in the WTO toolbox. It helps us bridge differences and avoid trade friction. We certainly need this today. It is time that this be recognized at the Ministerial level.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.10-->
                    <paragraph id="12.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>If adopted, the TBT declaration will be a good demonstration to all stakeholders that the WTO has the tools and capabilities to address new challenges, and also to demonstrate the political will of WTO members to address those challenges together. Let me stop here and invite my co-sponsors to share more insightful views on it.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>12.11</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.12-->
                    <paragraph id="12.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Cameroon wishes, in its capacity as co-sponsor, to express its support for the draft Ministerial declaration on strengthening regulatory cooperation to reduce technical barriers to trade, in view of the major importance of this matter within our National Development Strategy, particularly in relation to the development of our exports, import substitution and the reduction of our trade deficit.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.13-->
                    <paragraph id="12.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We acknowledge that the work of the WTO TBT Committee has been instrumental in advancing the implementation of the TBT Agreement and maintaining the TBT Agreement dynamic since 1995, particularly through the Triennial Review process.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.14-->
                    <paragraph id="12.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My delegation is of the view that the TBT Agreement provides a unique multilateral framework for regulatory cooperation that is essential to avoid and reduce unnecessary barriers to trade. We note, for example, that close regulatory cooperation among Members was fundamental in addressing the COVID-19 pandemic by facilitating trade through the reduction or suspension of unnecessary regulatory barriers, the use of international standards or the temporary recognition of multiple standards and the reduction of unnecessary costs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.15-->
                    <paragraph id="12.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>By following a constructive approach, we hope that a key step can be taken at MC13 to ensure that regulatory cooperation helps to avoid and reduce unnecessary barriers to trade; cooperation assists Members in meeting cross-border and global challenges, and builds confidence between trading partners through mutual understanding and dialogue; cooperation contributes to the development of effective and efficient technical regulations and avoids regulatory differences and unnecessary divergence.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>12.16</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Antigua and Barbuda, on behalf of the OECS, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 12.17-->
                    <paragraph id="12.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Technical regulation, standards and conformity assessment procedures can often be barriers to global trade. Developing countries that lack sophisticated systems to comply with TBT requirements can find themselves locked out of important markets. In this regard, we see a role for regulatory cooperation, exchange of information, transparency, predictability and technical assistance and capacity building and international recognition arrangements for accreditation. The proposal from the co-sponsors takes us in the right direction. We hope it will form the basis of a credible Ministerial declaration at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>12.18</statement_number>
