        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>13</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>DRAFT MINISTERIAL DECISION ON PROMOTING AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTION AND TRADE IN NFIDCS AND LDCS - REQUEST FROM THE AFRICAN GROUP</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 13.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson invited the delegation of Cameroon to introduce, on behalf of the African Group, the item "Draft Ministerial Decision on Promoting Agricultural Production and Trade in NFIDCs and LDCs".</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon, on behalf of the African Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.3-->
                    <paragraph id="13.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank you for availing us this opportunity to present our proposed Draft Ministerial Decision on Promoting Agricultural Production and Trade in NFIDCs And LDCs. As we speak, Africa, and some Developing Countries are on the throes of a food crisis not seen before in recent times. Food insecurity is higher for developing countries, especially NFIDCs and LDCs, as they are unable to provide enough support to develop their agricultural sector, given the unfair WTO rules that constrain their policy space. Furthermore, they also do not have enough financial resources to import food from a concentrated and volatile global market. We believe in the context of the persistent state of global food insecurity that has disproportionately impacted NFIDCs and LDCs, it is of critical importance that MC13 delivers credible outcome that would avail NFIDCs and LDCs policy space needed to strengthen domestic production and enhance their participation in global trade.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.4-->
                    <paragraph id="13.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The African Group Proposal has five elements that seeks to enhance LDCs and NFIDCs agriculture production and productivity; accessibility to food markets: access to finance for imports and enhancement of production; the productive capacity as well as transparency of Food Aid programmes and Export credit, guarantee and insurance initiatives. The first element centered to policy space that would enable NFIDCs and LDCs to provide AMS support for basic food stuff in excess of their applicable de-minimis limit in situations where they are net importers with imports accounting for greater than 45 per cent of domestic net food availability, in each year of the immediately preceding five calendar year period for which data is available; or in situation of food crisis when, for a month where the average monthly import price for that product exceeds a trigger price of 130% of the base period defined in the proposal. LDCs and NFIDC would revert to applicable de-minimis level when the situations that necessitated them to exceed their applicable de-minimis level improves or ceases to exist.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.5-->
                    <paragraph id="13.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The second element which borders on enhancing accessibility to food markets centres on how to lessen the effects of Export Restrictions on LDCs and NFIDCs importers. It also contains a reaffirmation by Members to provide international food aid to LDCs and NFIDCs. Furthermore, it seeks to clarify the rules on repayment term in case of exceptional circumstances under para. 17 of the Nairobi Decision on Export Competition by proposing a 54- and 72-months extension of the time frame. The proposal also seeks to extend the benefits under Article 9.4 of the Agreement on Agriculture in respect of the export subsidies to 2050 for LDCs and NFIDCs as against the 2030 deadline enshrined in paragraph 8 of the Nairobi decision.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.6-->
                    <paragraph id="13.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The third element centered on international compensatory financing mechanism to finance normal levels of commercial imports of basic foodstuffs by LDCs and NFIDCs while the fourth is on enhancing transparency regarding food aid and export credit, guarantee, and insurance initiatives. The fifth element centered on fostering WTO partnership with relevant international and regional organizations to explore funding mechanism to improve the agricultural productive capacities, infrastructure, and access to agricultural inputs of NFIDCs and LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.7-->
                    <paragraph id="13.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This proposal contains decisions on constructive measures that would strengthen domestic production and faster access to basic food stuff for NFIDCs and LDCs. In our view, the decisions contained therein are part of the solution to the food insecurity situations in LDCs and NFIDCs. The proposal is without prejudice to other flexibilities identified through the work conducted in the Special Committee set up under the mandate of paragraphs 8 and 9 of the "Ministerial Declaration on Emergency Responses to Food Insecurity" on which negotiations with the objective to reach an outcome by MC14 are envisaged.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.8</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Djibouti, on behalf of the LDC Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.9-->
                    <paragraph id="13.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The agricultural potential of our countries is underutilized in particular because of technological constraints and the fact that the vast majority of our producers are small or semi-subsistence farmers who remain very vulnerable to external shocks. Indeed, agricultural production and the supply chain have been disrupted in recent years due to the COVID-19 pandemic and more recently the food and energy crises associated with the conflict in Ukraine. The periods of soaring prices that we have experienced intermittently since 2007 have also enormously weakened our economies. Now the major challenge for LDCs is to improve domestic agricultural production to build resilience and long-term preparedness against future crises and other supply chain disruptions, while ensuring product availability and affordability of basic foods, at affordable prices to meet our food security needs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.10-->
                    <paragraph id="13.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Against this background, we urge Members to consider positively our draft decision contained in document JOB/AG/251 as well requesting that countries net exporters of the food product affected by an export prohibition or restriction measure refrain from applying this measure to LDCs and NFIDCs importing such products for their domestic consumption needs.  We also support a permanent solution on public stockholding covering future programmes for LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.11</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Egypt delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.12-->
                    <paragraph id="13.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to express our strong support and commendation for the proposal submitted by the African Group aimed at promoting agricultural production and trade in Net Food Importing Developing Countries (NFIDCs) and Least Developed Countries (LDCs). This proposal, as articulated in the draft ministerial decision, is a crucial step towards addressing the pressing issue of food insecurity faced by many vulnerable countries, particularly those heavily reliant on food imports.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.13-->
                    <paragraph id="13.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The significance of this proposal lies in its timely response to the growing challenges posed by global crises, including the COVID-19 pandemic and geopolitical instability, which have exacerbated food insecurity, especially for NFIDCs and LDCs. The proposal recognizes the limitations of existing measures and underscores the need for practical solutions to bridge the gaps in efforts to meet the food needs of these countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.14-->
                    <paragraph id="13.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The African Group's proposal demonstrates a comprehensive understanding of the challenges faced by NFIDCs and LDCs in the context of agricultural reform, as undertaken under the mandate of the AoA. It acknowledges the specific vulnerabilities of these countries, particularly those with net imports accounting for a significant portion of domestic net food availability. The proposal tends to level the playing field between those who have serious challenges and limited flexibility and those who are significant producers and exporters and enjoy humongous flexibilities. The proposed decision reflects a balanced and pragmatic approach to enhancing food security.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.15-->
                    <paragraph id="13.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Furthermore, the recognition of the non-trade concern of food security is pivotal. Unfortunately, we were unable to reach a practical outcome following para 8 of the food insecurity decision's dedicated work Program. Therefore, we believe that this proposal aligns with the mandate outlined in the Ministerial Declaration on Emergency Responses to Food Insecurity and underscores the relevance of the WTO in addressing critical issues beyond trade. Time has come for the General Council to take this matter up and deal with it based on its urgency. This initiative reflects the WTO's commitment to fostering global cooperation and leveraging its mandate to contribute meaningfully to the well-being of our countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.16-->
                    <paragraph id="13.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Egypt believes that endorsing this proposal is not only a moral imperative but also aligns with the principles of solidarity and shared responsibility among members. Food security is a basic human right, and addressing it requires collective action that transcends traditional trade negotiations. We urge all members of the General Council to support and adopt this proposal, recognizing its importance in addressing the urgent and escalating challenges faced by NFIDCs and LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.17-->
                    <paragraph id="13.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We call upon the General Council to take this matter up to the ministers who should be able to deal with it based on its urgency and sensitivity. Food availability, accessibility and affordability is a national security issue that almost does not need to always be based on technical, unproductive discussions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.18</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Antigua and Barbuda, on behalf of the OECS, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.19-->
                    <paragraph id="13.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The OECS thanks the African Group for its communication. As WTO Members classified as net food importing developing countries, the OECS States imports a large share of the food that we utilize with some countries importing more than 80 per cent of total food consumption. Meanwhile, output from the agricultural sector has been declining since 1990, both in an absolute sense and as a percentage of gross domestic product. Furthermore, OECS countries have a low ration of cultivated land - suggesting a fundamental challenge for us to meet domestic food demand. Our estimates suggest that if all lands counted under cultivation in the OECS were used for domestic food needs there will at most be sufficient to feed only one fifth of the OECS population.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.20-->
                    <paragraph id="13.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Notwithstanding the challenges, we are aiming to deploy a combination of shared knowledge, best practices, research and development, innovation and the facilitation of agricultural trade, finance and investment to facilitate agricultural transformation in the OECS. This background underscores the importance that we attach to the proposal from the African Group of which we are broadly supportive. We look forward to future constructive engagements to deliver an outcome by MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.21</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nigeria delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.22-->
                    <paragraph id="13.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We associate ourselves with the statement delivered on behalf of the African Group on this issue. In the context of the persistent state of global food insecurity that has a disproportionate impact on developing economies especially NFIDCs and LDCs, we believe the WTO should within its mandate proffer solutions that would strengthen NFIDCs and LDCs domestic production and enhance their participation in global trade.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.23-->
                    <paragraph id="13.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The proposal contains decision on policy space to augment production and productivity in NFIDC and LDCs to buttress against the global market uncertainties and volatilities, which is itself contributed by the flawed and inequitable AoA rules. The decision would also foster access to basic food stuff for NFIDCs and LDCs. We believe the decision adopted would be part of the solution to the food insecurity situations in LDCs and NFIDCs. We call on Members to support the draft decision.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.24</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the European Union delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.25-->
                    <paragraph id="13.25">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The European Union would like to thank Nigeria and the African Group for their submission. The paper proposes several flexibilities for LDCs and NFIDCs related to a food security crisis. We are reviewing this submission in detail. Nevertheless, I would like to make some preliminary comments on some of the elements proposed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.26-->
                    <paragraph id="13.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Considering the ideas on a possible exemption for LDCs and NFIDCs on the use of their domestic support limits, this is an element that could be considered in the context of the reform of trade-distorting support disciplines, which is one of our key priorities in the negotiation. In relation to the proposal on export restrictions, we are still analyzing the ideas in the submission. But in principle, the European Union is in favor of any initiatives leading to the limitation of the use of export-restricting measures, which may in particular have a negative impact on importing Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.27-->
                    <paragraph id="13.27">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The European Union naturally supports the reaffirmation of the rules agreed in Nairobi on the conditions under which international food aid is granted with a view to limiting trade distortions. The paper also points at the shortcomings of transparency on food aid. The European Union agrees that this is a problem that needs to be addressed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.28-->
                    <paragraph id="13.28">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is important not to consider ideas that could result in backsliding on the provisions and disciplines agreed in Nairobi regarding export subsidies and measures with equivalent effect. The European Union remains open to engaging with the African Group, LDC, and NFIDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.29</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Paraguay delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.30-->
                    <paragraph id="13.30">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We wish to highlight the importance of the tools that already exist under the Agreement on Agriculture, which allow Members enhanced productivity and resilience, through investment in research, innovation and technology, and which do not have any relative or absolute limits under the current rules. Domestic support and possible flexibilities for specific products are part of the proposals made by both the African Group and the Cairns Group in the CoA SS, and these discussions have not developed enough for the issue to be referred up to the General Council as a proposal that has never been submitted to the CoA SS and is being circulated at the last minute.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.31-->
                    <paragraph id="13.31">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Many of these elements were included in other proposals by certain delegations from the African Group, which were unsuccessful and would be unlikely to lead to consensus in a Ministerial Declaration. The report by the Working Group on Food Security is yet to be adopted, not because of a lack of political will or commitment among non-proponents, but because one Member insists on legitimizing its policies on direct government-to-government exports.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.32-->
                    <paragraph id="13.32">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We further recall that the category of NFIDCs should be revised to establish more granularity. We note with concern that the category of NFIDCs currently includes large exporters of, inter alia, rice, wheat and wheat flour, hard grains, oilseeds, vegetable oils and sugar, simply because they are net importers. Around 70 Members are included in the category, which is equivalent to 41 per cent of the membership.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.33-->
                    <paragraph id="13.33">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We invite the African Group to review the parts of this proposal that spark sensitivity and re-submit the proposal as a JOB document to the Committee on Agriculture in Special Session so that the Committee can be part of the ongoing discussions, rather than trying to force a political decision without the technical discussion necessary to reach consensus.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.34</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Sri Lanka delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.35-->
                    <paragraph id="13.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Sri Lanka thanks the African Group for submitting this very important Draft Ministerial Decision. We had in-depth deliberations on food security issues of NFIDCs and LDCs for over sixteen months at the dedicated Work Programme established under the CoA. However, we could not deliver anything on the food security issues of the NFIDCs and LDCs as mandated by our Ministers.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 13.36-->
                    <paragraph id="13.36">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This does not mean that our path is closed. We need to inform this to our Ministers and request for their immediate intervention on this matter. In this context, the Draft Ministerial Decision is indeed a timely submission. The Draft Decision has well captured the most pertinent elements related to food security challenges of the NFIDCs and LDCs. Therefore, we believe this Ministerial decision could be one of the deliverables at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>13.37</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
