        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>14</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>DRAFT MINISTERIAL DECISION ON SPS MEASURES - REQUEST FROM THE AFRICAN GROUP</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 14.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson invited Cameroon, on behalf of the African Group, to introduce the item "Draft Ministerial Decision on SPS Measures".</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon, on behalf of the African Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.3-->
                    <paragraph id="14.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Thank you, Chair, for giving me the opportunity to present, on behalf of the African Group, the draft Decision on Sanitary and Phytosanitary (SPS) Measures, which has been submitted for consideration by the General Council with a view to a decision by ministers at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.4-->
                    <paragraph id="14.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This draft decision, contained in document WT/GC/W/914 - G/SPS/W/347, is part of a parallel approach and is complementary to the SPS Declaration adopted on 17 June 2022 at MC12, under which an SPS Committee programme was established. The purpose of this draft text is to propose specific measures to effectively and diligently address the challenges constantly faced by developing countries, particularly LDCs, regarding compliance with the SPS standards imposed by importing Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.5-->
                    <paragraph id="14.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>While the African Group recognizes Members' right to take measures to protect human, animal and plant health, it remains concerned about the rise in SPS measures that are arbitrary and not based on science, as well as the specific challenges faced by developing countries and LDCs in meeting the sanitary and phytosanitary requirements of many of their trading partners, with consequences that continue to affect their market access and export competitiveness.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.6-->
                    <paragraph id="14.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Thus, while reaffirming the rules and principles guiding the adoption and application of measures, as set out in the Agreement on the Application of SPS Measures, the draft decision focuses on steps that could be taken to minimize the impact of SPS measures on the exporting capacities of the countries concerned. In this connection, the WT/GC/W/914 draft contains provisions that would require all importing countries to enter into consultations, within a reasonable time period, with any exporting developing country or LDC that identifies specific problems in complying with a sanitary or phytosanitary measure that the importing Member has taken or plans to introduce, with a view to finding a mutually satisfactory solution.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.7-->
                    <paragraph id="14.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The decision would also require developed country Members and developing country Members in a position to do so, to take account of the special needs of developing country Members and, in particular, least developed country Members, when introducing and applying SPS measures, in particular by granting longer time frames for compliance, upon request from any developing country, for products of interest to it.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.8-->
                    <paragraph id="14.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The draft text also provides that all importing developed country Members shall assist exporting developing country Members that identify specific problems of capacity in fulfilling the sanitary or phytosanitary requirements of a developed country, to acquire the required capacity on preferential and non-commercial terms, preferably free of cost, keeping in view the development, financial and trade needs of the exporting developing country. In addition, it is proposed that the Codex Alimentarius Commission, the World Organization for Animal Health (WOAH) and the International Plant Protection Convention (IPPC) assist the SPS Committee with interpretation of the SPS standards that are the subject of specific trade concerns.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.9-->
                    <paragraph id="14.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Lastly, the draft text calls on Members and the Secretariat of the SPS Committee to strengthen efforts to provide technical assistance to developing country Members to adjust to and comply with sanitary and phytosanitary measures in order to achieve the appropriate level of sanitary and phytosanitary protection. The African Group remains open to consultations with interested delegations and intends to engage constructively with Members in discussions on the draft text, with a view to a Ministerial Decision on SPS measures at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.10</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Paraguay delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.11-->
                    <paragraph id="14.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My delegation thanks the African Group for submitting this document, which we broadly support. The proliferation of tariff barriers that create unjustified restrictions to trade, primarily in agricultural products, is evident from the huge number of trade concerns being raised in the WTO subsidiary bodies. In the SPS Committee, some measures clearly fail to meet the requirement of being based on scientific principles and risk assessments. This is especially true of measures adopted by certain developed Members or groups of Members, which have strayed from the science to the point of ignoring their own regulators and taking decisions based purely on political considerations.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.12-->
                    <paragraph id="14.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My delegation, as part of the group of Latin American countries that have been working together on SPS matters, takes a keen interest in this issue, in the strengthening of the SPS Agreement, and in the question of how to give effect to the special and differential treatment for developing countries under the SPS Agreement. We invite the African Group to reach out to the Latin American delegations with a view to moving forward on a revised draft together.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.13-->
                    <paragraph id="14.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Before I conclude, I wish to recall that the SPS Declaration at MC12 has resulted in important work and a report on findings and recommendations, which is still under consideration by the capitals of two delegations, one of which is an African Group member. We call for Members to engage with that delegation so that it can join the consensus, given the African Group's clear and stated interest in these issues, and the report of the working groups of the MC12 Declaration can be presented to ministers in Abu Dhabi.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.14</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chinese Taipei delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.15-->
                    <paragraph id="14.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank the African Group for its proposal of WT/GC/W/914. We understand the background of this submission. However, we would still like to make a couple of observations on this item: First, several elements suggested in this proposal seem to have exceeded or added to the rights or obligations of Members provided in the SPS Agreement. This might not be strictly in line with Members' understanding during the SPS Committee meetings in this regard.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.16-->
                    <paragraph id="14.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, the SPS Committee has intensively discussed a possible SPS Declaration, a report of which is scheduled to be submitted to MC13. This intended report is supposed to expect the SPS Committee to continue its targeted discussions and reflections on the implementation of the SPS Agreement. In other words, mechanisms and procedures are already in place within the SPS Committee to improve the implementation of the SPS Agreement. We therefore urge the relevant discussion to be taken place within the SPS Committee, before the issue being submitted to the General Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.17</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Côte d'Ivoire delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.18-->
                    <paragraph id="14.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Côte d'Ivoire wishes to associate itself with the statement made by Cameroon on behalf of the African Group. We have ongoing concerns regarding the application of SPS measures. We continue to draw Members' attention to the proliferation of SPS measures, which are restrictive or without scientific basis that limit our export opportunities and are major challenges and constraints raised regularly by our export companies, especially micro-, small- and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs).</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.19-->
                    <paragraph id="14.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The draft decision submitted by the African Group includes specific measures to tackle these issues without undermining the right of Members to implement measures to protect human, animal, and plant life or health. We therefore urge delegations to welcome this draft decision. For our part, we remain ready to engage in consultations with the other delegations with a view to arriving at a decision.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.20</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.21-->
                    <paragraph id="14.21">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>China thanks the African Group for submitting the proposal on SPS Measures and sees many valuable views and suggestions in it. Though our experts in the capital are still reviewing it, we support it in general. China is ready to have further discussions with the proponents and is interested in seeking further elaborations on some issues. For this purpose, we would suggest having it discussed in the SPS Committee for better understanding.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.22</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the Russian Federation delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.23-->
                    <paragraph id="14.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Russian Federation would like to thank the African Group for its draft of Ministerial decision on SPS measures intended to strengthen special and differential treatment provisions and making them more precise, effective and operational.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.24-->
                    <paragraph id="14.24">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We note that this proposal largely resembles G-90 initiative on modifying SDT in the SPS and TBT Agreements. Acknowledging difficulties of developing countries in meeting the SPS requirements of many of their trading partners and a consistent trend towards a significant increase of SPS measures in the last few years we still believe that such proposals should be duly examined and discussed in the WTO bodies such as the SPS Committee and the Committee on Trade and Development. The Russian Federation expresses its readiness to work constructively on this issue.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.25</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Egypt delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.26-->
                    <paragraph id="14.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In advocating for the adoption of this decision at MC13, Egypt underscores the critical need to address challenges faced by developing countries, especially LDCs, in adhering to Sanitary and Phytosanitary (SPS) standards imposed by importing members. The proposed decision, outlined in WT/GC/W/914 and G/SPS/W/347, aligns with the parallel approach initiated following the SPS declaration in June 2022. Egypt emphasizes the rising concerns about arbitrary SPS measures lacking scientific basis, disproportionately affecting Developing and Least Developed Countries, impacting their market access and export competitiveness negatively. We support the statement made by Cameroon on behalf of the African Group.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.27-->
                    <paragraph id="14.27">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This decision calls for a collaborative effort, urging importing countries to engage in timely consultations with developing or LDC exporting countries to find mutually satisfactory solutions for specific SPS compliance challenges. It also encourages developed members to consider the special needs of developing and least developed countries, offering extended timelines upon request, particularly for products of interest. Furthermore, the decision proposes that developed importing members provide non-commercial, preferably free assistance to developing exporting members facing capacity challenges in complying with SPS requirements. Egypt highlights the support from the Codex Alimentarius Commission, World Organization for Animal Health (OIE), and International Plant Protection Convention (IPPC) to interpret SPS standards of specific commercial concern.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.28-->
                    <paragraph id="14.28">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In conclusion, Egypt asserts that adopting this decision is crucial for promoting fair and effective trade practices, addressing the technical and capacity challenges faced by developing members, and ensuring the appropriate level of sanitary and phytosanitary protection. Egypt remains open to consultations and commits to constructive engagement with fellow members to facilitate a ministerial decision on SPS measures at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.29</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Costa Rica delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 14.30-->
                    <paragraph id="14.30">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Costa Rica wishes to thank the African Group for presenting this document. We share the concerns of the African Group regarding the increase in non-tariff barriers through sanitary and phytosanitary measures. We welcome the valuable elements of this proposal, which cover many of the points discussed in the MC12 SPS Declaration working groups. We also note that the text was not referred to the SPS Committee, which would have been very useful in drawing up the draft report. We would therefore like to invite the African Group to refer these issues to the SPS Committee, which will begin the Sixth Review of its operation in 2024.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>14.31</statement_number>
