        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>15</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER AND ECONOMIC RESILIENCE – REQUEST FROM THE AFRICAN GROUP</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 15.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson invited Cameroon, to introduce on behalf of the African Group, the item "Technology Transfer and Economic Resilience" that has been included in the agenda.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon, on behalf of the African Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.3-->
                    <paragraph id="15.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I deliver this statement on behalf of the African Group, representing the collective voice of 44 members, particularly focusing on the critical issue of technology transfer and diffusion within the framework of the WTO. Recognizing the paramount importance of technology transfer and diffusion in the context of building economic resilience in developing and least developed countries, we acknowledge the transformative power of technology in establishing a modern and technologically advanced industrial base. Technology serves as a catalyst for progress, playing a pivotal role in addressing multifaceted challenges such as food insecurity, pandemics, climate change, and fostering innovation, all of which are fundamental to sustainable development.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.4-->
                    <paragraph id="15.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The declaration proposed builds upon the foundation laid by the Fourth WTO Ministerial Conference Declaration in Doha in November 2001, establishing the Working Group on Trade and Transfer of Technology (WGTTT). It is incumbent upon us to further advance this work to ensure that the barriers hindering the facilitation, access, and transfer of technologies to developing and least developed countries are effectively addressed. Considering this, the African Group, proposes that our ministers approve this Declaration/Decision in mC13, the main elements of which are as follows:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.5-->
                    <paragraph id="15.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First: The establishment of a dedicated agenda item in all relevant WTO bodies to examine the specific relationship between trade and transfer of technology. This includes an assessment of measures adopted by members constraining technology transfer and the identification of agreement-specific flexibilities needed to promote transfer and diffusion to developing and least developed countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.6-->
                    <paragraph id="15.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second: initiating a Comprehensive Examination Process that should encompass a thorough assessment of issues such as constraints hampering technology transfer, the needs of developing and least developed countries for enhanced assistance, and an evaluation of the role of technical assistance and capacity-building programs. Particularly, focus on environmentally sound technology (EST) and financial commitments should be emphasized.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.7-->
                    <paragraph id="15.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Third: conducting "periodic reviews" by the Working Group on Trade and Transfer of Technology based on reports submitted by relevant WTO bodies, members shall be encouraged to continue sharing experiences on initiatives and programs aimed at facilitating and promoting technology transfer. These reviews shall contribute to developing recommendations, by MC14, for increasing technology flow to developing and least developed countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.8-->
                    <paragraph id="15.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Fourth: the decision urges Members to conduct a review of Article 66.2 of the TRIPS Agreement to ensure an effective transfer of technology to least developed countries, including through the Technology Bank for LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.9-->
                    <paragraph id="15.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Fifth: the decision initiates "Enhanced Data Collection Process" by the Secretariat, which should play a proactive role in collecting information on the cost of technology transfer, including royalties and other payments to developing and least developed countries. Additionally, the decision advocates for an improvement in the collection of public statistics, including intellectual property rights statistics in WTO stats, with the production of annual publications on technology transfer flows in all sectors.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.10-->
                    <paragraph id="15.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The African Group has invested substantial effort and time to engage with the membership on that matter in almost all subsidiary bodies since the beginning of the year. We submitted several documents, and we presented our ideas and thoughts in that regard. Now it is time that this organization considers reinvigorating the work on such an important issue. This decision should align with our vision for a future where technology serves as an inclusive force, driving economic growth, fostering resilience, and contributing to the sustainable development of our nations. We call upon all members to join hands in supporting these proposals for the betterment of our shared future.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.11</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chile delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.12-->
                    <paragraph id="15.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Chile recognizes the growing importance of discussions around technology transfer and the role of the multilateral trading system therein, within the different forums of the WTO. In our opinion, Members have a clear interest in the matter, which will likely grow – rather than diminish – in the future, owing to the urgent and unprecedented challenges we are facing in areas such as food security, health, the environment and the digital divide. We see a growing belief among Members that technology transfer could help to mitigate these challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.13-->
                    <paragraph id="15.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With this in mind, we welcome the initiative of the African Group, which we regard as an invitation to hold more substantive discussions on technology transfer and the role of the multilateral trading system therein. Accordingly, we wish to express our interest in exploring the relationship that exists between technology transfer and economic development, particularly the role of technology transfer in increasing productivity; technology transfer as a tool for enhancing industrial development and economic diversification; the role of technical assistance and capacity building programmes for developing and least developed countries; and how to enable small and medium sized enterprises in developing and least developed countries to benefit from the various technology transfer tools, instruments and platforms. We are likewise in favour of sharing experiences of technology transfer and trade, and of supplementing and strengthening our work with that of other international organizations, industry and academia.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.14</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Tanzania delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.15-->
                    <paragraph id="15.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to briefly register our strong support to the submission of the African group as presented by the coordinator of the group, Cameroon. It is factual that climate change related disasters have increased, and we are likely to witness more and more in the new future. Most of climate adaptation and mitigation measures are in a form of technological solution. Developing countries should be facilitated to produce of certain type environmentally friendly or cleaner products, as a shared responsibility for a common course.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.16-->
                    <paragraph id="15.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Extending some flexibilities to developing countries in the context of the for environmentally sound technologies and in particular for clean energy technologies would help make the multilateral trade regime more consistent with international climate change agreements. This would offer manufacturers in developing countries quicker access to key green technologies, with a view to combat climate change, that will benefit all of us looking at it from a holistic view.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.17-->
                    <paragraph id="15.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Therefore, having extensive examination of the relationship between trade and transfer of technology and allowing discussion to take place in WTO relevant bodies, is something to be encouraged. From such discussion, we will identify some specific flexibilities and technologies to be diffused in developing and LDC. It will lead to a meaningful implementation of TRIPS Article 66.2, as well as invigorate the work of the Working Group of Transfer of Technology in the WTO. In closing, our delegation would like to commend the chair of the Working Group on Transfer of Technology for encouraging members to submit their ideas to revamp the work.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.18</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Egypt delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.19-->
                    <paragraph id="15.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Egypt emphatically supports the endorsement of the elements of a draft decision on Technology Transfer and Economic Resilience (as presented in the statement made by the Ambassador of Cameroon on behalf of the AG group) for a myriad of compelling reasons that resonate with our commitment to inclusivity, sustainable development, and addressing the unique challenges faced by developing and least developed countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.20-->
                    <paragraph id="15.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We firmly align ourselves with the proposed elements for a Declaration (as presented by Cameroon on behalf of the AG), recognizing the indispensable role of technology in fostering economic resilience. The WTO should adopt a decision that underscores the urgency of addressing the distinctive development needs, particularly in developing and least developed country members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.21-->
                    <paragraph id="15.21">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We see merits in the African call for a dedicated agenda item in relevant WTO bodies, emphasizing our commitment to transparency and inclusivity. The WTO should affirm its dedication to creating a more inclusive platform that evaluates measures constraining technology transfer as it relates to trade and more to current challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.22-->
                    <paragraph id="15.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The potential decision should acknowledge the significance of the Comprehensive Examination Process, focusing on environmentally sound technology and financial commitments. The WTO would actively contribute to the global agenda of sustainable development, aligning our efforts with the broader objectives of the WTO and the international community.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.23-->
                    <paragraph id="15.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The proposed elements of the decision include a mandate to Enhancing Information-Sharing through the proposed periodic reviews by the Working Group on Trade and Transfer of Technology. The potential decision should recognize the power of collaborative information-sharing among WTO members, facilitate a more informed decision-making process, allowing countries to benefit from shared experiences and best practices in technology transfer.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.24-->
                    <paragraph id="15.24">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Egypt urges all WTO members to consider a ministerial decision on ToT in MC13. This pivotal step reflects our collective commitment to addressing the developmental needs of member countries, promoting inclusivity, advancing sustainable development goals, enhancing information-sharing, addressing challenges in the TRIPS Agreement, and facilitating evidence-based decision-making.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.25</statement_number>
