                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.33</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Switzerland delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.34-->
                    <paragraph id="15.34">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We understand this agenda item to deal with the African Group's communications, six in total, on trade and technology transfers. We thank the Ambassador of Cameroun for the introduction. There is still a lot to be learnt on how effective technology transfer can take place. In this regard, additional evidence-based analysis, as well as exchanging views and sharing experience may be useful in order to gather and discuss evidence and get a better understanding on the relationship between trade and technology transfer. It also seems essential to take into account efforts that are made in other international fora in order to build on existing work rather than duplicate it.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.35-->
                    <paragraph id="15.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Many factors are needed to create real incentives for technology transfer to happen – including the right infrastructure, a conducive business environment, sufficient absorption capacity, and last but not least, a well-functioning, reliable, safe and enforceable regulatory framework, including the protection of intellectual property rights. Ultimately, it is regularly the private sector which is the holder of technology and it will decide on the basis of these and other factors whether and with whom to share its technology. It is therefore paramount that the private sector be involved in subsequent deliberations and experience-sharing activities on the matter.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.36</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.37-->
                    <paragraph id="15.37">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This agenda item is very important. I think there is some confusion on this because this agenda is on the transfer of technology. It emanates from the February retreat on development; after the February retreat on development the African Group came up with a broad proposal in March, which was circulated to various Committees and then in the month of July, they had Committee-specific proposals for technology transfer, there were six proposals, and I hope Cameroon will bear me out, that we are discussing under this agenda those six items, plus the mother proposal of March. Since no links or papers were given, there is confusion, I would request that you take it afresh tomorrow with those six papers, circulated to the Members, so that we can engage in these discussions more effectively. However, if it is not agreeable, then I will just read a one-minute statement, which is the reinvigoration of discussion on technology transfer.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.38-->
                    <paragraph id="15.38">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We welcome the submissions made by the Africa Group and support it. We hope that a concrete mandate will be delivered in MC13 on these issues. Technology transfer is a priority for us. The WTO recognizes the close relationship between trade and the transfer of technology, as evidenced in the establishment of the Working Group on Trade and Technology Transfer (WGTTT) in 2002. The role of the WGTTT was to discuss ways to increase technology flows from developed to developing countries. The issue of technology transfer is now perhaps more important than ever before, given the central role of development and transfer of environmentally sound technology to address climate change. India's paper JOB/WGTTT/2, also submitted to the Committee on Trade and Environment and Council for TRIPS makes a case for advancing these discussions in the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>15.39</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of South Africa delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 15.40-->
