        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>16</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>THE CONTRIBUTION OF THE MULTILATERAL TRADING SYSTEM TO SUSTAINABLE AND RESILIENT AGRICULTURE AND FOOD SYSTEMS – STATEMENT BY THE CAIRNS GROUP (WT/GC/261)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 16.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson invited Australia, on behalf of the Cairns Group, to introduce the item "The Contribution of the Multilateral Trading System to Sustainable and Resilient Agriculture and Food System".</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Australia, on behalf of the Cairns Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.3-->
                    <paragraph id="16.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The reason we introduced this in the July General Council, the reason that the Cairns Group has in mind this statement is because resilient and sustainable agriculture and food systems are essential to meeting the goals of global food security and economic development, as well as environmental sustainability. This relationship between trade and sustainability is something we have got to keep working on together. We said at the last GC meeting that we would be pleased to present this statement on the contribution of the multilateral trading system to sustainable and resilient agriculture and food systems in document WT/GC/261. We originally submitted this statement at the Committee on Agriculture in September.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.4-->
                    <paragraph id="16.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>There is no one-size-fits-all approach to sustainable agriculture. What works in one part of the world does not necessarily work in others. This is an important recognition. Second, we would make the point that measures in the name of environmental sustainability should not be unnecessarily trade restrictive. That is a big fundamental thought behind this piece of paper. Third, unilateral approaches do risk undermining multilateral approach to trade and sustainability. So, this statement underlines that measures need to be based on science, evidence and need to be consistent with WTO Members' obligations as we focus on environmental outcomes. We have been pretty active right across the membership on looking at ways to reconcile trade and environment measures and to avoid unnecessarily trade restrictive import measures. We look forward to further discussions with Members on this issue in the months ahead.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.5</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon, on behalf of the African Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.6-->
                    <paragraph id="16.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The African Group thanks the Cairns Group for their paper. This paper is yet another attempt to reset the agriculture negotiating agenda by pitching a narrative of food security that harps completely on trade liberalization while ignoring Ministerial mandates on critical food security instruments such as PSH and SSM. This would have detrimental effects on developing economies that are disproportionately affected by global food insecurity.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.7-->
                    <paragraph id="16.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe Developing countries, which face a greater burden of food insecurity, must themselves decide on the solutions and not have solutions superimposed on them from outside, especially by countries which have commercial/export interest in agriculture rather than a food security perspective. The African Group is of the view that a medium and long-term solution to food security challenges can only be delivered through a MC13 outcome that include substantive food security and livelihoods package with decisions on issues under negotiations in the CoA SS such as PSH, and SSM, as well as outcome on domestic support that addresses the inequitable elements of Domestic Support, trade distorting forms of Green Box and Blue Box. This would foster fair agriculture trading system and allow greater policy space for Developing Countries to support production and livelihoods. These are the outcomes that are necessary for ensuring food security in developing countries and LDCs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.8-->
                    <paragraph id="16.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We know that reforming the agricultural trade support architecture from the imbalances in the AoA that benefit large agricultural subsidizers, in particularly developed economies, and the substantial reduction in agricultural trade support is central to the reform envisaged under Article 20. However, we believe that it is premature for any Member to call for further market liberalization when our agriculture sector is itself constrained from using necessary tools which are limited by the AoA rules, and also because of the continuation of massive subsidies especially in Developed Countries. The African Group would continue to engage constructively with the Cairns Group and other Members so we can deliver effective WTO solution to Global Food insecurity.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.9</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Ecuador delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.10-->
                    <paragraph id="16.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I thank the Cairns Group for including this item on the agenda. We concur with the Cairns Group that the long-awaited multilateral agricultural trade reform must be progressed as a matter of urgency in a comprehensive manner, consistent with Article 20 of the Agreement on Agriculture. To promote fair and transparent international agricultural trade, compliance with the relevant WTO Agreements is essential, while recognizing that Members have different and unique agricultural production conditions and practices. Sustainable agriculture is vital for improving food security.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.11-->
                    <paragraph id="16.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is a fundamental pillar of the future we aspire to, in which the deterioration in human health caused by malnutrition and poverty, invariably linked to hunger, are things of the past. However, we must also reiterate that imposing trade policy measures for environmental purposes may constitute a form of arbitrary discrimination. It may adversely affect agricultural production and trade, especially in developing countries, when such measures are applied unilaterally, without taking into account the fact that multilateral standards, such as the Codex Alimentarius, are in force, and without recognizing other Members' points of views or environmental policies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.12-->
                    <paragraph id="16.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Ecuador shares the approaches set out in the proposal and we stand ready to work with other Members to promote agricultural trade without arbitrary barriers, that finds the balance between trade and environmental protection, and that safeguards developing countries' sustainable development and needs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.13</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Egypt delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.14-->
                    <paragraph id="16.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Egypt aligns itself with the African Group's stance in response to the Cairns Group's paper on the multilateral trading system's role in sustainable agriculture and food systems. Our appreciation extends to the Cairns Group for their submission. We share concerns, as outlined in paragraph 1.1 of this submission, about global environmental and food security challenges, emphasizing the need for collective action. Egypt supports the Cairns Group's vision of a fair, equitable, and market-oriented agricultural trading system, adaptable to the diverse needs of all members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.15-->
                    <paragraph id="16.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We reaffirm our commitment to multilateral environmental, development, and food security goals, aligning with the UNFCCC and its Paris Agreement. Egypt looks forward to collaborating with the Cairns Group to foster a non-distorted, rules-based international agricultural trade system that supports global food security and enhances environmental outcomes. Additionally, Egypt seeks common ground with the Cairns Group on Article 20 of the Agreement on Agriculture. Acknowledging the Cairns Group's recognition, as stated in paragraph 6, that there is no one-size-fits-all approach to improving sustainability in agriculture, we are eager for further discussions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.16-->
                    <paragraph id="16.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We concur with the African Group's emphasis on integrating the Ministerial mandate on PSH into the narrative of food security. We support the call for a ministerial outcome in Abu Dhabi addressing food security and livelihoods. Highlighting the importance of allowing Developing Countries greater policy space, Egypt recognizes the need for reform in the agricultural trade support architecture. We agree with the African Group that advocating further market liberalization is premature while constraints persist due to AoA rules and substantial subsidies in developed countries. Egypt commits to constructive engagement with the Cairns Group and fellow Members, working collaboratively to achieve an effective WTO solution to global food insecurity.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.17</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of South Africa delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.18-->
                    <paragraph id="16.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to add to what others have already expressed, especially the African Group coordinator and also just to implore the different groups, the African Group, the Cairns Group and others to work together to ensure that we do not only liberalize agriculture, but that we pay attention to the specific needs of developing countries. I do sense that we are coming closed on many issues where previously there have been differences. Let us not waste the opportunity, the widow is open but it will not stay so for long.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.19</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Brazil delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.20-->
                    <paragraph id="16.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The unilateral adoption of trade restrictive measures with extraterritorial application, such as due diligence, anti-deforestation laws, MRLs that are not science-based, and mirror clauses, is a threat to the multilateral trading system with the WTO at its core. The claim that they are being adopted under the umbrella of environmental policies is but an attempt to green wash protectionism.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.21-->
                    <paragraph id="16.21">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The unilateral adoption of trade-restrictive measures with extraterritorial application will increase even further the burden and costs of transaction and compliance to agricultural producers, especially in developing countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.22-->
                    <paragraph id="16.22">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>That will hinder their progress in securing a "share in the growth in international trade commensurate with the needs of their economic development", as prescribed in the Marrakesh Agreement Establishing the World Trade Organization.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.23-->
                    <paragraph id="16.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In the worst-case scenario, agricultural producers from developing countries could be downright excluded from value chains. Such measures will lead to regulatory fragmentation and prevents the furthering of international regulatory cooperation, for it creates a conflictive dynamic between exporters and importers with negative consequences on sustainable development on its three pillars.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.24-->
                    <paragraph id="16.24">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The 11 guiding principles in WT/GC/261 provide the basis for a fair and equitable transition towards more sustainable agricultural and food systems that not implodes the MTS. We call on all Members to respect them and stress our commitment to work with other WTO Members and groups.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.25</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chinese Taipei delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.26-->
                    <paragraph id="16.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We recognize the submission's support of the idea that a rule-based and well-functioning multilateral trading system can contribute to global food security. It also correctly points out that different Members have unique agricultural production conditions, circumstances and practices and there is no "one size fits all" approach for improving sustainability outcomes in agriculture.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.27-->
                    <paragraph id="16.27">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to note that it is also because of the different natural conditions and production patterns among Members, an agricultural policy of the same form may have different effects on or contribution to any distortions and sustainability. One particular point that the Cairns Group's submission misses mentioning is that agriculture plays a multifunctional role in ensuring food security, protecting the environment and many other non-trade aspects.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.28-->
                    <paragraph id="16.28">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Due to such unique nature of agriculture, a policy on agricultural trade cannot be judged purely based on a technical calculation of economic efficiency. The valuable positive aspects arising from agricultural support to enhance environmental sustainability and from its positive non-trade roles should also be fairly recognized.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.29</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chile delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.30-->
                    <paragraph id="16.30">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Chile thanks Australia for presenting document G/AG/GEN/222 on behalf of the Cairns Group. We endorse the points made with regard to promoting fairer and more equitable international agricultural trade, capable of responding to the challenges related to food security, environmental sustainability and climate change. Among these points, my delegation draws attention to the recognition of the agricultural production characteristics and methods unique to each country, as there is no one-size-fits-all approach to addressing agricultural sustainability; and the implementation of practices that help agri-food systems adapt to a changing climate, reduce greenhouse gas emissions, eradicate hunger and safeguard global food security, with the participation and leadership of women, Indigenous Peoples and rural communities.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.31</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.32-->
                    <paragraph id="16.32">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>China thanks the submission from the Cairns Group. Though as a major agricultural and food net importer, we share many similar views with the group members in promoting sustainable and resilient agricultural and food system. We believe that sustainable agriculture is essential for improving food security, nutrition, economic development, and that environmental policies and outcomes should not be designed for protectionist purpose. We share the increasing concern about the significant surge in the adoption of various forms of unilateral trade-related environmental measures. We agree with the view highlighted in the paper, particularly regarding the potential misuse of trade measures in the pursuit of environment goal and the application of one-size-fits-all approach to Climate Change and mitigation and adaptation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.33-->
                    <paragraph id="16.33">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On agricultural subsidy, given the different nature of subsidies, different needs and development stages of members as well as different per capita support level, we agree that the "one size fits all" approach should not be the choice. Under existing rules of AoA, green transition support measures should be encouraged by members for sustainable development while exploring feasible domestic reform modality aiming at leveling the playing field. We hope members could continue to have objective and data-based and science-based discussions in the CTE on the role of agricultural subsidy to the environment, which we believe could be a positive complementary to the agricultural reform and negotiations in CoA SS.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.34</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nigeria delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.35-->
                    <paragraph id="16.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We associate ourselves with the statement delivered on behalf of the African Group on this issue. As stated by the African Group, this paper is yet another attempt to reset the agriculture negotiating agenda by pitching a narrative of food security that harps completely on trade liberalization while ignoring Ministerial mandates on critical food security instruments such as PSH and SSM. In our view, this approach cannot proffer solution to food security challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.36-->
                    <paragraph id="16.36">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe that the proposals submitted by the African Group including the joint African Group, ACP and G33 proposal on PSH are those related to tools for addressing food security and crises. Nigeria and a vast majority of Developing countries and LDCs have outlined for a long time that a solution to long-term food security challenges for us is through the delivery of the mandated outcomes on the issues under negotiations at the CoA SS; PSH, SSM, and domestic support that addresses the inequitable elements of DS such as AMS entitlements, trade distorting forms of Green Box and Blue Box, and strengthens and upholds S&amp;D. These can allow Developing Countries greater policy space to support product and livelihoods.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.37-->
                    <paragraph id="16.37">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe that without an assessment of the cost of 28 years of liberalization of agricultural markets under the WTO, and the failure to get the developed countries to remove their subsidies, the same prescription cannot again be adopted as solution for long term food security across the developing world.  We look forward to engaging constructively with all members so we can collectively proffer effective solutions to food insecurity difficulties.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.38</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Paraguay delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.39-->
                    <paragraph id="16.39">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The multilateral trading system can and should contribute to the resilience and transformation of the agrifood systems falling within its mandate. In this regard, the best way for the WTO to contribute is by concluding the agricultural reform process.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.40-->
                    <paragraph id="16.40">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The substantial and progressive reduction of trade distortions and protections in the agricultural sector will help ensure greater predictability for trade in agricultural products, the diversification of sources of origin and stability in supply chains. In addition, it will allow for resources to be used and distributed more efficiently, which would result in higher output with a lower environmental impact, enabling better conservation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.41-->
                    <paragraph id="16.41">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>However, this will involve more than just the reform process, which would improve conditions in the future. To prevent the current conditions from being undermined, it will also require strict compliance with the existing rules, both in the relevant WTO Agreements and the international legal obligations undertaken in other forums, such as those of an environmental nature, including Articles 2.1(b) and 2.2 of the Paris Agreement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.42-->
                    <paragraph id="16.42">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We recall that advancing together towards our common goals requires cooperation, negotiation and the non-imposition of unilateral measures. We encourage Members to work collaboratively to recognize good agricultural practices that contribute to sustainability and are adapted to national needs and circumstances and to facilitate the adoption, transfer and use of technology that helps to improve the productivity, sustainability and resilience of agrifood systems.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.43</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Indonesia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.44-->
                    <paragraph id="16.44">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We appreciate the work of colleagues from the Cairns Group in putting together this document. On this note, we would like to reaffirm our well-known position regarding the issue of domestic support.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.45-->
                    <paragraph id="16.45">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>At the same time, there are some merits and alignments with our views in some of the paragraphs in the Statement, including appropriate recognition of each country's unique agriculture situation, and on the imposition of environment-related trade measures that constitute a means of arbitrary or unjustifiable discrimination, or a disguised restriction on international trade, as well as excessive compliance requirements. There are among issues that we would continue working together in future agriculture negotiation in the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.46</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Japan delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.47-->
                    <paragraph id="16.47">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We appreciate the contribution from the Cairns group. We recognize the statement contains points that Japan agrees with, such as "there is no 'one size fits all' approach for improving sustainability outcomes in agriculture" or "avoid unjustified trade restrictions". In the meantime, with regard to the point that "the majority of agricultural subsidies in the world are distortive and harmful to the environment and health", Japan does not agree with the view that agricultural subsidies generally have a negative impact on the environment, and in fact, Japan designs and implements agricultural subsidies in a way not to have a negative impact on the environment, but rather to have a positive impact. We hope that the discussion on sustainability of agriculture be conducted using a fact-based perspective.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>16.48</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Malaysia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.49-->
                    <paragraph id="16.49">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>With regard to Agenda item 16, we thank Australia for presenting the statement, in which Malaysia is also one of the co-sponsors. We wish to stress and reemphasize the importance of a fair, facilitative and transparent agricultural trade system, in the face of global environmental and food security challenges. Sustainable agriculture plays a pivotal role in enhancing food security, fostering economic development and promoting environmental sustainability. As we move forward, it is imperative that our policies promoting sustainable agriculture prioritize long-term sustainability, rather than being driven by protectionist objectives.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.50-->
                    <paragraph id="16.50">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In this regard, Malaysia wishes to reaffirm our unwavering support for the multilateral trading system, with the WTO at its core - upholding WTO principles and agreements, such as the Agreement on Agriculture, TBT and SPS. In our quest of sustainable agricultural trade, we must avoid unjustified trade restrictions and burdensome compliance requirements. Most importantly, we must address the distortionary and harmful effects of global agricultural support, paving the way for a more sustainable and equitable global agricultural landscape. In conclusion, we call upon all Members to collaborate and promote sustainable and resilient agriculture and food systems, and on this note, Malaysia stands ready to engage constructively with all Members in this crucial agenda.</t>
                            </p>
