                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.71-->
                    <paragraph id="16.71">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In this intervention, I would like to cover items 13 and 11, as well as item 16 this morning. On the statement on sustainable, resilient agriculture and food systems presented this morning by Australia from the Cairns Group, New Zealand supports the call for greater dialogue and cooperation on trade-related environment measures at the WTO. This helps us to ensure that our respective efforts to drive more sustainable agriculture and food systems are in line with our WTO commitments and do not pose additional barriers to trade. As others have emphasized, there is no one-size-fits-all approach to environmental sustainability, which have different natural environments and production systems and consequently, will use different approaches and tools to achieving the same outcome of enhanced environmental sustainability. In this regard, New Zealand shares the overall objectives and principles set out in the Cairns Group statement, and looks forward to working with other Members in striving for multilateral coherence in respect to trade-related environmental measures to the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.72-->
                    <paragraph id="16.72">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the earlier item from Singapore (WT/GC/W/908), we recognize the value of enhanced transparency of export restrictions and in particular, the importance of ensuring open, fair and predictable markets, including stable trade flows to net food importing countries, especially LDCs. There have been a number of proposals on export restrictions put forward on the Committee on Agriculture, and we would encourage further deliberations on them in that forum. However, increased transparency is only one leeway to try to address food insecurity, and not the most powerful.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.73-->
                    <paragraph id="16.73">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Turning to item 13, the proposal from the African Group on draft Ministerial Decision on Promoting Agricultural Production and Trade in NFIDCs and LDCs, we note that many of the ideas on this paper have been raised in the food security Working Group under the Committee on Agriculture, and have also been discussed in the CoA SS. As we outlined previously, in this working group and in the CoA SS, there are many ways to enhance food security and agriculture production within existing rules, and we are open to discussions on these and on the ideas of these papers on those two bodies.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 16.74-->
                    <paragraph id="16.74">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In conclusion, to seriously tackle the underlined issues giving rise to these concerns working to address the wider problems, like the very high levels of trade-distorting domestic support in agriculture is vital, so we can achieve a more resilient, food secure global trading system. This is why New Zealand remains committed to a comprehensive and holistic approach to agriculture and trade reform under Article 20 of the Agreement on Agriculture, and as the ambassador from Nigeria has said, it is high time that we achieve positive outcomes.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
