        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>17</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>EUROPEAN UNION REGULATION ON SUPPLY CHAINS FREE FROM DEFORESTATION AND FOREST DEGRADATION – COMMUNICATION FROM ARGENTINA, COLOMBIA, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC, GUATEMALA, HONDURAS, PANAMA, PARAGUAY, AND PERU (WT/GC/W/912)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 17.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson invited Honduras to introduce, on behalf of the co-sponsors, the item "European Union Regulation on Supply Chains Free from Deforestation and Forest Degradation" (WT/GC/W/912).</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 17.2-->
                <p>
                    <t>The representative of Honduras delivered the following statement, on behalf of the co-sponsors:</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 17.3-->
                <p>
                    <t>In relation to this item, we would like to reiterate our firm commitment to environmental principles, particularly in the battle against deforestation and forest degradation. We are, however, deeply concerned about the way in which the European regulation addresses these matters. While a more detailed statement will be sent to the Secretariat, in general terms, we urge the European Union to review its unilateral environmental regulations, which are causing poverty and generating tensions among WTO Members. In spite of the discussions that have taken place in the WTO committees, the concerns of the affected countries have not been taken into account, and the WTO General Council is the only option for addressing this issue. The regulation penalizes, diverting attention from the real causes of the problem and shifting responsibility to countries that are less responsible.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 17.4-->
                <p>
                    <t>The key word is therefore "trust". We are faced with institutionally designed trade measures that are regressive and, in our view, have a marginal environmental impact. Those affected by the measures have no protective mechanisms because they are the most vulnerable actors in faraway countries. There are no effective discussion forums that allow for dialogue and truly meaningful constructive cooperation. This situation in which dialogue is impossible undermines trust; it generates reactions and an interest in searching for legal and political alternatives, which unfortunately makes the discussions on environmental provisions in this Organization even more difficult. Creating poverty and penalizing a very specific vulnerable sector, rather than focusing on those that are really responsible, is not the appropriate multilateral path for trade measures that seek to address global environmental problems.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 17.5-->
                <p>
                    <t>For this reason, and in the absence of better mechanisms, we are bringing the discussion before the General Council. While this is an unusual agenda item in that it refers to a specific country, it affects all of us. We urge the European Union and other Members of this Organization to engage in open and sincere discussions on public trade and environmental policy – discussions that are not merely informative, but also effective and cooperative.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.6</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Peru delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.7-->
                    <paragraph id="17.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Peru welcomes and echoes the statement made by Honduras. Exports of the products covered by the regulation account for a significant share of Peru's exports to the European Union. Some of these products, such as cocoa and coffee, have value chains made up of thousands of small-scale producers, whose livelihoods through trade may be impacted by measures such as the one under discussion today. Moreover, for countries like Peru, the European regulation will not only affect trade, but also security policies, specifically with respect to efforts to combat drug production through the substitution of illicit crops.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.8-->
                    <paragraph id="17.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As we have reiterated in other forums, we are concerned that there are still many aspects of the European regulation that remain unclear or require supplementary regulations. This means that the actual time frame that operators have to make the necessary adjustments for compliance will, in reality, be far shorter than the 18-month time frame established by the regulation. Similarly, we note that the regulation fails to specify which documents are required for compliance. It does not define procedural steps or set any fixed time frames, meaning that both operators and the European Union authorities have considerable discretion and that there is, thus, a lack of predictability in the regulatory landscape. The European Union has said that the regulation will be applied as of 30 December 2024. However, we do not when supplementary regulations will be finalized.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.9-->
                    <paragraph id="17.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>From our point of view, in addition to asserting that the implementation deadline is non-negotiable, the European Union should provide clarity and certainty about the implementation of all aspects of the regulation. Peru is committed to addressing the threats of climate change, global warming and deforestation, and has therefore implemented strategies and regulations in this area. Of course, we agree with the European Union's objective. However, we believe that in order to achieve this, measures that unnecessarily restrict trade should be avoided.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.10-->
                    <paragraph id="17.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We cannot lose sight of the fact that one of the drivers of deforestation is poverty and a lack of opportunities to earn an income legally. In that context, international trade is certainly a valuable tool that we need to encourage. In our case, cocoa and coffee, which fall within the scope of the European Union's regulation, are crops that currently help thousands of small-scale producers to abandon the illicit crops that fuel drug trafficking. Lastly, we reiterate our request to the European Union to respond in writing to the questions we circulated together with other Members regarding details of the regulation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.11</statement_number>
