                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.13</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of India delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.14-->
                    <paragraph id="17.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>On the agenda, we thank the co-sponsors, particularly Honduras who presented, on behalf of the co-sponsors, for bringing this particular issue to the General Council, which we have discussed at length in Committee on Trade and Environment. Chair, our paper JOB/TE/78/Rev.1 submitted jointly with South Africa highlights our broad concerns with the growing list of environment related trade measures. Despite claiming to make an environmental impact, these measures exclude from design the well-established principles of global environmental law such as common but differentiated responsibilities (CBDR), respective capabilities and the concept of nationally determined contributions (NDCs). It was heartening to listen to our colleague from EU today reiterating the COP outcome and I hope that the outcome in</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.15-->
                    <paragraph id="17.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>COP21 on common but differentiated responsibilities (CBDR), respective capabilities (RC) and nationally determined contributions (NDCs) later on would be respected by EU in future. Specifically in the case of this EU deforestation regulation, we have voiced our concerns both bilaterally as well as here in the WTO. This regulation qualifies as a perfect example of a typical non-tariff measure, blocking the market access of developing countries to the EU market, while providing no evidence that the regulation will meet the intended objectives outlined by the European Union. The regulation in its current form, heavily empowers EU's own economic operators in seeking business critical data from the exporters, disregards efforts being made on afforestation by European Union's trade partners and imposes its own regulatory choices without accounting for the operational conditions prevailing in other countries. The regulation will also harm will also harm segments like women working as farm labor, women entrepreneurs in agriculture, as well as the MSMEs whose interests the European Union apparently seeks to preserve in this Organization.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.16</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Panama delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.17-->
                    <paragraph id="17.17">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As a proponent of this agenda item, Panama also wishes to express its deep concern, shared by the Panamanian production sector, at this European Union's Regulation. A great deal of uncertainty remains over its application, particularly with respect to the traceability and geolocation requirements. The Regulation poses a systemic challenge that affects the entire multilateral trading system and the rules on which it is based.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.18-->
                    <paragraph id="17.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We therefore reiterate our requests for the European Union: to rapidly craft implementing regulations and guidelines that provide clarity to operators and producers from third countries, specifying the requirements, stages and time frames of each procedure; to incorporate differentiated compliance and due diligence standards tailored to the different situations of developing countries, in order to foster an environmentally conscious but also equitable and inclusive regulation; to provide developing countries with assistance comparable to the one received by their own producers and operators to avoid discrimination that further skews the playing field; to provide appropriate cooperation to retribute conservation efforts to countries with comparatively high rates of conservation; and to provide for more stringent rules and cut-off dates for restoration applicable to its own producers, and refrain from applying its conservation ideals in a discriminatory and extraterritorial manner.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.19-->
                    <paragraph id="17.19">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Panama is one of the very few carbon-negative countries. Although we share the European Union's environmental objectives, we reiterate that they cannot be achieved by regulating the production of third countries through a one-size-fits-all approach.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
