                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.31</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Cameroon, in national capacity and on behalf of the African Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.32-->
                    <paragraph id="17.32">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Cameroon fully shares the concerns that have been expressed, in particular by Honduras and the sponsors of the document.  We would like to express to our partners in the EU that these measures are counterproductive for our economy, which is basically a forest and agriculture economy. We believe that environmental protection can be addressed with different solutions in mind, however we believe that any measure should be adopted constructively and in close consultation with other stakeholders. We will therefore join others in the expression of interest in this matter.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.33-->
                    <paragraph id="17.33">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The African Group thanks the co-sponsors of this communication on the European Union's Deforestation Regulation. The African Group shares the European Union's commitment to the environment, but has reservations and serious concerns about this Regulation, as we believe that the climate agenda should not be used to promote unilateral and protectionist measures and create competitive disadvantages to restrict foreign competition on many products.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.34-->
                    <paragraph id="17.34">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The implications of the European Union Deforestation Regulation extend to millions of small farmers producing agricultural products. Many small farmers will now face the challenge of assuring buyers that they have produced the products lawfully. Why use the concept of fixing land and forests in the case of foreign countries, and not use the concept of deforestation in Europe in its strictest sense?</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.35-->
                    <paragraph id="17.35">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is important to note that no international agreement calls for the complete conservation of forests in their original forms and sizes. In fact, no country could agree to this. The rezoning of agricultural land as construction plots seen in Europe could thus be challenged, as vegetation is replaced with concrete, notwithstanding regreening initiatives. Consequently, States have undertaken, on the one hand, to manage their forests sustainably and, on the other hand, to work to preserve biodiversity. This includes reforestation, and the management and protection of wetlands. The Regulation also re-examines some provisions of international law.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.36-->
                    <paragraph id="17.36">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In addition, the Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism fails to take into account historic contributions of countries to current pollution levels, meaning certain countries and regions such as Africa have a favorable balance. Africa is responsible for less than 5 per cent of total global greenhouse gas emissions and is home to the world's second-largest forest lung, the Congo Basin. A weighted approach that takes into account common but differentiated responsibilities is not only fair, but also consistent with the foundations of international environmental law. The African Group remains open to any new meaningful discussions or constructive and transparent deliberations.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.37</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Nepal, on behalf of the LDC Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.38-->
                    <paragraph id="17.38">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The LDC Group commends the co-sponsors for their communication on the European Union Regulation on Zero Deforestation and Forest Degradation (EUDR). As we have stated several times here in the General Council and in other WTO bodies, we recognize the right of each Member to adopt measures to mitigate the effects of climate change. However, we believe that Members' national laws must be compatible with WTO rules as well as the principles of international environmental law such as SDT and common but differentiated responsibility.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.39-->
                    <paragraph id="17.39">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The European Union's unilateral trade measures adopted under the aegis of environmental protection, particularly the EUDR, risk increasing the range of non-tariff measures that our exports already face. This risks further weakening the integration of LDCs into the multilateral trading system.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.40-->
                    <paragraph id="17.40">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The EUDR targets a group of seven commodities: livestock, cocoa, coffee, palm oil, rubber, soy, and wood, as well as their derivatives. The majority of these products are exported by LDCs. This EU regulation and the strict and unclear criteria of its benchmarking mechanism and due diligence process risk restricting LDC access markets and endangering LDC economies that depend on export of these products leading to the loss of hundreds of thousands of jobs and increase in poverty in LDCs. These risks are causing serious socio-political problems in LDCs, as well as waves of massive emigration.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.41-->
                    <paragraph id="17.41">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>LDCs urge the European Union to seek multilaterally viable and smooth solutions to combat deforestation across the world by implementing relevant provisions of WTO rules and other international instruments to facilitate adaptation to climate change with a view to achieving a better impact in terms of mitigating its effects. A clear commitment for environmentally friendly technology transfer to developing countries and additional climate financing must be ensured in this regard. The LDC group also requests to keep the CBDR-RC principle at the heart of any policy on climate and environment.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.42</statement_number>
