                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.46-->
                    <paragraph id="17.46">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank the proponents for their communication regarding the European Union's Deforestation Regulation. Although Malaysia and the proponents are thousands of miles apart, we share similar concerns, and Malaysia is of the view that the proposal is timely. As a background, Malaysia, along with 16 other countries, has expressed our concerns regarding the EUDR in a joint letter sent to the European Parliament, European Council, and European Commission in September 2023. Additionally, we were among the 14 signatories that voiced our concerns on a similar issue, in a joint letter sent in July 2022 to the European Parliament and European Council.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.47-->
                    <paragraph id="17.47">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Our foremost concern is that the current form of the EUDR overlooks the specific circumstances, capabilities, and national legislations of developing producer countries. By unilaterally implementing a benchmarking system, the regulation fails to acknowledge and understand the efforts made by these countries to combat deforestation; and at the same time may potentially violate WTO obligations.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.48-->
                    <paragraph id="17.48">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Furthermore, the European Union's unilateral approach through due diligence and traceability disregards the diverse local conditions. This measure imposes significant costs on exporters, importers, producers, and consumers without guaranteeing effective reduction in deforestation rates.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.49-->
                    <paragraph id="17.49">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In conclusion, we urge the European Union to continue its engagement with other members, and to consider all the feedback objectively. Malaysia believes that by working together – we could establish 'greater trust' and find a balanced solution that promote sustainable practices, while taking into account the unique circumstances and challenges faced by other members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.50</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Samoa, on behalf of the ACP Group, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.51-->
                    <paragraph id="17.51">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The ACP Group identifies with some of the concerns expressed in WT/GC/W/912 by the co-sponsors. An overarching concern for us is the impact of the regulation on the capacity of smallholder producers in our countries to comply with higher export standards and information requirements. This could lead to exclusion of smallholders and Indigenous peoples and local communities from high-value supply chains, due to their lack of resources and know-how to comply, which would have adverse consequences for global progress with respect to the achievement of SDGs 1, 2, 10 and others.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.52-->
                    <paragraph id="17.52">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We believe that the implementing acts, regulations and guidelines need to provide adequate protection against not only exclusions of smallholders, but protection of the rights of local communities to manage and restore forests, and protection against inadvertently exacerbating land tenure security issues and/or any human-rights risks in developing country producer regions. Such protections would ensure that the European Union regulation does not unintentionally exacerbate global deforestation, contrary to the regulation's goals. The regulation is expected to shrink supply chains to improve traceability. This may have the unintentional consequence of expanding large scale agriculture at the expense of small- scale, leading to greater land conflicts as well.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.53-->
                    <paragraph id="17.53">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>A just transition to sustainable global supply chains requires inclusivity, especially for smallholders in developing countries. This, in turn, requires greater regulatory incentives for operators and traders to involve smallholders. Countries placed in 'higher' risk category, in turn, require adequate support to transition to sustainable practices, including through funding and development co-operation programmes, such as that of European Union's Forest Partnerships. Therefore, we support the call by the co-sponsors for the provision of assistance measurable to what the European Union provides domestically.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.54-->
                    <paragraph id="17.54">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>As supply chains can often be difficult and costly to trace, we agree that the concern is real that operators and traders subject to the Regulation may shift their sourcing to the countries designated by the European Union as 'low-risk' at the expense of suppliers from 'high-risk countries,' even if the latter may be compliant with the requirements of the EUDR. In this regard, more clarity is required with respect to the benchmarking systems that the European Union will be utilizing, its parameters, and the compatibility issues that have been raised with respect to the non-discrimination principles of the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.55</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the Russian Federation delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.56-->
                    <paragraph id="17.56">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to echo concerns expressed by Members in respect of the deforestation-free regulation. The European Union continues to stick to the practice of introducing unilateral and WTO incompatible trade-related restrictive measures under the pretext of environmental protection and combating climate change. The consequences associated with the full operation of the policies implementing the European Green Deal such as this particular regulation as well as the CBAM appear to be distorting traditional trade flows and supply chains, undermining Members' rights to apply appropriate policies to address environmental challenges as well as decreasing the global prosperity, especially of developing countries.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.57-->
                    <paragraph id="17.57">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The measures that the European Union attempts to justify by "sustainability" are neither based on the rules and principles of the Multilateral Trading System nor on global environmental agreements. The EU merely aims at protecting its domestic industries from imports and improving its competitive advantages on global markets.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.58-->
                    <paragraph id="17.58">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Furthermore, from the systemic standpoint, the EU seeks to replace the concept of a "product" as an object of consumption implied in the GATT with the idea that a product is the "result of a production process", while completely ignoring the current understanding of a "like product" which is the result of a long-standing consensus. Along with that, I would like to recall that the reasons why this Organization was founded in the first place were to enhance trade and increase prosperity rather than create new restrictions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.59-->
                    <paragraph id="17.59">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Bearing all this in mind, I would like to point out that Brussels neglects the attempts to find a common solution for the existing challenges at the multilateral level, preferring unilateral agenda and trying to establish a friend-shoring approach leading to the fragmentation and destruction of the Multilateral Trading System.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.60</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Chile delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.61-->
                    <paragraph id="17.61">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We appreciate the communication from Honduras on behalf of a group of Latin American countries. We believe that the urgency of the triple climate crisis requires the WTO to strengthen and deepen its analysis of how trade can and must help tackle the crisis, but in the least restrictive manner possible. In our view, this should be done through discussions on wide-ranging topics. We welcome the communication submitted on this issue. We are examining its substance, and we will continue to follow the matter very closely as part of the discussions on trade and environment both in this Council and in the CTE.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.62</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Canada delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.63-->
                    <paragraph id="17.63">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Canada shares many of the concerns that have been raised today in this room, and we look forward to engagement by the European Union at the WTO on this very important matter.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.64</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Norway delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.65-->
                    <paragraph id="17.65">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would like to thank the proponents for this communication (WT/GC/W/912). Norway considers it critical that we tackle deforestation and forest degradation. During the last 15 years, we have disbursed more than 5 billion dollars to rainforest protection in developing countries. The Norwegian parliament just approved a 30 per cent increase in the budget for the Norwegian International Climate and Forest Initiative for 2024.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.66-->
                    <paragraph id="17.66">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Norway has together with 147 other countries and the European Union signed the Glasgow Leaders' Declaration on Forest and Land Use, where we commit to halt and reverse forest loss and land degradation by 2030. Forest and land use can contribute as much as one third to reach the temperature target of the Paris agreement. More than two thirds of terrestrial biodiversity are found in the world's forests. Norway supports a number of tropical forest countries transition to deforestation- free value chains. Developing countries cannot stop demand side pressure on forests alone- they need our support.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.67-->
                    <paragraph id="17.67">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We view the European Union Deforestation Regulation as an important contribution to the reduction of deforestation and forest degradation. At the same time, we do clearly understand that this is challenging for many WTO Members, as illustrated in the communication under discussion. It is important that the European Union implements and further develops the Regulation in a manner that is transparent and takes into account the concerns of Members that are directly impacted. We commend the European Union's assurances in this regard.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
