                    <statement_number>17.70</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Thailand delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.71-->
                    <paragraph id="17.71">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Thailand supports the statement made by Honduras and we want to register our interest in the EU's deforestation regulation. In its implementation with our private sector, we have heard a lot of concerns, which we have heard today, not only from Thailand. We believe that this one-size-fits-all approach may not be the most effective solution to arrive at the objective that the European Union is looking for. We also value the EU's attempt to keep transparency and constantly providing updates on these measure under the CTE and other information sessions, but we believe that this has not been enough, or sufficient.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.72-->
                    <paragraph id="17.72">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I met with the private sector here in Geneva two weeks ago and they have specifically talked to me about how vague, or how unclear the implementation of this regulation is; particularly in the registration of commercial forest, which in Thailand is a bigger part of where we make our products. But there is no way the European Union can assure how to ascertain the registration of such commercial plantations, not indigenous plantations. So, we look forward to continuing the discussion on this matter and we would like to seek more clarification from the European Union, particularly on the implementation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.73</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.74-->
                    <paragraph id="17.74">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We wish to thank the group of Latin American countries for submitting document WT/GC/W/912. We reject the application of any unilateral measure that has a negative impact on the multilateral trading system, particularly on developing Members and LDCs. We share the Latin American group's concern about the regulation in question, which is a clear example of a unilateral measure that regulates production in third countries, selects a one-size-fits-all type of solution, is the result of insufficient dialogue and creates tensions between multilateral trade and environmental regimes. We wish to reiterate that the WTO has proved to be an organization that is primarily guided by economic considerations and sound legal rules. The very definition of unilateralism implies conduct that violates principles and rules. In this connection, we call for a return to multilateralism as the best way to resolve our differences and we express our support for a forward-looking, transparent and inclusive multilateral trading system founded on consensus-based rules.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.75</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Colombia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.76-->
                    <paragraph id="17.76">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to echo the statement made by Ambassador Castillo. With regard to decarbonization, we are the first oil-producing country to join the Fossil Fuel Non-Proliferation Treaty, and our environmental goals are very ambitious. With regard to deforestation, we reduced deforestation by 70 per cent last year. However, despite this, we will be assessed and, regardless of the result, our most vulnerable exporters will have to meet requirements that will increase their costs and limit their options. Therefore, although we are advancing more quickly, being more ambitious and seriously discussing fossil fuels and other issues, our producers will still be penalized.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.77-->
                    <paragraph id="17.77">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This situation can be improved and needs to be reviewed. The large number and diversity of countries concerned about this issue speak for themselves and should give our European partners pause for thought.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.78</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the European Union delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.79-->
                    <paragraph id="17.79">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This is an important point for many Members. It is also an important topic for the European Union, which is why we have engaged on the Deforestation Regulation at length in various committees), and we have organized several informal sessions and workshops.  We have all made the commitment, under the Sustainable Development Goals, to halt deforestation by 2020. Clearly, this has not been achieved. And that is why 143 producer and consumer countries including the European Union pledged to halt and reverse forest loss by 2030 as part of the Glasgow Leaders Declaration on Forests and Land Use. If we want to achieve this goal, we need to act. And with continued alarming rates of deforestation globally – we need to act now.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.80-->
                    <paragraph id="17.80">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The Deforestation Regulation is part of our response. The European Union contributes to deforestation by consuming a significant share of products associated with deforestation and forest degradation. We therefore have the responsibility to contribute to more sustainable value chains and foster more sustainable consumption, production, and trade. But we also understand we cannot do it alone. We are committed to implementing the Deforestation Regulation in a spirit of close partnership, transparency, and open dialogue. This is why we have closely engaged with all Members, when preparing the Regulation. And why we have intensified these efforts once the Regulation was adopted.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.81-->
                    <paragraph id="17.81">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>These exchanges are a two-way street: on the one hand, we are keen to help business and regulators understand the Regulation better; on the other, they are useful opportunities for us to better understand concerns, and feed our ongoing reflection on what further tools are necessary to facilitate its smooth implementation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.82-->
                    <paragraph id="17.82">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Going forward, we will continue our close engagement with all of you in the run-up to the Regulation's entry into application in December 2024 and beyond. Via bilateral channels as well as deforestation-specific platforms such as the EU Multi-Stakeholder Platform on Protecting and Restoring the World's Forests, or the Initiative on deforestation-free supply chains and the Sustainable Cocoa Initiative. We will also continue the dialogue on this matter in the WTO. In January, on 9 January, I have invited, Ms. Florika Fink-Hooijer, Director-General of the European Commission in charge of the EU's Deforestation Regulation for a dialogue with the WTO Ambassadors in Geneva, which I hope you will be able to attend.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.83-->
                    <paragraph id="17.83">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We have also heard your concerns on the risk categorization. This is why we have decided to take more time to finalize the assessment, so as to allow for constructive engagement and dialogue with trading partners in this regard. The risk categorization will take into consideration objective and internationally recognized data, as well as efforts undertaken to fight deforestation and forest degradation nationally and globally. Our intention is to prepare this assessment through extensive dialogue with interested trading partners.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.84-->
                    <paragraph id="17.84">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>European Union Delegations throughout the world will be reaching out to your respective ministries to invite you to feed the information into the risk assessment process. In addition, we will also seek your input on trade facilitating tools (for example, guidelines on implementation, repository of best practices on due diligence, or financial support). We encourage you to share all the information that you may consider relevant, including on ongoing sustainability initiatives at national and/or regional level, as well as on emerging best practices.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 17.85-->
                    <paragraph id="17.85">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We can only succeed in halting deforestation if we join forces. We look forward to continuing our cooperation and dialogue to meet our shared climate and biodiversity goals and to protect the world's forests for the benefit of all.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>17.86</statement_number>
