                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>18.64</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.65-->
                    <paragraph id="18.65">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First of all, I would like to join previous speakers to express my heartfelt appreciation to the co-coordinators for sharing the Information on Investment Facilitation for Development, for their concise but comprehensive report, as well as their commendable leadership in steering the IFD negotiations. The significance of investment has been widely acknowledged. The G20 New Delhi Leaders' Declaration emphasized the importance of investment in promoting trade and economic growth, eliminating hunger, delivering quality education, implementing energy transition and enhancing women empowerment.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.66-->
                    <paragraph id="18.66">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The G20 trade and investment ministerial meeting chaired by India also underlined the positive role of investment facilitation in promoting sustainable and inclusive global value chains, and supported deliberations at WTO on intersections between trade and investment. IFD was also discussed by G20 trade and investment Ministers. In the WTO, more and more members have shown their support to the IFD. Currently 117 members have joined the IFD. And more members are coming on broad. For the non-participants, some are favorably considering it, pending domestic procedures, while others would not oppose adding the IFD Agreement into Annex 4 of the WTO Agreement. Through recent collective outreach efforts, it is clear that the vast majority of non-participants can bless the IFD. Counting these Members, the IFD agreement is either participated or blessed by at least over 95 per cent of WTO Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.67-->
                    <paragraph id="18.67">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The broad support and engagement from a diverse range of the WTO members underscore the importance of IFD, in particular its role of attracting FDI to make up for the investment deficit faced by developing members. It could help the WTO meet the 2030 Sustainable Development Goals. Investment Facilitation for Development, as its name implies, is a development-oriented agreement, with four distinctive developmental dimensions. First, it is an agreement that was initiated and launched by a group of developing members and widely supported by members from all regions and levels of development. Second, it is an agreement that developing members have made substantial contributions, with two-thirds of text-based proposals either came from, or were co-sponsored by, developing or LDC members. Third, it is an agreement with a dedicated development chapter, embodying elements of S&amp;DT, need assessment, technical assistance, and capacity building. Fourth, it is an agreement that is conducive to increase industrial production capacity and diversification and could provide for the exact kind of policy space and business environment that are needed by the developing countries for economic growth and transformation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.68-->
                    <paragraph id="18.68">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is the common aspiration of all Members to make the WTO relevant to our times by reinvigorating its negotiating functions, in particular on issues of development. The IFD Agreement is the best example in this regard. As we are making every endeavor to prepare the upcoming MC13 outcome, it is worth recalling the spirit of good faith and cooperation which had empowered members to achieve unprecedented success in the MC12. We are ready to engage and discuss further with all members including non-participating members, to support the inclusion of the IFD agreement into Annex 4 of the WTO Agreement at MC13. Together, let us deliver.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
