                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.113-->
                    <paragraph id="18.113">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I will try to be brief, as we have a very long statement. So, I will share it with the Secretariat for the consumption of every Member. India would like to thank the coordinators for submitting this proposal and if you recall day before yesterday, there was a specific clarification or question from India, whether this proposal is coming for information. It was said that yes, it is coming for information and chair you also said that your view is also that it is for information. I thank all the respondents or the proponents who have spoken on this topic. I would like to take some of us back in memory and I am sure those who were here in 2017, during the May General Council meeting may be aware of the historical facts of this subject. There are four things to recall.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.114-->
                    <paragraph id="18.114">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>One is what we call July 2004 framework. This I would like to place on record as part of our statement. The document number WT/L/579 of 2 August 2004, which is covering that July framework and that is the July 2004 GC decision which actually give a negative mandate - negative forget non-mandated, it gave a negative mandate to this topic. Then we come to Nairobi Ministerial which was not in WTO context, not very distant. It was in 2015, eight years back. The paragraph 34 of Nairobi Ministerial declaration - I would again like to put that on record as part of my statement. I will not repeat those paragraphs or those documents. Paragraph 34 of Nairobi Ministerial declaration again continued the negative mandate. I am not saying non-mandated issues but negative mandate of Ministers not to have negotiations on this subject.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.115-->
                    <paragraph id="18.115">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Then, of course we had in 2017 the GC deliberation over two days, 10 and 18 May 2017. The minutes are available in WT/GC/M/167, which is dated 21 July 2017. So, this is the third document which I would like to place on record as part of my statement, giving the background of this topic and the last document which, I would like to quote is the document presented by Namibia, South Africa and India, which is WT/GC/W/819/Rev.1 that is the legal status of JSIs. I will not get into the substance of this agreement, and I will only talk about the process. As per the provisions of Article III.2 and Article X of the Marrakesh Agreement, any new disciplines, needing discussions require agreements of all WTO Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.116-->
                    <paragraph id="18.116">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Second, in 2017 General Council meeting, India had objection to the adoption of the agenda, citing reservations about the procedural part of General Council functioning. In that response, if we read the minutes of that meeting, some of the proponents who have spoken today, several countries stated that informal dialogue is only aimed at information sharing instead of negotiation. Further, India was asked to allow the agenda that it was not a proposal to start any negotiations. They were taking this opportunity to inform other Members of an informal process they wanted to initiate.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 18.117-->
