        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>19</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>ENHANCING MULTILATERAL DELIBERATIVE FUNCTION ON ENVIRONMENT-RELATED TRADE MEASURES AND FOSTERING SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT - REQUEST FROM CHINA AND COLOMBIA</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 19.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson invited China or Colombia to introduce the agenda item "Enhancing Multilateral Deliberative Function on Environment-Related Trade Measures and Fostering Sustainable Development".</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.2</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.3-->
                    <paragraph id="19.3">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Under this item, I will deliver an overall statement representing both China and Colombia. Following that, Colombia will provide a supplementary statement addressing the intersection of international trade and environmental laws. The link between trade and environment is vitally recognized. Trade policies are increasingly being used as a policy tool for environmental purposes.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.4-->
                    <paragraph id="19.4">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Environmental policies on the other hand affect more and more trade flows. The WTO could and should play a more prominent role in ensuring the mutual supportiveness of trade regimes and environment regimes and in deliberating concrete multilateral trade solutions to respond to global environmental challenges and foster sustainable development. In this regard, we are greatly encouraged by the revitalized discussions in the Committee on Trade and Environment pursuant to MC12 mandate. A large number of proposals were submitted, transparency and experience sharing exercises were carried out and a first thematic session on trade and energy transition was held on the reform by doing basis.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.5-->
                    <paragraph id="19.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Meanwhile, many Members' have voiced their concerns on unilateral and actual territorial environmental measures affecting trade, which may act against the multilateral cooperation and have significant trade impacts for Members, especial developing Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.6-->
                    <paragraph id="19.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Against this background, more and more Members have advocated for enhancing the deliberative function of the WTO to respond to global environmental challenges. That is why China and Colombia requested to have this item on this GC agenda, we believe MC13 offers a valuable opportunity for such purposes and invites Members to consider the following ideas for potential MC13 outcomes.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.7-->
                    <paragraph id="19.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>First, a strong political commitment to multilateral cooperative approaches to address global environmental challenges, including reiterating the principles among others that "measures taken to combat climate change, including unilateral ones, should not constitute a means of arbitrary or unjustifiable discrimination or a disguised restriction on international trade". Second, setting up a multilateral mechanism such as a standing Agenda item in CTE for enhancing multilateral deliberative functions on environment-related trade measures and environmental measures affecting trade. Such agenda could include the following elements: (i) enhance the transparency and deliberation of environment-related trade measures and environmental measures affecting trade through structured and informative dialogue among Members, to allow meaningful exchange of views on policy designs, attend to the environmental affects and potential market access impact, particularly on developing countries. (ii) examine the interplay between international trade and environmental laws, to ensure a coherent, mutually supportive and harmonious rapport between international trade and environmental policies. (iii) identify policy instruments within the mandate of the WTO that can support members' efforts on combating environmental challenges and achieving the Sustainable Development Goals, including for example trade liberalization and facilitation for the deployment of environmental goods and services, advancement for facilitation to foster green supply chains and green trade, technology transfer and diffusion to accelerate energy transition or other relevant policy tools with a special focus on development dimensions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.8-->
                    <paragraph id="19.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>These elements are by no means exhaustive, we encourage all members to offer their ideas to enhancing the deliberative function of WTO for sustainable development purposes. The global environmental challenges are real which require real actions from trade outside as the WTO. Let us commit ourselves to moving from vision to reality from MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.9</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Colombia delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.10-->
                    <paragraph id="19.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Colombia supports the comments made by China under this agenda item and aligns itself with China's statement. We would also like to add the following. Multilateral environmental fora are probably the most important fora in the world at this time. The three fundamental environmental conventions, in addition to their respective conferences of the parties (COP) and the agreements resulting from them, are the keys to a common and shared future. Within these forums, they assess the situation and the main causes of environmental problems, prioritize some activities over others and negotiate the balances and the ways in which the main objectives should be met.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.11-->
                    <paragraph id="19.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We see relatively little of this at the WTO. We focus on our usual tools with a certain disconnection from the overall picture. We discuss existing trade measures that have an impact on the environment, but often overlook the fact that there are other measures that are deemed to be much more important and that there are different, negotiated ways of doing things. It does not necessarily have to be this way. Here at the WTO, we could start by carrying out joint and periodic reviews of the findings made, and agreements reached at the environmental COPs.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.12-->
                    <paragraph id="19.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This is a necessity, including from a legal standpoint. The rules of public trade law cannot be considered in "clinical isolation" from the rules of public environmental law, as was stressed by the Appellate Body in US — Gasoline. This means that WTO rules must be interpreted in a manner that is consistent and in harmony with other areas of law and, first and foremost, with international environmental law. The conclusions reached within the environmental forums, the priorities agreed, the fundamental principles governing both spheres and the negotiated ways of doing things cannot be ignored, as they are an integral part of our rule book.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.13-->
                    <paragraph id="19.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Within the WTO, we have entered into a somewhat controversial and complex discussion on the principle of common but differentiated responsibilities, which has generated significant opposition. However, we are of the view that this point is just one aspect of a much bigger picture. We should enhance our discussions by using all of the principles, findings, conclusions, priorities and agreements established within the environmental forums. Perhaps we are the ones who should adapt to them, rather than applying unilateral trade measures that fail to take adequate account of what has been achieved in these forums' negotiations.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.14-->
                    <paragraph id="19.14">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In addition, despite the major difficulties, the discussions within environmental forums are conducted in a much more cooperative way that recognizes important nuances. I will give some examples, all of which are taken from statements made by large delegations. In environmental forums, they recognize that the subsidization of certain activities has significant adverse environmental effects, whereas, here, in the main forum for discussing subsidies, we prefer to refrain from talking seriously about limiting them. In environmental forums, they recognize that energy goals must take into account energy poverty, whereas, here, we ignore arguments about poverty and opt instead for unilateral trade measures that have a particular impact on the most vulnerable. In environmental forums, they say that we need to grant more support to the developing world, including technology and technology transfer, whereas, here, we say that it is not something to be spoken about. In environmental forums, they work on the basic premise that we should set environmental goals and see how each country can contribute based on its capacity, whereas, here, we discuss one-size-fits-all measures that are imposed from above. In environmental forums, they recognize that developed countries need to move faster, whereas, here, we deny the existence of certain principles and of common but differentiated responsibilities in particular.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.15-->
                    <paragraph id="19.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>It is not, therefore, just a legal or logical necessity. We truly need to familiarize ourselves with the environmental forums, to improve our discussions with them and to learn from their positions. The WTO has made some important, albeit tentative, progress in this regard. The Trade Day at COP28, supported by the Director-General and the Secretariat, is good news. The revitalization of the Committee on Trade and Environment, under the leadership of Ecuador, is good news. The discussions and documents on environmental principles, including the forum promoted by Colombia during the Public Forum, are good news. While the study proposed by the Chief Economist on carbon pricing based on environmental principles appeared to be good news, we are yet to see this study despite the fact that it was announced more than nine months ago.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.16-->
                    <paragraph id="19.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>These pathways for improved discussions between both spheres need to be strengthened and, above all, maintained. The WTO cannot deny or ignore what is happening in the most important multilateral forums of our time. The WTO cannot and should not be a silo and should strive to remain in step with the progress that our own countries are making in multilateral environmental forums.  We apologize for the fact that we have not submitted documents at this stage. It is partly because we wanted to hear about and highlight the progress and most significant interventions made at the recent COP28, which ended just a couple of days ago, precisely as part of this deliberative exercise among forums that we are proposing.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.17</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Brazil delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.18-->
                    <paragraph id="19.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>My delegation thanks China and Colombia for requesting the agenda item. Brazil echoes and supports China's statement. We would also like to acknowledge the collaborative ongoing work with a number of developing countries on the current and future work of the CTE; It is our understanding that the CTE should promote multilateral and collaborative strategies that ensure trade and environmental policies are mutually supportive and effectively contribute to the overarching objective of sustainable development; Among other things, we believe the CTE should: (i) examine the interplay between trade and environmental laws, focusing on their concepts, principles and responsibilities, to ensure a balanced and harmonious rapport between multilateral regimes in the pursuit of sustainable development; (ii) enhance the transparency and monitoring of trade measures used for environmental purposes and of environmental measures which have significant trade effects, through a meaningful dialogue among Members on their fundamentals and their consistency with relevant trade and environmental concepts, principles, and responsibilities. We will continue to work closely with other delegations in this area, including with a view to possible outcomes at MC13.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
