                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.24</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Egypt delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.25-->
                    <paragraph id="19.25">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank China and Colombia for putting this item on the agenda and we share many of the elements mentioned. We advocate for the initiation of multilateral discussions, within the framework of the CTE mandate, concerning environment-related trade measures and their implications for market access especially on developing and least developed countries. These discussions should prioritize supporting developing countries and LDCs through capacity building, financial assistance, and proper technology transfer programs and initiatives. The objective should be to mitigate the adverse effects, particularly those stemming from unilateral measures, on their market shares and promote sustainable development and multilateral solutions. MC13 presents an opportune moment to launch such a discussion.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.26-->
                    <paragraph id="19.26">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We reiterate our position that the environment-related trade measures should be consistent with WTO rules and have no harmful effects on other countries, especially developing countries and LDCs. These measures should be transparent and should take into consideration the diverse level of development of member states and capacity constraints of developing countries and LDCs. These measures should avoid creating unnecessary or disguised barriers to trade flows and market access, especially for developing countries, to help them increase their share in international trade, as recognized in paras. 1 and 2 of the Marrakesh agreement.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.27-->
                    <paragraph id="19.27">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Furthermore, we believe that MC13 should establish discussion on the relationship between trade, environment and development and how to ensure coherence and complementarity between WTO work and negotiations under UNFCCC and other multilateral environmental agreements. The conference should also give a mandate to discuss the set of guidelines and principles that should guide the relationship between trade and environment in WTO and how to ensure that the environment-related trade measures are in line with longstanding environmental rules and principles, especially the principles of equity and CBDR.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
