                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.64</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Switzerland delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.65-->
                    <paragraph id="19.65">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank China and Colombia for their interventions. As we all know, the whole planet is facing climate change, pollution and biodiversity loss and some Members may face bigger consequences. These issues require international collaboration and an approach that includes all policy fields, including trade. In other words, trade has to contribute to the solution, and we believe that these global issues need a global answer, which means all hands-on deck. We support enhancing the deliberative function on trade and environmental sustainability issues at the CTE.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.66-->
                    <paragraph id="19.66">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>However, in principle, we believe that some of the concepts that are put forward by China and Colombia have not been agreed on in other international fora and remain controversial. We would therefore be cautious when using the term "guiding principles". Importing political polarization from other fora would not help our discussions in the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.67-->
                    <paragraph id="19.67">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In our view a discussion on the implications of a controversial and sometimes misunderstood principle in the WTO will not lead us any further, and we are here to discuss concrete topics in the environment-trade nexus and how the WTO can play a meaningful role in addressing environmental challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.68-->
                    <paragraph id="19.68">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We should rather focus on the fundamental question, which is how trade can contribute to mitigation of and adaptation to climate change and how trade related measures can address climate change – including how S&amp;DT provisions can be utilized. S&amp;DT is a clearly defined concept at the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.69-->
                    <paragraph id="19.69">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We encourage Members to focus discussions on concrete actions rather than having discussions on principles, that might not lead us any further.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.70</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the United Kingdom delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.71-->
                    <paragraph id="19.71">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>2023 is set to be the hottest year on record, dangerously nearing the 1.5-degree threshold. As our Ministers return from the UAE, we are pleased to see the first Trade and Finance Day at COP. We should feel the collective push behind us to make real progress here in this Organization. While we work the work that the DG and Secretariat have done, if I may, just encourage a little more engagement and transparency with Members in advance so that we can really help and contribute to that work.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.72-->
                    <paragraph id="19.72">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The CTE and its recent reinvigoration is a key part of working here on what Members can do to tackle the climate crisis, alongside other environmental challenges.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.73-->
                    <paragraph id="19.73">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We welcome the process and thank the CTE Chair to really drive this forward.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.74-->
                    <paragraph id="19.74">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In June, the UK tabled its own paper on how to revitalize the deliberative functions of the CTE, and make sure it works for all Members, in line with our wider reform efforts. This included practical steps to improve the efficiency and inclusivity of our work.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.75-->
                    <paragraph id="19.75">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We started we thematic sessions and it is great to see that these are now underway. It is the UK's view that the discussion at the CTE work better when they are thematic to preserve the CTE's valuable function as a forum for dialogue and exchange, rather than litigation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.76-->
                    <paragraph id="19.76">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>They should aim to foster a more rigorous analysis of emerging policies and evidence. Members, with stakeholders' support, can and should take time to explore what good policy design could look like. We also wish to emphasis the bottom-up, pragmatic work on trade policy solutions. This is the key added value of the CTE and we seek to not duplicate the existing WTO functions and the work that is done elsewhere.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.77</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Japan delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.78-->
                    <paragraph id="19.78">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Japan thanks China and Colombia for the initial introduction of the ideas on this agenda.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.79-->
                    <paragraph id="19.79">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Japan shares the importance of enhancing the deliberative function on trade and environmental sustainability centered on the CTE. In view of deepening technical and substantial discussions on this issue, it is essential to discuss it thoroughly at the CTE rather than to bring up the issue to the General Council directly.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.80-->
                    <paragraph id="19.80">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Any Member can propose a new agenda item at the CTE. However, we do not see the necessity to set up a standing agenda item, which may result in rigid and repetitive discussions at the committee. In this regard, we welcome the fact that the CTE began the thematic sessions in November, which create a space for flexible and informal discussions, and we hope to continue constructive discussions in these sessions.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 19.81-->
                    <paragraph id="19.81">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We would also like to emphasize that, for the purpose of revitalizing the deliberation on this issue, it is genuinely necessary to find common themes on trade and environmental sustainability among all Members and to deliberate practically and constructively without repeating specific principles or positions. It is not helpful for this purpose to attempt to start formal discussions on principles, especially those from outside the scope of the WTO Agreements. We hope to have discussions that will serve to deepen mutual understanding rather than create division among Members.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>19.82</statement_number>
