        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>20</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>REVIEW OF THE EXEMPTION PROVIDED UNDER PARAGRAPH 3 OF GATT 1994 (WT/L/1165, WT/L/1178)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 20.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that paragraph 3(a) of GATT 1994 provides an exemption from Part II of GATT 1994 for measures under specific mandatory legislation – enacted by a Member before it became a contracting party to GATT 1947 – which prohibits the use, sale or lease of foreign-built or foreign-reconstructed vessels in commercial applications between points in national waters or waters of an exclusive economic zone.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 20.2-->
                <p>
                    <t>She further noted that in 1994, the United States had invoked this provision with respect to specific legislation that met the requirements of that paragraph. Paragraph 3(b) of GATT 1994 calls for a review of this exemption five years after the date of entry into force of the WTO Agreement – and thereafter every two years for as long as the exemption is in force – to examine whether the conditions for the exemption still prevail.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 20.3-->
                <p>
                    <t>The General Council last considered this matter at its meeting in March 2023. She noted at the time that statements, questions and responses from interested delegations and the United States, together with the annual reports provided by the United States, circulated in WT/L/1165 and WT/L/1178, would form the basis for this year's review. The General Council had also agreed that it would consider this matter again at the last meeting of the year in 2023.This exemption was without prejudice to solutions concerning specific aspects of the legislation covered by this exemption negotiated in sectoral agreements or in other fora.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.4</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the United States delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.5-->
                    <paragraph id="20.5">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The United States welcomes the opportunity to participate in the review of the exemption under paragraph 3 of GATT 1994. This exemption was agreed to by all Members to deal with non-conforming provisions of domestic legislation of a non-discretionary character in a specific area addressed by the exemption, and it is an integral part of the GATT 1994.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.6-->
                    <paragraph id="20.6">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In paragraph 3(a), Members agreed that as long as the legislation that the United States notified prior to the date of entry of force of the WTO Agreement remained in force and was not modified to reduce its conformity with Part II of the GATT 1994, Part II would not apply to that legislation.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.7-->
                    <paragraph id="20.7">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Paragraph 3(b) specifies that Members shall review the exemption every two years to examine "whether the conditions which created the need for the exemption still prevail."</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.8-->
                    <paragraph id="20.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The United States confirms that the conditions that created the need for this exemption continue to exist, including the US Navy's reliance on commercial shipyards for day-to-day maintenance of naval and surge-fleet vessels. It also remains critical for US shipbuilders to build commercial ships for trade in order to ensure the maintenance of a viable industrial base to meet future US naval requirements.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.9-->
                    <paragraph id="20.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>In short, the United States has the same need as it had in 1994: to maintain its shipyards' readiness to build and maintain naval vessels. The United States has also continued to provide Members with annual statistical reports under paragraph 3(c) of the GATT 1994, including the most recent report submitted in November 2023. These reports provide detailed annual reporting of vessel orders and deliveries from US shipyards.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.10-->
                    <paragraph id="20.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We thank other Members for their interest in this issue. We stand ready to answer Members' questions on the topic as needed.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.11</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Japan delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.12-->
                    <paragraph id="20.12">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The exemption provided under paragraph 3 of GATT 1994 is essentially a serious deviation from the fundamental principles of the GATT. Therefore, Japan's position is that the continuation of the provisions would undermine the consistency of the entire legal system of the WTO.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.13-->
                    <paragraph id="20.13">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Japan expressed its concern on this matter in the Trade Policy Revision of the United States last year. Japan does not think substantive explanation has been provided by the United States at the General Council on why it considers it necessary to avail of this exemption; Japan continues to ask the US to share relevant data and expects the General Council to conduct a substantial examination in order to address whether the condition which originally necessitated this exemption still exists.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.14</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of the European Union delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.15-->
                    <paragraph id="20.15">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The European Union supports this review process. I must once again underline our strong concerns with this unjustified exemption. The European Union continues to view the Jones Act as a piece of legislation that restricts fair competition in the shipbuilding and shipping markets and no longer serves a legitimate purpose in today's global economy. Even more, new implementing rules show an increasingly protectionist interpretation of the Jones Act, going even further beyond its original intention.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.16-->
                    <paragraph id="20.16">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The prevailing situation has negative economic consequences for the European Union's and other countries shipbuilding, logistics, dredging, and energy industries. But the costs are also high for the United States, which is faced with higher costs for off-shore energy production, coastal protection from flooding, adapting to climate change, and haulage services due to the closure of the US market for foreign-built, serviced, and operated ships.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.17</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Bangladesh delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.18-->
                    <paragraph id="20.18">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>Under this item, the delegation of Bangladesh takes the floor to register its appreciation on record for the United States delegation in advance as Bangladesh waits for the responses of the two questions sent to the United States on this item. Our delegation looks forward to working with the United States on this file.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.19</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Norway delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.20-->
                    <paragraph id="20.20">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>This exemption from the GATT 1994 is an important subject for Norway. Our focus is as always on the salient point of paragraph 3(b) of the GATT agreement, whether the conditions, which created the need for the exemption, still exist. This question seems even more relevant when considering the fact that the Jones Act has been in effect for more than 103 years.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.21-->
                    <paragraph id="20.21">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We note the United States emphasis in the consultations on national security and humanitarian emergency reasons, that Jones Act is critical for United States shipbuilding, not least of military vessels, and for maintaining enough qualified American mariners.  It is, however, not clear whether the United States has considered alternative measures for stimulating activity in the United States ship building sector.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.22</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Panama delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.23-->
                    <paragraph id="20.23">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I would like to thank the United States for the information that they have provided, for the meetings that they have held with interested Members, and for their ongoing readiness to engage with Members on this matter. Panama has a clear interest in matters relating to maritime services, and we would simply like to express our interest in continuing to participate in future consultations and interactions with the United States on this subject.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>20.24</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of China delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 20.25-->
                    <paragraph id="20.25">
                        <content>
                            <p>
