        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>21</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>WAIVERS UNDER ARTICLE IX OF THE WTO AGREEMENT</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 21.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that there were a number of sub-items under this agenda item. In this regard, she started by noting that the draft waiver decisions for the matters listed in sub-items 21(A) to 21(E) which had been taken up for consideration by the Council for Trade in Goods at its meeting on 30 November. For those items, the Chairperson invited the Chairperson of the Goods Council to report to the General Council.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 21.2-->
                <p>
                    <t>Ambassador Dr. Adamu Mohammed Abdulhamid (Nigeria), Chair of the Council for Trade in Goods, delivered the following report on the CTG's consideration of these matters in a single intervention:</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 21.3-->
                <p>
                    <t>I would like to report that, at its meeting of 30 November – 1 December 2023, the Council for Trade in Goods considered five collective waiver requests of extensions to the introduction of Harmonized System changes for 2002, 2007, 2012, 2017 and 2022 into WTO Schedules of Concessions, which are based on similar waivers currently in force that will expire on 31 December 2023. The Council approved the draft decisions contained in documents G/C/W/831, G/C/W/832, G/C/W/833, G/C/W/834 and G/C/W/835/Rev.1. The five draft decisions that are being put forward today for consideration by the General Council have followed the procedures provided for in Article IX:3 (b) of the Marrakesh Agreement and are contained in the documents listed in the Airgram of today's meeting. Finally, I would like to note that, at its November meeting, the CTG recommended that the five draft waiver decisions contained in these documents be forwarded to the General Council for adoption.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 21.4-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson proposed that, in accordance with the Decision-Making Procedures under Articles IX and XII of the WTO Agreement agreed in November 1995 (WT/L/93), the General Council adopt these five draft Decisions referred to by the CTG Chairperson in his report.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 21.5-->
                <p>
                    <t>The General Council so agreed.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 21.6-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson recalled that, in accordance with paragraph 4 of Article IX of the WTO Agreement, "any waiver granted for a period of more than one year shall be reviewed by the Ministerial Conference not later than one year after it is granted, and thereafter annually until the waiver terminates." She noted that there were seven waivers before the General Council for review, as listed under sub-item (f) in the proposed Agenda. She also recalled that these waivers had already been agreed by the General Council and that they were in force. Therefore, the General Council was not expected to take any new decision on their renewal or otherwise at this meeting. She further noted that five of the waivers under review provide that an annual report should be submitted by the Members concerned. The reports from these Members had been circulated in documents WT/L/1179 from Cuba, and WT/L/1173 – 1176 from the United States.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
                <!--STATEMENT INFO-->
                <statement_info>
                    <statement_number>21.7</statement_number>
                    <statement>The representative of Guyana, on behalf of CARICOM, delivered the following statement:</statement>
                </statement_info>
                <!--STATEMENT CONTENT-->
                <statement_content>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 21.8-->
                    <paragraph id="21.8">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>I take the opportunity to express CARICOM's continued appreciation of the duty-free accorded to them for access to the United States market for eligible products from the Caribbean, under the Caribbean Basin Economic Recovery Act (CBERA). As we would have stated before, the United States remains the region's largest export market and a valuable trading partner, and CBERA is of significant economic importance to CARICOM. The programme provides opportunities to expand trade between the United States and beneficiary CARICOM countries, thereby promoting the growth of economic development and opportunity in the Region. As small and vulnerable economies, CARICOM countries place significant value in this programme and we are appreciative of this continued support by the United States.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 21.9-->
                    <paragraph id="21.9">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The representative of Antigua and Barbuda, on behalf of the OECS, provided the following statement:</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 21.10-->
                    <paragraph id="21.10">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>We align with the statement by the CARICOM Group. We also thank the United States for its presentation and report. The Caribbean Basin Economic Recovery Act (CBERA) plays a vital role in the trade and economic development of OECS countries. In the past two years, four of six OECS WTO Members registered a growth in their exports to the US under CBERA. Nonetheless, it is concerning that exports are markedly down compared to a decade ago for all OECS WTO Members. This is largely representative of wider structural constraints in our economies, many of them brought on by exogenous factors. We shudder to think of what the state of exports would have been in the absence of programmes such as CBERA, notwithstanding the structural challenges. This further underscores the need for these kinds of programmes and for dedicated attention by the entire membership to provide the necessary policy space geared towards improving the terms of trade for developing Members. Again, we thank the United States for its update and look forward to continuing to build on this important trade and economic relationship with the United States.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                    <!--STATEMENT PARAGRAPH 21.11-->
                    <paragraph id="21.11">
                        <content>
                            <p>
                                <t>The General Council took note of the reports contained in the documents mentioned and of the statements.</t>
                            </p>
                        </content>
                    </paragraph>
                </statement_content>
            </statements>
        </agenda>
        <!--AGENDA-->
        <agenda>
            <!--AGENDA ITEM, HEADING-->
            <agenda_item>
                <agenda_item_number>22</agenda_item_number>
                <p>
                    <t>INTERNATIONAL TRADE CENTRE UNCTAD/WTO - REPORT OF THE JOINT ADVISORY GROUP ON ITS 57th SESSION (ITC/AG(LVII)/292)</t>
                </p>
            </agenda_item>
            <!--OPENING-->
            <opening>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.1-->
                <p>
                    <t>The Chairperson said that the CTD Chairperson would provide the General Council with a report on the CTD's consideration of the report of the Joint Advisory Group on the International Trade Centre UNCTAD/WTO. She then invited the CTD Chairperson to report on this matter.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.2-->
                <p>
                    <t>Ambassador Sánchez-Fung (Dominican Republic), Chair of the Committee on Trade and Development, delivered the following report:</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.3-->
                <p>
                    <t>The ITC's Joint Advisory Group held its 57th Session on 20 July 2023. The report on that meeting is contained in document ITC/AG(57)/292. The report was presented to the CTD at its 122nd Session on 17 November by the Chairperson of the Joint Advisory Group, Ambassador Nadia Theodore of Canada. Ambassador Theodore noted that, in an ever-evolving global trade landscape, the ITC has rightfully maintained its focus on empowering small businesses to compete in regional and global markets. Its added value is clear: the ITC presents practical and innovative solutions that small firms can use to navigate these uncertainties and build greater resilience.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.4-->
                <p>
                    <t>At the Joint Advisory Group meeting, delegations shared their perspectives on the pressing needs of countries grappling with fragility, uncertainty, and the post-pandemic recovery. What came through, loud and clear, was the importance of finding ways to connect with new markets, especially through digital platforms. Delegations recognized the ITC's role in facilitating the transfer of technology, providing market intelligence, and empowering small businesses to access and thrive in online marketplaces.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.5-->
                <p>
                    <t>It was appreciated that the ITC's value lies in its collaboration with national and international partners to identify key stakeholders and needs in beneficiary countries, adhere to global best practices, and address local challenges while navigating the intricacies of international markets.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.6-->
                <p>
                    <t>Delegations also expressed appreciation for the ITC's commitment to inclusivity and poverty reduction. The ITC's focus extends beyond merely finding new opportunities for small businesses; the organization is equally committed to ensuring that women, youth, refugees, and vulnerable communities are driving MSMEs' participation in the global economy.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.7-->
                <p>
                    <t>The SheTrades Hubs were particularly commended for providing a unique platform that encompasses training, tools, and networking opportunities to boost the competitiveness of women-led businesses. As the ITC's evaluation unit noted, these hubs are a key factor in enhancing the ITC's efficiency and effectiveness. They do so by establishing partnerships with local institutions and enabling outreach to a larger number of small businesses led and owned by women. This partnership-driven model, as a result, drives scalability to ensure maximum impact.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.8-->
                <p>
                    <t>Appreciation was also expressed for the dedication of ITC staff. This dedication extends to internal change management. The ITC Moving Forward initiative, as highlighted by the Executive Director, represents a comprehensive roadmap to build a stronger ITC, tackling prohibited conduct and fostering a better workplace culture. This is vital to ensure that the ITC continues to be an agile, responsive, and fit for purpose channel to deliver the SDGs through global trade.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.9-->
                <p>
                    <t>To summarize the discussions at the Joint Advisory Group meeting, Ambassador Theodore pointed to three main takeaways: First, there was a recognition that, despite the challenging trade and aid environment, the ITC continues to deliver at the top of its game, delivering on its core mission of ensuring the competitiveness of small businesses while adapting its offerings to address global challenges. Second, it is important for the ITC to scale up its successful approaches so that thousands more small businesses in developing countries are supported to grow and thrive sustainably. For this, there was a call for donors to keep financing the ITC's work at the intersection of trade and development. Third, it was clear that partnerships are vital for jointly addressing challenges, leveraging strengths, and maximizing impact. Whether in Geneva or in cooperation with private sector partners, NGOs, and foundations across the world, ITC is committed to working with partners to meet the needs of small businesses.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.10-->
                <p>
                    <t>As is the practice, the CTD took note of the report of the 57th Session of the Joint Advisory Group, and agreed to forward it to the General Council for adoption.</t>
                </p>
                <!--OPENING, PARAGRAPH 22.11-->
                <p>
                    <t>The General Council adopted the report of the Joint Advisory Group in document ITC/AG(LVII)/292 and took note of the CTD Chairperson's statement.</t>
                </p>
            </opening>
            <!--STATEMENT SECTION-->
            <statements>
